<FIRST>r a AM-PowerExplosion 1stLd-Writethru a0681 06-19 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Power Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0681,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Critically Burned; Cause Of Underground Blast Unknown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Two of...,' and last graf to UPDATE with third
victim upgraded to serious condition.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Power was restored to downtown and residential
areas early Sunday after a blackout caused by an explosion in a
transformer vault that also knocked out telephone operator service
to parts of three states.
   Three utility workers were critically burned.
   About 13,000 volts of electricity were running through the
underground equipment when a flash fire sparked the explosion,
forcing the evacuation of neighboring US West Communications and
AT&amp;T buildings, officials said.
   ``You can imagine that's pretty powerful,'' Assistant Fire Chief
Bill McDonnell said of the voltage.
   Two of the victims who were in the vault at the time of the
blast, a man and a woman, `breathed in fire'' and were in ``very
critical'' condition Sunday at St. Joseph Hospital in Omaha, nursing
supervisor Becke Majors said. The third worker, a man, was at
another hospital in serious condition.
   Ruth Howard, a US West employee who was standing near the alley
where the explosion occurred, said two of the workers ran out of the
alley engulfed in flames.
   ``I've never seen anything like it before in my life,'' she said.
``Their clothes were burned completely off and they were screaming
for help.''
   Kari Eckert, a private security guard, who was one of the first
people on the scene. She said the injured woman yelled: ``Help me!
Help me! I'm on fire!''
   ``I turned around and I almost got sick,'' Ms. Eckert said. ``I
was scared to death.''
   Mark Gautier Jr., a spokesman for the Omaha Public Power
District, said Sunday the explosion Saturday night knocked out power
to the entire downtown area and about 350 square blocks of two
residential neighborhoods.
   Power was restored to all areas by 4:15 a.m., he said. He said
the number of customers who lost power was not known.
   ``We may be able to ascertain a cause but sometimes it will take
several weeks. Sometimes you never find out,'' he said.
   ``The problem is so much of the evidence burns up. We may be able
to get some information from the workers. We just don't know,'' he
said.
   Fire Chief Robert Warsocki said his department had completed its
investigation and that any other information would have to come from
the utility. ``It was just an accidental electrical fire,'' he said
Sunday.
   Jim Brader, a spokesman for US West Communications, a subsidiary
of US West, said the three workers were replacing a 3,000-amp
switching unit for the telephone company.
   Gautier said power had to be turned off in parts of the US West
Building, and the workers were turning the power back on when a
flash started the fire and blast.
   The evacuation of the two communication buildings meant there
were no operator-assisted calls for about three hours for AT&amp;T
customers in all of Nebraska, half of South Dakota and the western
third of Iowa, a company spokesman said.
   Omaha World-Herald editors worked by flashlight to piece together
late Sunday editions and some metropolitan deliveries were delayed
for hours.
   Paul Nieman, 46, of LaPlatte, and Carla Fitzpatrick, 32, of
Omaha, suffered inhalation burns in addition to third-degree burns
over 70 percent to 85 percent of their bodies, said Majors, the
nursing supervisor.
   Frank Dwornicki of Omaha was taken to the burn unit at St.
Elizabeth Hospital in Lincoln, where he was in serious condition
Sunday afternoon with burns over 25 percent of his body, a nurse
said.
</TEXT>
