<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-19 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to corn, a 32-year-old
secretary is cob.
   Anita Hack of Temple was a double winner at the 15th annual
Holland Corn Festival, capturing the corn-eating contest and the
corn seed spitting event.
   She munched all the kernels off a cob in less than a minute with
a different approach than most of about 30 other competitors:
Instead of stripping off rows, she ate round and round until she
finished.
   ``I've been practicing all week. I thought the quickest way was
to eat all around the ear, but I didn't expect to win,'' she said.
   Winning the spitting contest with a distance of 16 feet, 2
inches, was an even bigger surprise.
   ``I really don't know how I won this one,'' she said. ``I never
spit.''
   But even though she didn't expectorate to win, and did anyway, it
was a close contest. Jane Montgomery, 50, had earlier sent a seed 16
feet, 1 inch after soaking it in beer.
   Competition also was held in corn cob tossing and relay racing
with ears of corn squeezed between racers' knees. The festival on
Saturday drew several thousand to the town of about 860 people, 20
miles south of Temple.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOULTRIE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Okmulgee, Okla., has thrown down the
wooden spoon, Moultrie is picking it up.
   At issue: Which community can bake the biggest pecan pie.
   ``I think that's just a challenge that we can't quit,'' Moultrie
Mayor Bill McIntosh said Sunday night after hearing Okmulgee
boosters had baked a 40-foot pie, breaking Moultrie's 1988 record of
30 feet in diameter.
   Georgians have been battling with bakers in Okmulgee for three
years. Saturday's pie was 4 inches thick.
   Fred Burks, co-chairman of the sixth-annual Okmulgee Pecan
Festival, said the committee members planning this year's event
didn't want to beat the Georgia record by just a few inches:
   ``They said, `Let's take a quantum leap and see if we can't take
charge of this thing and eliminate them from the competition.'''
   ``Never,'' said McIntosh. ``I think we will respond at the
appropriate time with a larger pie.'' He said the pie would be baked
at the Sun Belt Expo, a giant farm show held in October.
   The ingredients of the Oklahoma pie _ mixed in two new,
steam-cleaned cement trucks _ cost about $20,000, although most were
donated. Burks said.
   The pie included 77,770 cups of flour, 6,666 cups of shortening,
13,290 teaspoons of salt, 3,333 cups of water, 1,357{ cups of
margarine, 64,280 eggs and 3,000 pounds of pecans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHALMETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the bottom fell out of recreational
boat sales, the Cajun food craze helped one boat builder stay afloat.
   Besides his full-sized line of boats, Ron Chapman sells hundreds
of miniature pirogues, skiffs and sailboats which will never see a
bayou or sail on a lake. Instead, they decorate seafood buffets and
salad bars in hotels and restaurants in 31 states and the District
of Columbia.
   ``I consider myself lucky. ... It's like a functional Pet Rock,''
said Chapman, who runs Ron Chapman Shipwright Inc. in Chalmette, a
New Orleans suburb.
   Last year, sales totaled nearly $40,000. The boats, which range
from 2 to 4 feet, go for $20 to $125 each and account for about
one-quarter of his business. He expects to double sales this year on
the miniature boats.
   Hotels like the fiberglass boats because they're easy to clean
and make a stylish food display, he said.
   ``They're pretty neat,'' said John Gregory, banquet manager for
the Albuquerque Marriott in New Mexico. ``They're great for
decorations, and they hold a lot of seafood.''
   A birthday present for a friend's daughter started Chapman's
buffet business. His friend thought the little boat would work well
in a seafood display and offered to take one to Tim Paoletti, then
marketing manager of the New Orleans Hilton. Paoletti ordered 18.
Soon other hotels followed suit.
</TEXT>
