<FIRST>u a AM-HighwayDeaths 2ndLd-Writethru a0756 06-19 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Deaths, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0756,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>8 Killed In Head-On Collision On Alligator Alley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 1 graf to UPDATE with police saying pickup
tried to pass car; SUBS 8th graf pvs, `Ellen Burgess ...' to CORRECT her
first name to Amy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people burned to death in a head-on
collision involving a pickup truck and two cars Sunday afternoon on
a remote Everglades roadway known as Alligator Alley.
   The accident on the two-lane stretch of state Route 84 occurred
at 4:40 p.m. about 44 miles east of Naples, said Florida Highway
Patrol Sgt. Craig Perkins in Fort Myers.
   A car carrying seven people collided head-on with a pickup truck
containing one person on the two-lane road, said patrol duty officer
Doug Dailey. Troopers said the pickup was attempting to pass when it
collided with the car.
   Another car coming from behind and trying to avoid the accident
immediately sideswiped the wreckage, Perkins said, adding that the
two people in that car were not injured.
   The patrol earlier reported that nine people were killed because
officers mistakenly identified a large fish in the burning wreckage
as a victim, Dailey said.
   The 100-mile, east-west highway through the Everglades, which
links Fort Lauderdale on Florida's eastern coast and Naples on the
west coast, was immediately closed following the accident, Perkins
said. The road is also part of Interstate 75.
   Patrol Lt. Malcolm Rhodes said dental records will be needed to
positively identify the eight victims. The results are not expected
until at least Monday.
   Amy Burgess, who was in the car that sideswiped the wreckage,
said there was chaos following the accident.
   ``People were yelling, `Move the car, it's going to explode,' and
I just tried not to look,'' Ms. Burgess said, adding that the memory
of the crash on Alligator Alley will remain with her forever.
   ``This was my first time on it,'' she said. ``I'll never get on
it again.''
</TEXT>
