<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CapitolSecret Bjt   06-19 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capitol Secret, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Won't Give Own Workers Same Rights as
Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capitol Hill has a little secret, one that has
caused some to dub Congress ``the last plantation.''
   When Congress passes laws affecting the rights, working
conditions, health and safety of hundreds of millions of American
workers, it routinely exempts itself and the thousands of people who
work for it.
   Most American employees are ensured that their basic rights will
be protected by law, that standard occupational health and safety
regulations will be observed, that they can expect to earn at least
a minimum wage, that they cannot be discriminated against because of
race, sex or age.
   But the word ``most'' does not apply to workers in the marble
halls and utilitarian kitchens and basements of Congress.
   ``It is a little known fact,'' says Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio,
``that both the Senate and the House have exempted themselves from
provisions of federal law passed by Congress in these areas.''
   ``A double standard is established when Congress passes
legislation for the rest of the country and then exempts itself,''
Glenn said.
   Glenn commented last week as he and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
introduced legislation intended to give most congressional workers
the same employment protection enjoyed by other Americans.
   He quoted the late Sen. Sam Ervin, D-N.C., as saying the
congressional practice of avoiding the laws it passes for others
looks like a case ``where the doctor is prescribing medicine for his
patients that he himself will not take.''
   ``I agree with that statement,'' Glenn said. ``I believe this
medicine is good for both the patient and the doctor.''
   Glenn's medicine is designed to get around two obstacles.
   One is the traditional reluctance of Congress to put its
activities and practices under the jurisdiction of the executive
branch.
   It would be a violation of the doctrine of separation of powers
to permit Congress to be judged by an equal branch of government,
many House and Senate members contend.
   The other is the preference of many members of Congress to hire
staff members from their own states and, most of the time, from
their own political parties.
   The Glenn-McCain bill addresses both sticking points, perhaps
making the medicine a little easier to swallow.
   In the first place, it places the mechanism for policing
enforcement of the laws inside the legislative branch itself by
creating a Congressional Employees Relations Office to do the job.
   Secondly, it makes a concession.
   If a senator from Wisconsin, for example, wants to hire only
Wisconsin natives to serve on his staff, he could do so under the
terms of the bill.
   And if a member of Congress wanted a purely partisan staff, he or
she would have that right.
   ``However, it should be made very clear that those persons who
prepare and serve our food, who maintain these picturesque grounds
around the Capitol, who repair our office furniture and who work
generally in a non-legislative capacity, should have the same kind
of protection that their counterparts in the executive branch and
private sector have,'' Glenn said. ``It is only fair.''
   And fair, Glenn said, is one thing the present situation is not.
   While Congress has a policy of recruiting minorities and women.
he said, blacks number no more than 50 in the ranks of 2,500 top
professional staffers.
   ``Women have done only slightly better,'' he said. ``Less than 20
percent of the top jobs in the Senate are held by females while 80
percent of the lowest-paying jobs are reserved for female
employees.''
   Specifically, the bill would mandate the provisions of such laws
as the Civil Rights Act of 1966, the Fair Labor Standards Act of
1938, mandating a minimum wage; the Age Discrimination in Employment
Act of 1976, the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970 and the
Rehabilitation Act of 1973.
   McCain said Congress has enough problems at the moment without
exempting itself from laws that eliminate bias and discrimination.
   Continuing the double standard, he said, ``can only further erode
the confidence of the American people in their government.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence L. Knutson covers Congress for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
