<FIRST>r i PM-China-Journalist     06-19 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Journalist,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Journalist Says Government Will Last Only Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-China, Bjt ^By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's best-known journalist, Liu Binyan,
predicts the current Chinese government will last no more than two
years because of public anger over the country's serious economic
problems.
   Liu, who was expelled from the ruling Communist Party in 1987 for
reporting on government corruption, says he will not go back to
China soon because he probably is on the hard-line government's
wanted list.
   ``I did not consider myself a dissident, but the situation made
me become one. I did not consider myself to be in exile, but it
seems like I have to be in exile,'' he told a news conference Sunday.
   Liu arrived in Hong Kong from the United States on Saturday at
the invitation of the Hong Kong Journalists' Association.
   He said the government will fall ``because of the economic crisis
and the political impact it has already caused.''
   He said people in cities are angered by mounting inflation and
farmers are upset at low grain prices. This anger will mushroom as
news of the June 3-4 massacre in Beijing spreads throughout the
country, he said.
   ``The leaders might not live that long because they are thinking
of dealing with the people all day,'' he said.
   ``The present government has much less credibility than Mao, but
the pressure from the people it is facing is ten times stronger than
what Mao (Tse-tung) had,'' he said late Chinese ruler and the
1966-76 Cultural Revolution that Mao inspired.
   ``I don't believe there will not be any changes in China's
leadership in the next two years,'' he said.
   Despite the bloody crackdown, he said, the student-led
pro-democracy movement succeeded ``because it was the first time in
40 years that students represented the people and showed their
discontent with the government to the whole world.
   ``Among the hundreds of thousands of students, the first and
second generation of political leaders are growing and they are
maturing quickly.
   ``Chinese are not the same as in they were in 1949. They are more
politically mature and will not be fooled,'' he said.
   Liu, 64, wrote for the official Communist Party newspaper
People's Daily before he was expelled for attacking the party and
Marxism.
   He went to the United States in March 1988 and taught at the
University of California at Los Angeles, then went to Harvard
University on a Nieman fellowship.
   He was one of three prominent intellectuals ousted in a party
campaign against supporters of Western ideas. The others are writer
Wang Ruowang and astrophysicist Fang Lizhi.
   Fang and his wife, Li Shuxian, have taken refuge in the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing. Wang is believed to be in China, but his
whereabouts are unknown.
   Liu said authorities probably would kill Fang or student leaders
if they caught them:
   ``They are not kind. They are cruel, hyprocritical and would use
any means to achieve their aims.''
</TEXT>
