<FIRST>r a PM-DogFound     06-19 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dog Found,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valuable Show Dog Recaptured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT PROSPECT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Korsair, a valuable European show dog
missing for a week, had only to hear a few words of French to
realize he was back among friends.
   ``As soon as I started speaking to him in French, he came right
up to me and buried his head in my side,'' said Gerald A. Rousseau,
a dog trainer who took command of the 3-year-old Belgian Malinois
after he was captured by police.
   The dog, valued as high as $50,000, slipped from his cage while
he and his French owner were changing flights at O'Hare
International Airport on June 12.
   Korsair was spotted Sunday morning in the back yard of a Mount
Prospect home, a few miles from the airport.
   Police officer Jim Lange won Korsair over with a few dog biscuits
and was able to slip a leash over the animal's head.
   An examination by a vet showed the dog had gashes on his front
legs and inside an ear, but otherwise was alert and in good shape,
said Rousseau.
   ``As soon as I saw him, I ran him through a series of commands in
French: heel, sit, bound, jump, stay,'' he said. ``That and a tattoo
proved he was Korsair.''
   Bob Rankin, 61, didn't know the dog understood only French when
he spotted the animal lying in his backyard, and it started snarling
at him.
   ``I don't know a French dog from a Polish dog, especially when he
bares his teeth at me,'' Rankin, a roofer, said Sunday night.
   The breed is a kind of sheepdog resembling a German shepherd.
   Korsair is highly trained and was being transported across the
nation by owner Daniel Paul to be shown at seminars on training dogs.
   Rousseau said the dog probably gashed his leg by climbing or
jumping over the barb wire-topped fence that rings the 7,000-acre
airport.
   While the dog appeared a little thin, Rousseau said he's sure the
animal has been finding some food.
   ``I'm certain he either caught rabbits or other wild game or
found food going through garbage,'' he said.
   Rousseau said Korsair's owner was elated when he heard the dog
had been found.
   ``He started crying,'' Rousseau said.
   Paul said the dog is worth $20,000 because of his pedigree, stud
value and championship record, but Louis Auslander, chairman of the
American Kennel Club, said it could be worth $50,000.
   United Airlines, which was transporting the owner and dog when
Korsair disappeared, had offered a reward of several hundred dollars
for his return.
   The police department is not allowed to accept the money, so it
will be donated toward the medical expenses of 9-year-old Joshua
Mayo of Mount Prospect, who was struck by a car and critically
injured Friday.
</TEXT>
