<FIRST>r a PM-Poll-Method     06-19 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-Method,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-Education, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is based
on telephone interviews May 5-13 with 1,084 adults in the
continental United States.
   Phone numbers were selected randomly and interviews were
conducted with the adult who had the most recent birthday, a random
phenomenon.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the sample.
The poll has a 3 percentage point margin of error, meaning that 19
of 20 times its findings should be within 3 points of the result if
every adult American were asked the same questions.
   The error margin is larger for subgroups; it is 6 points, for
example, for respondents who have children in public schools.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions in this
poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. How would you rate the quality of the public schools in your
community _ excellent, good, only fair or poor? Excellent: 15
percent. Good: 38. Fair: 28. Poor: 15. Don't know or no answer: 4.
   2a. Do you think spending on public schools should increase,
decrease or remain the same? Increase: 66. Decrease: 3. Same: 28.
DK-NA: 3.
   b. (If ``increase'') Would you be willing to pay higher taxes for
that? Yes: 91. No: 8. DK-NA: 1.
   c. (If ``increase'') Where should most of the additional money
come from _ the federal, state or local government? Federal: 32.
State: 41. Local: 17. DK-NA: 11.
   3. Do you think standardized test scores reflect how well
students are learning in school, or not? Yes: 37. No: 54. DK-NA: 9.
   4. How would you rate the job the public schools in your
community do at teaching students basic facts and skills _
excellent, good, only fair or poor? Excellent: 12. Good: 40. Fair:
31. Poor: 13. DK-NA: 5.
   5. How would you rate the job the public schools in your
community do at teaching students how to think and reason _
excellent, good, only fair or poor? Excellent: 7. Good: 32. Fair:
35. Poor: 19. DK-NA: 7.
   6. Do you think that raising teacher salaries would attract
better qualified people to the teaching profession? Yes: 66. No: 29.
DK-NA: 5.
   7. Do you do think the public schools in your community make
subjects interesting for students, or not? Yes: 51. No: 29. DK-NA:
21.
   8. Some people say parents should be able to choose which public
school their child attends. Others say that would take resources
away from schools that need the most improvement. Do you think
parents should be able to choose which public school their child
attends, or not? Yes: 58. No: 37. DK-NA: 5.
   9. Would you support or oppose year-round public school, with
vacations scattered throughout the year in place of the long summer
vacation? Support: 44. Oppose: 49. DK-NA: 7.
   10. Do you think President Bush will be able to improve public
education in this country, or not? Yes: 46. No: 37. DK-NA: 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-LookingOut     06-19 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Looking Out,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Disdain For World Opinion Reflects Tradition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt ^AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's disdainful response to world criticism
over its bloody crackdown on student protesters is in keeping with a
2,000-year tradition of insularity and a sense of righteousness.
   China long assumed a vast gulf between itself, called the
``central country'' in Chinese, and other countries, which were
considered uncivilized. Economic self-sufficiency enabled it to
maintain this view as the limits of communication preserved
ignorance about the rest of the world.
   But China no longer is self-sufficient and foreign opinion cannot
be blocked out.
   Foreign investment and technology are key to its economic
development plans and China has come to rely on some imports. Even
while denouncing the United States for sheltering a leading
dissident in its Beijing embassy, China imported extra tons of U.S.
wheat to make up for its own poor harvest.
   Since senior leader Deng Xiaoping began economic reforms a decade
ago, nearly 10,000 foreign companies have set up joint ventures in
China with a total investment of $12 billion. Many manufacture goods
for export, generating hard currency China needs for its
modernization.
   Chinese leaders have said repeatedly since the army attacked
unarmed protesters in Bejing on June 3-4, killing hundreds, that
they want and expect foreign countries to continue trade and
investment. But they also have reiterated they will not accept
foreign criticism of the bloody crackdown.
   ``We hope that all countries that wish to keep and develop
friendly relations with China will take a long-term view and avoid
doing anything to hurt the feelings of the Chinese people,'' Premier
Li Peng told top party officials in a recent speech.
   Government spokesman Yuan Mu was blunter, telling a news
conference, ``We are not spineless people. We are not afraid ...
(of) condemnation or sanction.''
   It has gotten both. The United States cut off military sales and
contacts; France and the Netherlands froze relations. Japan, China's
largest single-country source of aid, put off new development
assistance loans. Canada and France temporarily withdrew their
ambassadors.
   Several countries canceled planned high-level official exchanges.
   It is not the first time foreign governments have criticized
Deng's policies. The U.S. Congress has passed repeated resolutions
criticizing China for opening fire on pro-independence protesters in
Tibet over the past two years.
   However, it is the first time condemnation of China has been so
nearly universal. Even Hungary's Communist government expressed
outrage and the Soviet parliament urged ``wisdom, reason and a
weighted approach.''
   It also is the first time that criticism has been backed by
action.
   A speech Deng gave in 1987 indicates he may not have expected
that. He said that after the last large-scale arrests of
pro-democracy activists in 1979, China suffered no ``discredit.''
``On the contrary, the prestige of the country is steadily
growing,'' he said.
   China also has emerged unscathed from controversies over its
foreign policy, such as its arms sales to Iran and support in
Cambodia of the Khmer Rouge, whose forces killed hundreds of
thousands of countrymen while in power from 1975-78.
   The decision of the top government spokesman, Yuan Mu, to give a
rare interview to the U.S. television network NBC last week may have
been an effort to counter the avalanche of foreign condemnation.
   In it, he reiterated the government's position that the army
fired on the crowds June 3-4 only after provocation. He condemned
foreign news reports as distortions and suggested that even foreign
film of the killing was fabricated.
   China could have avoided much of the bad press abroad if it had
expelled all foreign reporters ahead of time. But thousands of
foreign businessmen and diplomats who also could bear witness would
have had to be expelled as well.
   What's more, such a move would have been an admission that China
had something to hide. Chinese officials apparently believe that if
they reiterate the official explanation often enough and wait long
enough, foreign businessmen and diplomats will trickle back.
   They may be right. A survey of 116 American business executives
before the crackdown found 55 percent believed China would become a
more attractive market. After the shooting, 67 executives were asked
again. Fifty-three percent still agreed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Kathy Wilhelm has been reporting for The
Associated Press from Beijing since 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
