<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   06-19 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0403,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Lower, Dollar Returns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing dollar, Nikkei</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell
Monday, while the dollar rebounded against the Japanese yen after a
sharp drop on Friday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 41.99
points, or 0.13 percent, and closed at 33,013.18. It added 142.08
points Friday, when it closed at 33,055.17.
   The dollar opened at 144.20 yen, down 0.85 yen from Friday's
145.05-yen close, but then climbed during the day's trading and
closed at 145.50 yen, up 0.45 yen from Friday's finish.
   On Friday, the dollar fell 6.25 yen.
   Goshin Mizuno, a dealer with Nomura Securities, said that
although the Nikkei index fell Monday, there was a considerable
volume of transactions.
   ``The most important factor is that financial authorities
including the Bank of Japan have coordinated their intervention
activities,'' he said.
   As a result, speculation has decreased and sharp fluctuations
have become fewer, Mizuno said. He added that transactions centered
around capital investment issues such as Yamatake-Honeywell.
   He also said there would not be many announcements of important
economic indexes this week. Such announcements often affect the
direction of trading.
   On the foreign exchange market, the Bank of Japan intervened but
without much effect, dealers said.
   ``Many dealers were buying dollars today to cut losses,'' said
one dealer from Daiwa Bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
