<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PSACrashTrial     06-19 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSA Crash Trial,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors to Decide Liability in 1987 Air Tragedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 1771
took off from Los Angeles, its passengers included a no-nonsense
supervisor and a hot-tempered former underling who sneaked a gun
aboard.
   Over central California, the bad feelings between David Burke and
his former USAir boss, Ray Thomson, ended in an airborne shooting
that moved from the passenger compartment to the cockpit.
   With its slain crew slumped over the controls midway to their San
Francisco destination Dec. 7, 1987, the four-engine BAe-146 smashed
into a hillside north of San Luis Obispo. All 43 aboard were killed.
   Eighteen months later, attorneys are dissecting the final minutes
of the life of Burke, 35. The USAir employee was fired three weeks
earlier by Thomson, 48, who had denied Burke reinstatement during a
meeting shortly before they boarded the flight.
   The negligence lawsuit is midway through trial in Superior Court.
It was filed by the relatives of eight passengers and two crew
members against the Los Angeles Department of Airports; Ogden Allied
Security Co., PSA and USAir, which bought PSA.
   Jurors will have to fix percentages of responsibility, if any,
for the defendants as well as any damages, which attorneys agree
could run into millions of dollars. No set dollar amount was
requested.
   At issue is whether the defendants could have reasonably guessed
Burke's actions and stopped him. The defendants have said that was
impossible, and have countersued the estate of Burke as the man
solely responsible for the crash.
   The plaintiffs say Burke should never have been allowed past the
security checkpoint at Los Angeles International Airport.
   Norman Bottom, a security expert for the plaintiffs, said USAir
should have notified security personnel and airport police about
Burke's dismissal three weeks before, distributed a photo of him and
change locks to which he had keys.
   Defendants say nothing came to their attention to warrant such
action.
   Defense attorneys also have tried to point out that Burke's
considerable temper was largely limited to arguments with his
girlfriend, away from the job.
   Bottom said he has concluded that Burke managed to sneak the gun
past the security checkpoint by concealing it under clothing and
using his identification badge to avoid metal detectors.
   Defense attorneys have alluded to an FBI report, not yet admitted
into evidence, that suggests Burke used the airport's back stairways
and halls to reach the public storage lockers in the secure area of
the terminal.
   The FBI report said the use of employee-only hallways and stairs,
combined with wearing a USAir employee badge to avoid suspicion,
would have been the ``least obtrusive'' way to bypass security.
   Testimony has established that Burke, a ticket agent fired Nov.
15 for allegedly stealing petty cash, handed in two USAir employee
identification badges, but kept a third.
   Burke's whereabouts between 1:30 p.m. and 2 p.m. haven't been
established. At 2 p.m., he showed up at Thomson's office, outside
the security area, for an appointment to appeal his dismissal. He
met with Thomson for 25 minutes, seeking reinstatement, after
waiting to see him for nearly 20 minutes.
   Thomson's secretary, Ruth Wagner, testified that Burke seemed
happy after the meeting. ``I said, `Have a nice day,' and he said `I
will,''' she recalled.
   But she said Thomson emerged from the meeting red-faced and
stressed, heading for his flight home to San Francisco.
   Conflicting with that time frame was testimony from Mutual of
Omaha agent Marissa Chavez, who said she sold Burke two insurance
policies for $100,000 and $195,000 at about 2:30 p.m.
   Chavez also said she recalled smelling alcohol on Burke's breath.
   Burke originally bought his ticket for an earlier flight to San
Francisco, but changed it to the 3:30 p.m. flight after meeting with
Thomson. That assured he would be on the flight with Thomson, who
often commuted between Los Angeles and his San Francisco area home.
   Although the trial could result in sizable settlements for the
plaintiffs, its outcome would have little effect on the nation's
airport security, which already has been increased because of the
crash.
   The Federal Aviation Administration issued directives tightening
requirements for airline employees and management of ID badge
distribution.
</TEXT>
