<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HelicopterCrash     06-19 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helicopter Crash,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard Helicopter Crash Kills Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YARMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aviation officials were trying to
determine why a helicopter carrying four National Guardsmen and two
Army Reservists crashed in a thick fog, killing all aboard.
   The Army and Delaware Army National Guard on Sunday investigated
the wreckage of the UH-1 Bell helicopter, said Lt. Col. Stuart
Tauber, spokesman for the Massachusetts National Guard at Camp
Edwards.
   The helicopter crew was halfway through a two-week training
exercise at Camp Edwards. The exercise included 495 members of the
Delaware Guard. The camp is part of the 24,000-acre Massachusetts
Military Reservation on Cape Cod and straddles the towns of
Sandwich, Mashpee, Falmouth and Bourne.
   The crash's cause was unknown and no preliminary report was
planned, Tauber said.
   Maj. Mari K. Eder of the Virginia Army Reserve on Sunday
identified two of the victims as Master Sgt. Robert E. Lucey Jr. of
Emporia, Va., and Spec. Samuel K. May of Richmond, Va. Both were
members of the 80th Maneuver Training Command based in Richmond.
   Three other victims served in the Delaware Army National Guard
unit from New Castle _ 1st Lt. David Joseph Hendry, 26, Chief
Warrant Officer Hugh Bryan Pearce, 35, both of Wilmington, and Staff
Sgt. Benjamin Robert Greenplate, 40, of Newark, Del.
   Also killed was a member of the Connecticut National Guard, Sgt.
Ward Arthur Cornell, 43, of Mansfield, Conn.
   The helicopter, valued at $1 million, crashed in dense fog
shortly after midnight Friday as it returned to the camp from T.F.
Greene Airport in Warwick, R.I.
   The crew had flown to the commercial airport earlier in the
evening to pick up a passenger due to fly in on a commercial flight
from Philadelphia. He never arrived and the chopper crew decided to
return to Camp Edwards.
   The aircraft crashed in Yarmouth, about 30 miles from the camp,
in a wooded area near a housing development.
   No civilian casualties were reported and no homes were damaged,
but residents said the crash caused their walls to shake.
   Yarmouth is a resort community about 85 miles from Boston. Its
winter population of 20,000 multiplies fourfold during the summer
tourist season.
</TEXT>
