<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scattered Thunderstorms in Southeast; Heat Bakes Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered in parts of Kentucky,
Tennessee, Alabama and Mississippi early today, and heat continued
to bake the Southwest.
   Rain also was widely scattered across Georgia and along the coast
of the Carolinas.
   Farther west, the temperature cooled only to 90s early today in
the desert Southwest, following a day of 100-plus readings. The
nation's high temperature Sunday was 117 degrees at Bullhead City,
Ariz., and Laughlin, Nev.
   At least two record highs for the date were set in Arizona:
Phoenix, at 115 degrees, and Tucson 113. Winslow, Ariz., at 103
degrees, tied its record high.
   Also Sunday, thunderstorms spawned one tornado in Maine and
another in Florida. Other intense thunderstorms in Florida Sunday
night produced high winds that damaged a mobile home's roof in
Venice, toppled a restaurant sign onto a car in Clearwater and blew
away parts of porches from homes in North Fort Myers.
   The Maine tornado, which occurred near Farmington, toppled trees,
damaged homes and threw a camper 40 feet into the air. The trailer
landed in a tree. Showers and thunderstorms were also widely
scattered across eastern portions of the Dakotas and west-central
Minnesota.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from the Ohio Valley and the lower Mississippi Valley across the
Appalachians to the central Gulf Coast states and the southern
Atlantic Coast; numerous showers and thunderstorms over the upper
Ohio Valley, West Virginia, and parts of Alabama, Georgia and the
Florida Panhandle; scattered showers and thunderstorms later in the
day from the upper Mississippi Valley across northern Plains to the
central Rockies; showers and a few thunderstorms scattered across
the Pacific Northwest into western Montana.
   Predicted highs: 60s across much of the Pacific Northwest; 70s
and 80s from the Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic Coast, along the
northern and central California coast, and from southwest Oregon to
north-central Montana; 90s in most of the Plains, from the central
Intermountain region through the central Rockies and over Florida;
and 100 to 110 from the desert Southwest across the southern Rockies
to southwest Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming to 99 at Blythe,
Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 partly cloudy; Boston 66 hazy; Buffalo 60 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 72 cloudy; Cincinnati 69 cloudy; Cleveland 62
partly cloudy; Detroit 66 foggy; Miami 77 partly cloudy; New York 66
fair; Philadelphia 64 fair; Pittsburgh 62 cloudy; Portland, Maine 56
fair; Washington 70 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 51 fair; Chicago 69 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
74 fair; Denver 63 fair; Des Moines 62 fair; Indianapolis 70 partly
cloudy; Kansas City 63 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 63 fair; Nashville
68 cloudy; New Orleans 78 fair; St. Louis 66 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 80 cloudy; Anchorage 61 fair; Las Vegas 89
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 64 partly cloudy; Phoenix 91 fair; Salt
Lake City 76 fair; San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 54 windy;
Seattle 54 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 foggy; Toronto 57 fair.
