<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Palestinians 2ndLd-Writethru a0461 06-19 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Palestinians, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0461,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Repatriation Planned for Egypt's Forgotten Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To CORRECT date resettlement supposed to begin, SUB grafs
8-9, `But residents ... is completed.' Picks up 10th, `Under a ...' ^By
WILLIAM C. MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAFAH, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tear gas fumes and the sounds of rifle fire
and explosions from Israeli efforts to quell the Palestinian
uprising in the Gaza Strip are common in Camp Canada.
   The camp is home to about 5,000 Palestinians forgotten in the
Middle East conflict and barred from their Gaza homeland by the 1979
Israeli-Egypt peace pact. Camp Canada is in Egyptian Rafah _ 135
feet away across two chain-link border fences and rolls of barbed
wire.
   Under the peace treaty, the frontier between Egypt and the
Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip drawn in 1982 bisected Rafah, stranding
about 560 Palestinian families in Egypt's only refugee camp.
   The dividing line also divided many families, but they were told
they would be reunited in Gaza within a month.
   For years the main contact has been across the ``shouting
fence,'' where relatives exchange family news.
   The main topic is the Palestinian uprising in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip that began in December 1987. More than 500
Palestinians and at least 22 Israelis have been killed in the
violence; in a clash Friday in occupied Rafah, three Arab men were
killed by Israeli army gunfire.
   Neither Israeli nor Egyptian officials will talk about the
seven-year embarrassment of Camp Canada, named for a Canadian
peacekeeping unit once quartered there. Alon Liel, spokesman for the
Israeli Foreign Ministry, said recently ``the issue is under various
discussions.''
   But residents say an 11-week process is scheduled to begin this
week that, if completed, will return to Gaza 67 people in 20 Camp
Canada families.
   They say tentative plans called for the first two families to
cross into no-man's land next Monday, meet with relatives and then
move into occupied Gaza. They would be followed by two families on
successive Mondays until the program is completed.
   Under a 1986 agreement, Egypt is to give each family $8,000 for
resettlement. Residents said and sources in Cairo confirmed that
Israel backed out of its commitment to give each returning family
land and housing materials valued at $9,000.
   Evidence of the frustration of Camp Canada's residents is that
the 20 families agreed to Israel's conditions. They will live with
relatives.
   Much of the resentment is toward the United States, which camp
residents perceive as siding with Israel.
   ``The key to our problem is America,'' said one camp official.
``The Americans are the only ones who can solve it.... Why don't
they do something to make it happen?''
   ``We've been through this 20 million times before,'' said a
teacher at the Camp Canada school. ``We've been told we were going,
then no. I will believe we're going when we're there.''
   As Palestinians, camp residents are foreigners and barred from
government jobs in Egypt's government-dominated economy. Many have
not worked for seven years. Others are underemployed or work on day
jobs outside the camp.
   Carpenter Gamil Mohammed, who runs a kiosk decorated with a
Palestinian flag, spoke of smelling the tear gas used against fellow
Palestinians across the barbed wire in Gaza and of hearing the
``boom'' of houses being dynamited.
   Israeli forces frequently destroy homes of Palestinians suspected
of being involved in terrorism.
   Mohammed introduced his three small sons wearing T-shirts with
slogans supporting the Palestine Liberation Organization and
uprising. The shirts are becoming part of the uniform of Camp
Canada's young people.
   Mohammed said of his son, ``They hope to go to another place.
Home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MiGDogfight     06-19 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MiG Dogfight,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Museum Locked In Dogfight With Government To Keep Its Enemy Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is locked in a dogfight with
the Chino Planes of Fame Museum over two Soviet fighter jets on
display.
   The State Department, Customs Service and Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms insist the museum imported the MiGs from Poland
illegally.
   Officials also say the museum's 1947 Antonov, a Soviet-designed
biplane still in flying condition, must go because it was bought in
Hungary.
   U.S. law bars importation of military equipment from a list of
countries that includes Poland and Hungary, ``based our belief we
should not contribute to their armament industries by purchasing
implements of war,'' said Jack Killorin, an ATF official in
Washington.
   Museum officials said they had no idea their purchases were
illegal.
   ``They sat on the docks down there for two weeks and customs
passed them right through,'' said Karen Hinton, museum vice
president.
   ``We made a mistake,'' said Customs spokeswoman Maryanne Noonan.
``Those planes never should have reached the museum, but over a
million containers a year come in through the seaport. We physically
inspect only a small percentage.''
   The 31-year-old museum, which showcases 90 vintage aircraft,
figured it scored a coup last summer when it purchased the MIGs
through a broker. The MiG-15 and MiG-17, similar to those flown
against U.S. forces in Korea, were restored by volunteers and
quickly became a popular attraction.
   ``We had Japanese, British, German and American aircraft in our
collection,'' Ms. Hinton said, ``and to add something from the
Russian theater really rounded things out.''
   A June 8 deadline for surrender of the aircraft has long passed.
Customs officials said they could have seized the planes and added
they won't wait much longer.
   Determined to keep the planes, the museum has launched a Save the
MiGs petition drive, gathering nearly 7,000 signatures. U.S. Reps.
Jerry Lewis and Robert K. Dornan, both Republicans, have pledged
their support.
   ``We're at our wits' end,'' Ms. Hinton said. ``We just wanted to
preserve and display these aircraft so a grandfather can bring in
his grandson and say, `Look, this is what I flew in Korea, and
here's what the enemy used.'
   ``It's just terrible to think they may cut these planes up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
