<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-PalmeTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0489 06-19 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palme's Widow Says Defendant is Her Husband's Killer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Mrs. Palme identifying suspect,
RESTORES her first name. Pickup 6th graf, `I have....' TRIMS thereafter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENE MURDOCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Prime Minister Olof Palme
stood in court today 30 feet from the defendant in her husband's
murder trial and identified him as the killer.
   Lisbeth Palme, who was leaving a movie with her husband when he
was shot to death the night of Feb. 28, 1986, said she clearly saw
the defendant's face just after the shooting on a Stockholm street.
   Upon cross-examination, however, she said she had not seen the
man's hands, and thus could not say whether he had a gun.
   Mrs. Palme's testimony was crucial to the case against Christer
Pettersson, a 42-year-old Swede with a long criminal record. He was
arrested in December.
   Pettersson, wearing a blue-and-white sport coat, was brought into
the heavily-guarded courtroom at the end of Mrs. Palme's testimony.
   Prosecutor Anders Helin asked her if she could point out the man
she saw seconds after the shooting. Without hesitation, she pointed
at Pettersson, who was sitting across the room.
   ``I'm certain,'' she told Helin.
   ``If Olof Palme in his heaven could have heard this, he wouldn't
have liked it,'' said Pettersson, interrupting over the objections
of Judge Carl-Anton Spak. ``If you believe in what you're saying,
it's OK. But otherwise, it's not,'' said Pettersson in a calm, clear
voice.
   Guards took him from the room, and Mrs. Palme made no reply.
   ``You haven't got a camera in your head,'' said defense attorney
Arne Liljeros. ``How can you be certain? Isn't it wishful thinking
on your part to close the matter?''
   ``It will never be closed for me,'' Mrs. Palme said.
   Saying she still suffered from ``a deep wound,'' she had refused
earlier today to testify with Pettersson present in the Stockholm
district courtroom.
   However, the court ruled after she began testifying with
Pettersson outside the courtroom that he should be brought in for an
identification.
   Before he entered, Mrs. Palme had referred to the defendant only
as ``No. 8,'' a reference to Pettersson's place in a videotaped
police lineup where Mrs. Palme had earlier picked him out.
   ``I have been trained in my job to observe things. Not to
analyze, but to observe,'' she told the court. Mrs. Palme is a
psychologist by training.
   ``My state of shock made me even more observant,'' she said.
``That's why I remember his face so clearly.''
   Mrs. Palme, who wore a gray suit and a green silk scarf, appeared
on edge during much of her testimony. Accompanied by her son
Joachim, she entered the courtroom walking sideways to avoid facing
the 60 reporters present.
   When court officials tried to show her a map of the scene where
the killing took place, she refused to turn in profile to the
audience to look at it. The map was moved so she could keep her back
to the gallery.
   Mrs. Palme had requested that no official tape recording be made
of the session, that it not be broadcast, and that reporters be
excluded. The court agreed to the first two conditions but allowed
the press inside.
   Mrs. Palme was slightly injured in the attack, which occurred at
night on a main Stockholm street. The gunman escaped down a dark
alley.
   Pettersson, a 42-year-old Swede with a history of drug and
alcohol abuse and a previous conviction for manslaughter, has denied
killing Palme.
   He had demanded a courtroom identification by Mrs. Palme.
   ``You must realize the responsibility,'' Liljeros told her. ``My
client says he hasn't committed this crime, and if you're the least
bit uncertain about the identity, then your responsiblityy is to say
so.''
   ``I am absolutely certain,'' Mrs. Palme replied.
   Since Palme's death, Mrs. Palme has shied away from any public
discussion of the killing. She lashed out at the news media on the
stand today, saying they had ``tried their best to destroy the
investigation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
