<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     06-19 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlers Demonstrate to Protest Fatal Stabbing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARIEL, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish settlers today
demonstrated to protest the stabbing death of a U.S.-born settler in
the occupied West Bank and to demand harsher government measures to
quell the Palestinian uprising.
   The military command today extended the closure of West Bank
schools for another month despite pleas from the United States and
human rights groups to reopen them.
   The 1,194 schools, including 145 kindergardens, have been closed
for all but a few weeks since Feb. 3, 1988, keeping 320,000 pupils
out of classrooms.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, six Palestinians were wounded in
clashes in the Bureij and Nusseirat refugee camps, including a
65-year-old man struck in the knee, Arab doctors said.
   Outside the Ariel settlement, the home of the fatal stabbing
victim, 150 demonstrators waved Israeli flags and some shouted,
``How many Jews have to die before something is done?''
   In Jerusalem, 80 Jewish settlers blocked the entrance to the
Knesset to protest the slaying of Friedrich Steven Rosenfeld.
Fistfights occurred when Knesset guards ordered the protesters to
disperse, army radio said.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir blamed Palestinians for the slaying
of Rosenfeld, 48, and said punishment would be swift and harsh.
   ``This murder is another link in the chain of blood of violent
actions carried out against us in the country by murderers and
rioters who believe that by these actions they will put an end to
our settlement and our existence,'' he said. ``Israel's security
forces will uproot this violence with an iron fist.''
   Chaim Malka, a West Bank police commander, said police suspected
Palestinians in the slaying. But he said all possibilities would be
investigated. The army said it was checking the reports.
   Rosenfeld's body was found on Sunday by Palestinian shepherds on
a hilltop between the Arab villages of Salfit and Burkin, said Avivi
Shalom, head of security in Ariel. Shalom said Rosenfeld had been
stabbed in the back.
   Rosenfeld had been missing since Friday night.
   Shalom said Rosenfeld apparently walked to the barren area from
Ariel.
   ``It seems as though the assailants surprised him and hit him on
the head,'' Shalom told The Associated Press. Rosenfeld's empty
pistol holster, map, binoculars and two spent cartridges were found
near the body, Shalom said.
   The Maariv daily said it appeared the settler had been taken by
surprise and fired in the direction of the assailants.
   Ariel officials said Rosenfeld lived in Washington, D.C. before
emigrating to Israel in 1968. He served in the Israeli army and was
wounded in March 1968 when his jeep hit a land mine while on patrol,
the officials said.
   Rosenfeld lived in Tel Aviv and worked as an editor of technical
manuals before moving to Ariel 18 months ago.
   Ariel spokesman Dina Shalit said Rosenfeld was a nature lover and
frequent organizer of hikes for residents in the settlement of
5,000. She said he may have been mapping a hiking route when he was
killed.
   ``He was just walking on the hill looking at nature. He wasn't
disturbing anyone. He died just because he was Jewish,'' Shalom said.
   Before Rosenfeld's death, 22 Israelis had been killed during the
18-month Palestinian uprising against Israel's occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. At least 524 Palestinians have also died.
   The army placed curfews on Burkin and Salfit and launched a
manhunt, deploying helicopters, scouts and search dogs.
   Outside the Ariel settlement, its mayor, Ron Nachman, told
protesters that the government created an atmosphere against
settlers. About 70,000 Jews live among the 1.7 million Palestinians
in the occupied territories.
   ``All of them are responsible, and especially the Knesset members
who speak out and put a stigma on us as a group, in order to enable
attacks on us. I see them as directly responsible for this
assassination,'' Nachman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
