<FIRST>r a PM-People-Downey     06-19 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Downey,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talk Show Host Hopes To Buy Controversial But Ailing Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unabashedly abrasive Morton Downey Jr. says
he is trying to buy his show and turn it into a weekly program to
avoid cancellation.
   ``My position is and always has been that five times a week is
overexposure for this type of persona,'' he said in today's New York
Times.
   The talk show has been nationally syndicated for a year and is on
71 stations, but not enough stations are renewing the
five-day-a-week version.
   Last week, Downey told the Daily News that the show has been sold
for the coming year in 22 markets but needs at least 60 to get
renewed.
   ``No one will take a chance on it any more,'' he said.
   Downey, one of a spate of talk show hosts whose emotional style
and sensational topics have earned their shows the nickname
``tabloid TV,'' told the Times he hoped to purchase the show with
partners and revise it.
   The Times said executives for Quantum Media Inc., which produces
the show, believe Downey's off-camera behavior has hurt the program.
   In April, for example, he claimed he was attacked in San
Francisco by neo-Nazis, but police there said they were unable to
substantiate the claim.
   ``Downey'' doesn't get as good ratings as ``The Oprah Winfrey
Show,'' ``Donahue'' and ``Geraldo.''
   All three are carried by about three times the number of stations
that carry Downey and regularly rank in the top 10 nationally
syndicated programs. Downey's show ranked No. 84 this past season,
according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   The program premiered at a New Jersey station nearly two years
ago.
</TEXT>
