<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-US 1stLd-Writethru a0501 06-19 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas: American Photographer Arrested in Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to ADD background on O'Brien and previous arrests
of foreigners in Afghanistan. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American free-lance photographer
traveling with Moslem guerrillas has been captured and is being held
by the Afghan government, Afghan guerrilla sources said today.
   They identified him as Tony O'Brien, 42, a photographer from
Santa Fe, N.M., on assignment for Time-Life Inc. He had been
covering the Afghan war based in the Pakistani frontier city of
Peshawar.
   The Afghan government did not immediately confirm the arrest.
U.S. Embassy officials in Pakistan refused to comment on the report.
   Guerrilla sources in Pakistan who demanded anonymity said O'Brien
was captured Wednesday in western Kabul, the capital. The sources
said he was being held in the capital and was reported to be in good
condition.
   At least three Western correspondents and two foreign aid workers
have been captured while traveling with the guerrillas during the
11-year war in Afghanistan. All of them were later released unharmed.
   The report on O`Brien is the first known case of an American's
capture.
   The U.S.- and Pakistani-supported guerrillas have been fighting
the Soviet-supported Afghan government for a decade.
   Soviet combat troops ended nine years of involvement in the war
Feb. 15 but continue to arm the Kabul government.
   O'Brien had made several previous forays into Afghanistan with
the guerrillas. His photographs have appeared in several major U.S.
publications, including The New York Times and Time magazine.
</TEXT>
