<HEAD>Teresa Tirelli D'Amico, Actress, Dead at 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teresa Tirelli D'Amico, an actress, opera
singer and radio personality who had roles in the ``Godfather''
movies and on many TV shows, has died at age 81.
   Mrs. D'Amico died Friday of brain cancer, said her son, Nicola M.
D'Amico.
   Among her TV roles was one opposite Lucille Ball in a
grape-stomping scene from a 1956 episode of ``I Love Lucy.''
   She also appeared in ``The Godfather'' and ``The Godfather, Part
2'' as well as such series as ``Columbo,'' ``Baretta'' and ``General
Hospital.''
   For 17 years she was host of ``The Original Italian Hour,'' which
aired Sunday mornings on KTYM-AM. The show had its last live
broadcast in December.
   Born in Polla, Italy, Mrs. D'Amico moved to the United States in
the early 1920s and performed operas on stage and radio in New York
City.
   Survivors include four children and six grandchildren.
   A funeral Mass will be held Tuesday.
