<FIRST>r a PM-Bishops'Conference 1stLd-Writethru a0467 06-19 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bishops' Conference, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roman Catholic Bishops Seek to Keep Minority Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, ``I think ...' to CORRECT to `Convention'
sted `Conference.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic Church,
which has lost tens of thousands of minority members to conservative
Protestant groups in recent years, is fighting back.
   The president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops
charged during the prelates' annual spring meeting that some of the
nation's largest Protestant denominations, including the Southern
Baptist Convention, have worked to convert Hispanics.
   Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis said fundamentalist churches
have ``a very clearly fashioned plan to entice people away from the
church in a very deceptive way.''
   ``I think that's an unfair statement,'' the Rev. Daniel Vestal,
pastor at Dunwoody Baptist Church in Atlanta and the unsuccessful
candidate last week for president of the 14.5 million-member
Southern Baptist Convention, said Sunday.
   ``I can't speak for all Protestant groups but I know the Southern
Baptists offer a message of hope and redemption. That attracts
people regardless of race.''
   At their meeting at Seton Hall University, the bishops voted to
emphasize evangelism when they celebrate in 1992 the 500th
anniversary of the introduction of Catholicism to the Americas and
to start work toward giving blacks a greater role in the church.
   Leaders of the nation's largest religious denomination also
approved a resolution calling for normalization of U.S. relations
with Vietnam and a plan for resolving disputes between bishops and
theologians.
   After two days of business meetings, the bishops held a day of
recollection Sunday, gathering for Mass. The bishops were to meet in
executive session today to conclude the meeting.
   May said some fundamentalist churches go so far as to feature
Catholic art and music in their churches to draw Hispanics in, and
then start teaching anti-Catholic doctrines to keep the converts
from returning to Catholicism.
   A wave of immigrants from Spanish-speaking countries and a
relatively high birth rate have made Hispanics the fastest-growing
group of U.S. Catholics, making up an estimated third of the 53
million-member denomination. Due in part to immigration from the
West Indies and Haiti, the number of black Catholics has risen from
900,000 to 2 million during the past 20 years.
   But the Rev. Allan Figueroa Deck, associate professor of Hispanic
studies at the Jesuit School of Theology at Berkeley University,
said one national study has shown at least 60,000 Hispanics leave
the church each year, and 1 million have left during the past 15
years.
   Church leaders said a large part of the losses, particularly in
the Hispanic community, are the result of proselytizing by
conservative Protestant churches.
   Catholic officials, though, also admit the church has driven some
minority members away through apathy and insensitivity.
   Deck said that while Hispanic Catholics struggle to be noticed in
the Catholic Church, evangelical sects are providing numerous
Spanish-speaking ministers and small churches ``especially
appropriate for immigrants who need all the personal communal
support they can get.''
   A pastoral statement proposed by the nation's 13 black prelates
calls for giving blacks more positions of responsibility throughout
the church and integrating African-American cultural symbols into
liturgies and churches.
   Sister Thea Bowman of Canton, Miss., a black nun, said in an
emotional appeal to the bishops that black Catholics sometimes feel
``like a motherless child'' in the church.
   The black and Hispanic bishops met Thursday to begin what they
said would be an ongoing dialogue. One of their first actions was to
send a telegram to President Bush expressing regret over his recent
veto of minimum-wage legislation.
   But the average Catholic may find it hard to draw others into
church.
   Archbishop Edward A. McCarthy of Miami said a recent Gallup Poll
showed only 2 percent of Catholics are involved in evangelization.
   On Vietnam, the conference approved a statement from the bishops'
Committee on International Policy asking the nation to begin to heal
the wounds caused by the war, and start the process of resuming
diplomatic ties with its former enemy.
</TEXT>
