<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Uzbekistan     06-19 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Uzbekistan,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Create 200,000 Jobs In Troubled Uzbekistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today announced they would create
200,000 jobs, clean up polluting factories and grow more food in a
region where economic and ecological problems were blamed for
rioting that killed about 100 people.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda also reported that the last
of more than 16,000 Meskhi Turks had been evacuated from the Fergana
Valley in the republic of Uzbekistan.
   Rioting that broke out in the Central Asian republic pitted
ethnic Uzbeks against the Meskhi minority, which was forcibly
resettled in the valley by Soviet dictator Josef Stalin in 1944.
   Authorities and residents have given differing accounts of the
reasons for the sudden outbreak of arson and killings on June 3 that
required 9,000 Interior Ministry soldiers and evacuation of the
Meskhi Turks to contain.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov said about 100 people were killed in
the violence. Hundreds of homes were destroyed by arsonists.
   Officials have blamed groups of marauders for the violence and
said an investigation was under way to find out who they are.
   Uzbeks and Meskhi Turks said they have been frustrated by a lack
of work, agricultural and industrial pollution, and quotas requiring
them to grow cotton rather than food products.
   The leader of an Uzbek grass-roots movement called the
government's move to improve the economy and environment a good step
but added that it was late and the he doubted the government could
create those jobs by 1990, as it promised.
   ``This is very positive, but they had to think about it much
earlier,'' Abdurakhim Pulatov said in a telephone interview from
Tashkent, the Uzbekistan capital. Pulatov, 44, who heads the Berlik
movement, said he did not believe 200,000 jobs could be created so
quickly.
   He blamed the violence on ``the worsening of the socioeconomic
situation of the native population _ unemployment, poverty and
social injustice.''
   Some reports in the Uzbekistan media have accused the Berlik
movement of being behind the violence. Pulatov denied that.
   Pravda, quoting a Uzbekistan government report, said food
processing plants and sewing factories would be opened to provide
200,000 new jobs by the end of 1990.
   The newspaper said steps would be taken to end the concentration
on cotton production. Some activists charge that the chemical
fertilizers and pesticides used in cotton production is poisoning
the land and leading to malnutrition in a republic once known for
its fruits and vegetables.
   ``To heal the ecological situation, technology at polluting
enterprises will be modernized and reliable pollution control
devices will be created,'' Pravda said without elaboration.
   The newspaper said there was ``no information about new arson,
pogroms or murders'' in reports by military commanders.
   Pravda said an Ilyushin-76 transport plane took the final group
of Meskhi Turks to central Russia on Sunday, ending the evacuation
of 16,282 people.
   The Turks were evacuated from their homes in Fergana and other
cities in the valley to a camp where shelter, food and water were in
short supply.
   Official newspapers on June 12 reported that rioters had tried to
attack the camp and were driven off by soldiers.
   The Meskhi Turks are natives of an area of the Soviet republic of
Georgia, which borders Turkey. For more than 30 years they have been
demanding that they be allowed to return. Ryzhkov promised the
government will study the demand.
</TEXT>
