<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Mandel     06-19 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Mandel,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Former Maryland Governor's Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
former Maryland Gov. Marvin Mandel's 1977 mail-fraud conviction,
thrown out five years after he completed a prison term.
   The court, without comment, rejected a Bush administration appeal
aimed at using Mandel's case to set guidelines on when someone may
challenge a fraud conviction for which the sentence already was
served.
   Mandel and five others were convicted of charges stemming from an
alleged scheme in which the governor supported legislation favorable
to Marlboro Race Track in return for gifts worth more than $380,000.
   The race track's five owners _ W. Dale Hess, Harry W. Rodgers
III, William A. Rodgers, Irvin Kovens and Ernest N. Cory _ also were
convicted in 1977. Their convictions also were thrown out after they
had completed their respective sentences.
   The government appeal acted on today also sought to reinstate
those five convictions.
   At Mandel's trial, prosecutors charged that Mandel used his
influence as governor to help the track. Jurors were told by the
judge that Mandel could be convicted of mail fraud if they found
that Mandel had deprived citizens of their ``intangible rights'' to
his honest services.
   Mandel was convicted and sentenced to four years in prison. He
had served 19 months when the remainder was commuted. He also was
disbarred because of the conviction.
   Hess served 18 months of a three-year sentence and paid $40,000
in fines. Harry Rodgers and Kovens each served three years in prison
and paid $40,000 in fines; William Rodgers served his year-and-a-day
sentence and paid $40,000 in fines. Cory's 18-month sentence was
suspended.
   The Supreme Court in 1987, deciding an unrelated case, ruled that
federal mail fraud law does not protect against schemes to defraud
people of their intangible rights such as the right to honest
government.
   Mandel and the five others then sought to have their convictions
thrown out and the paid fines returned. A federal judge granted that
relief, and the ruling was upheld last Dec. 7 by the a 2-1 vote of
the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The appeals court said it could not determine whether the
convictions had been based on the ``intangible rights'' aspect or
some other aspect not affected by the Supreme Court's 1987 ruling.
   ``In a case in which the jury considers alternate theories of
liability, we must reverse the convictions if either theory is an
improper basis for punishment,'' the 4th Circuit court said.
   That ruling conflicts with one issued by another federal appeals
court. The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals recently upheld the
conviction of former Chicago Councilman Thomas E. Keane for
conspiring illegally to buy and sell tax-delinquent properties.
   The 7th Circuit court ruled that Keane was not entitled to have
his conviction overturned even though jurors had been instructed
about the since-invalidated ``intangible rights'' aspect of federal
mail fraud law because other evidence could support a conviction.
   The Supreme Court on May 22 refused to hear Keane's appeal.
   In the Mandel case acted on today, government lawyers said the
justices should clear up ``the considerable confusion'' in the lower
courts as to when such convictions should be overturned.
   The case is U.S. vs. Mandel, 88-1759.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0068 </DOCNO>
