<SECOND>PM-Osborne-API,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas News Executive to Head Press Institute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burl Osborne, president and editor of The
Dallas Morning News, has been named chairman of the board of
directors of the American Press Institute, it was announced today.
   Osborne, 52, has been a member of the board since 1985. As
chairman, he succeeds William O. Taylor, chairman and publisher of
the Boston Globe, who has held the post for six years.
   Taylor and Charles C. Glover, editor-in-chief of Cox Newspapers,
are leaving the board on July 1. Taylor has been a member since 1974
and Glover since 1978.
   Replacing them as members of the board are William R. Burleigh,
senior vice president for newspapers and publishing, Scripps Howard;
and Joseph D. Cantrell, president and publisher of the Daily Press
and The Times Herald, Newport News, Va.
   The institute is a non-profit organization dedicated to
continuing education and career development for newspaper men and
women. It was founded in 1946 by Canadian and American newspapers.
</TEXT>
