<FIRST>r i PM-ArmsTalks 1stLd-Writethru   06-19 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0483,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiations Reopen On Cutting Long-Range Nuclear Arsenals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with opening session ending, comments
by U.S. and Soviet negotiators. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Burt, a...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-Soviet talks on cutting long-range nuclear
forces reopened today after a seven-month recess with few prospects
of an early breakthrough in the 4-year-old negotiations.
   While Washington reportedly planned to press Moscow over the
inspection provisions of a future treaty, both sides have indicated
no change in their stands on other major oustanding issues.
   The two new chief delegates, Richard Burt and Yuri Nazarkin,
launched the 11th round of Geneva talks since March 1985 with a
meeting at the U.S. mission.
   After the 80-minute session, Burt told reporters he had outlined
``President Bush's overall approach to arms control, emphasizing the
president's commitment to reducing the risk of nuclear war.''
   ``I hope we will make some progress,'' he said.
   Nazarkin said, ``I'm satisfied. It was a good start.'' He said
Moscow may put forth new proposals ``in due time.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Burt, a military expert and former U.S. ambassador to West
Germany, replaced veteran arms negotiator Max Kampelman.
   Nazarkin replaced Alexei Obukhov and had been chief Soviet envoy
at the 40-nation Conference on Disarmament, which has been seeking
for years to complete a treaty banning chemical weapons worldwide.
   Along with the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks, negotiators will
resume talks on space and defense issues. Detailed negotiations are
due to begin Wednesday with a full meeting of both delegations at
the Soviet mission.
   The session, expected to last six weeks, comes against the
backdrop of recent progress and superpower initiatives in talks on
conventional disarmament in Europe.
   Resumption of the talks was delayed by the Bush administration's
review of national security policy during the Reagan presidency.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Friday ``there will
be a considerable degree of continuity'' in the U.S. position, while
not ruling out some adjustments.
   One new element is a U.S. proposal for on-site trial inspections
to monitor some cuts of long-range ballistic missiles already
written into a draft treaty, Washington officials said. A Pentagon
official said Bush wants to take advantage of the new Soviet
openness.
   It would be the first time in superpower arms control that
verification begins during talks rather than once a treaty is
completed.
   But neither side has hinted at movement on disputes over the
Pentagon's space-based ``Star Wars'' missile defense, sea-launched
cruise missiles and mobile land-based missiles.
   The Soviets say the U.S. missile shield, or Strategic Defense
Initiative, violates the 1972 superpower Anti-Ballistic Missile
treaty.
   And disputes have developed over Moscow's demand for including
sea-based cruise missiles under the treaty and Washington's call for
a ban on mobile missiles.
   Admiral William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, has predicted ``protracted and agonizing'' negotiations.
   Much of a draft treaty to cut each side's long-range, or
strategic, nuclear forces by 30 to 50 percent has been agreed in
previous rounds.
   START is intended to cover nuclear weapons with which the
superpowers can strike each other, including those considered most
dangerous _ sea- and land-based ballistic missiles and heavy bombers.
   Delegates are to begin the new session by reviewing agreements
already contained in the 400-page draft text.
   Among the agreements in earlier rounds are lowered ceilings of
6,000 nuclear warheads and 1,600 delivery vehicles _ missiles and
bombers _ for each side. Outlines of a system for monitoring
compliance were also set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
