<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     06-19 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Criticizes Proposal to Outlaw Criticism of Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Gregorio Rosa Chavez
criticized a right-wing proposal to virtually outlaw criticism of
the government.
   The so-called ``law in defense of democracy'' contradicts its
name, the Roman Catholic prelate said during his Sunday homily.
   It prescribes a ``medicine worse than the disease'' and could
take El Salvador back to the ``dark times'' of the early 1980s when
death squads killed thousands of people considered government
critics, he said.
   ARENA, the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, drafted a
law providing fines and imprisonment for those who oppose the
government or its policies, including journalists and protest
marchers.
   President Alfredo Cristiani's new administration was to introduce
the bill in the National Assembly on Thursday, but it failed to
without explaining why.
   Rosa Chavez said the proposal takes a partisan view of the
violence in El Salvador because it treats terrorism as something
committed only by leftists.
   Human rights and international organizations say rightist death
squads and the military are responsible for the majority of civilian
deaths in nine years of civil war. About 70,000 people, mainly
civilians, have died in the war between the U.S.-backed government
and left-wing guerrillas.
   Rosa Chavez said terrorism also includes ``terrorism of the
state.''
   He said Vice President Dan Quayle, in a meeting with Roman
Catholic Church leaders during his recent visit to El Salvador,
``spoke of liberty, of democracy but not of justice... He didn't
touch on the problem of injustice.''
</TEXT>
