<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Lombardo     06-19 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lombardo,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Conspiring to Bribe Nevada Senator Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear the
appeal of one of five men convicted in a scheme to bribe then-U.S.
Sen. Howard Cannon of Nevada.
   The justices, without comment, let stand Joseph Lombardo's
bribery conspiracy and wire fraud conviction, for which he was
sentenced to 15 years in prison and fined.
   Lombardo's co-defendants were Roy L. Williams, president of the
Central Conference of Teamsters; Allen Dorfman, a former special
consultant to the Teamsters Central States Pension Fund; Thomas F.
O'Malley, a pension fund trustee; and Andrew G. Massa, a former
pension fund trustee.
   A federal appeals court said that Lombardo's vocation at the time
as ``something of a mystery.''
   The 1982 convictions arose out of what prosecutors said was a
scheme to sell a piece of Las Vegas property to Cannon. The senator
was not charged in the case.
   The property, known as Wonderworld and owned by the union pension
fund, was located across the street from Cannon's residence.
   In late 1978, Cannon and a group of neighbors expressed interest
in purchasing the property to prevent it from being commercially
developed.
   At the time, legislation designed to deregulate the trucking
industry was pending in Congress. The Teamsters opposed the
deregulation, and considered Cannon, then chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, to be in a position to affect the legislation's
future.
   Prosecutors said Williams and Dorfman, seeking to influence
Cannon's actions on the legislation, promised to take steps so the
senator's group could purchase the Las Vegas property from the
pension fund for $1.4 million even if higher bids were received.
   The property, however, eventually was sold to an unrelated
corporation for $1.6 million.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Lombardo argued that
his conviction was based solely on a scheme to deprive the pension
fund of the ``intangible right'' to honest service from its trustees.
   The Supreme Court in 1987 ruled that mail-fraud convictions could
not be based on a theory that citizens' rights to honest government
had been violated.
   ``The underlying indictment is fatally defective under (the 1987
ruling),'' Lombardo's appeal contended.
   But Justice Department lawyers urged the high court to reject the
appeal. They said the jury, in convicting Lombardo, had to find that
he tried to defraud the union pension fund of real property _ the
value of the Las Vegas property.
   Although the scheme to sell the property to Cannon for $1.4
million ``deprived the pension fund of the loyal services of its
trustees, it also clearly contemplated depriving the pension fund of
the highest price for the Wonderworld property,'' government lawyers
said.
   A federal trial judge and the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
previously rejected Lombardo's arguments.
   The case is Lombardo vs. U.S., 88-1616.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
