<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Catawbas 1stLd-Writethru a0518 06-19 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Catawbas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Kill Lawsuit in Which Catawba Indians Claim Land</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; Subs graf 6, In the appeal, to insert dropped word ``General''
in title.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to kill a
nine-year-old lawsuit in which the Catawba Indian Tribe claims
ownership of 225 square miles of South Carolina.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that last January revived the tribe's efforts to recover
some, but not all, of the claimed land.
   The land in dispute encompasses the city of Rock Hill, the town
of Fort Mill and several smaller communities.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling barred the tribe
from recovering either possession of land or damages from people who
have held the land for 10 years between July 1, 1962, and Oct. 20,
1980.
   But the appeals court's 4-2 ruling said the Catawbas may proceed
with their effort to recover possession and damages from all others.
   In the appeal acted on today, South Carolina Attorney General T.
Travis Medlock and lawyers for numerous landowners argued that the
tribe had waited too long before filing its 1980 lawsuit.
   ``If review is not granted now, it may be a decade or more before
this court has the opportunity to completely resolve the potentially
dispositive (deadline) issue,'' the appeal said.
   ``Years of continuing litigation will result in a cloud on land
titles requiring innocent citizens to defend their homes and
businesses in protracted litigation at great expense.'' it added.
   The tribe's lawsuit contends that an 1840 treaty under which the
tribe transferred the disputed land to South Carolina was invalid
because the federal government did not participate in or approve the
treaty.
   When Congress passed a law that revoked the tribe's constitution
effective July 1, 1962, the tribe's land claim became subject to
South Carolina's statute of limitations.
   Medlock and the other lawyers seeking to have the tribe's suit
dismissed contend that the tribe had no longer than 10 years from
that 1962 date to sue.
   The appeal also argued that the Catawbas' claim to ``Indian
title'' is ``merely a right of occupancy'' and not ``legal title
within the meaning of a South Carolina statute.''
   Lawyers for the tribe urged the justices to reject the appeal,
saying the 10-year deadline cited by the state's lawyers does not
apply in this case.
   They also said the appeals court correctly ruled that, under
federal law, Indian title is legal title.
   The case is South Carolina vs. Catawba Indian Tribe of South
Carolina, 88-1752.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
