<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Election     06-19 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Election,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran's Presidential Vote Moved Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's presidential election will be held
July 28, three weeks earlier than planned, and the new president
will begin his four-year term before the official October starting
date, Iran said today.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said the Interior Ministry announcement gave no reason for advancing
the election from the scheduled date of Aug. 18.
   But the move appeared to be aimed at speeding up the transition
of power following the June 3 death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
and consolidating control under his successor, President Ali
Khamanei, and his likely successor as head of state, Parliament
Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani.
   The Interior Ministry said that a national referendum on major
constitutional amendments, which had also been scheduled for Aug.
18, will be held July 28 as well.
   Earlier today, Tehran's radical Jomhuri Islami daily quoted a
source as saying the election was moved forward because Khamenei had
been elected as Iran's supreme leader by the 83-member Assembly of
Experts, which was formed in 1979 to ensure a smooth succession when
Khomeini died.
   ``Because of the selection of Ayatollah Khamenei as leader ...
and the need for the election of a president as soon as possible,
the officials in charge of the election proposed the date be brought
forward,'' the paper said.
   The newspaper also said the new president would begin his term
``a little sooner than the scheduled date.''
   Khamenei's second term term officially ends Oct. 5. He is
forbidden under the 1979 revolutionary constitution from running for
a third term.
   Rafsanjani, Khamanei's political ally in the so-called pragmatist
camp in Tehran's fractious hierarchy, is the only declared candidate
so far. The Iranian media have in recent days taken his election as
a foregone conclusion.
   Rafsanjani, who is also commander-in-chief of Iran's armed
forces, has been endorsed by Khamenei and several influential
factions.
   Analysts have predicted that Khamenei, 49, and Rafsanjani, 55,
face challenges from radical rivals such as Interior Minister Ali
Akbar Mohtashemi and possibly Khomeini's son, Ahmad, 43, who has
shown increased political ambitions in recent months.
   The pragmatists are said to favor ending Iran's isolation and
opening up the economy to wider free enterprise, mainly to secure
foreign aid for Iran's reconstruction program following a cease-fire
in the 8-year war with Iraq.
   The anti-Western radicals seek to tighten state control of the
economy and to retain the goal of spreading Khomeini's
fundamentalist revolution to the Moslem world as a bulwark of Iran's
foreign policy.
   The constitutional amendments, which are being formulated by a
committee appointed by Khomeini, are widely expected to enhance the
presidency with more executive powers, at the expense of the prime
ministry, to eliminate competing power structures which have snarled
the decision-making process for years.
   That would give Khamenei and Rafsanjani formidable power in the
post-Khomeini era with which to fend off any challenge from the
radicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
