<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Pollute     06-19 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Pollute,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Leaves $1 Million Fine Intact Against Maryland Paper Mill Operator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a fine of
nearly $1 million against a Maryland paper mill operator that failed
to comply with a federal clean water law's reporting requirements.
   The court, without comment, rejected a challenge to a key
provision of the act authorizing citizens and environmental groups
to sue alleged polluters.
   Simkins Industries Inc. runs a paper mill in Catonsville, Md., on
the banks of the Patapsco River.
   The Sierra Club sued the company for failing to monitor and file
quarterly reports on discharges into the river from Aug. 1, 1981, to
March 31, 1984.
   Under the federal Clean Water Act, the company's permit to
operate the mill required it to monitor discharges and report them.
   Simkins faced fines of up to $10,000 a day, or a total of $9.77
million. A federal judge assessed penalties of one-tenth that
amount, $977,000, payable to the U.S. Treasury.
   There was testimony that the company's plant supervisor did not
regard sampling of its discharges as a priority.
   The Sierra Club, based in California with members nationwide,
charged that Simkins had discharged copper into the Patapso at
10,000 times the safe levels for fresh water, and that oil and
grease in the river from the mill were twice the allowable limit.
   The company said the Sierra Club did not have the legal authority
to sue it because the club suffered no direct injury, and also that
the suit should be dismissed because it was filed after Simkins
stopped violating the law's reporting requirements.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last May upheld the fine.
   The appeals court said the Sierra Club established that at least
one of its members who uses the Patapsco River for recreation was
injured by Simkins' violations.
   Fines for failure to monitor and report possible pollution ``can
be an important deterrence against future violations,'' the appeals
court added.
   The appeals court, citing a 1987 Supreme Court decision, said
such private citizen suits under the clean water law may not be
``based upon wholly past violations.''
   The appeals court added that Simkins was violating the law at the
time the suit was filed in late 1984. The company did not file a
complete quarterly report until January 1985, nearly three months
after the Sierra Club filed suit.
   ``It is true that Simkins' failure to sample occurred solely
before Sierra Club filed suit,'' the appeals court said. ``But
Simkins' monitoring obgligations were not designed to be a mere
academic exercise.''
   ``Unless a permit holder monitors as required, it will be
difficult if not impossible for state and federal officials...to
know whether or not the permit holder is discharging effluents in
excess of the permit's maximum levels.''
   The appeals court also noted that Simkins began monitoring its
discharges after it was alerted by the Sierra Club that it was about
to be sued.
   The case is Simkins vs. Sierra Club, 88-660.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UAWConvention     06-19 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAW Convention,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident UAW Group Loses Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most serious dissident movement in the
United Auto Workers in 40 years lost its first test of strength at
the union's constitutional convention.
   Amid sometimes raucous debate during Sunday's opening session,
more than 2,000 delegates rejected motions challenging elections
weeks ago in UAW locals in the Detroit area and the south-central
United States.
   Based on Sunday's voting, the dissidents had support from 10
percent to 20 percent of the delegates.
   Jerry Tucker, leader of the dissident movement called New
Directions, was philosophical about the setback. ``The decisions
that may be made here are not necessarily reflective of where the
rank-and-file may be,'' he said.
   Tucker's movement has charged that the UAW under President Owen
Bieber has become too cozy with management. New Directions is
pushing a resolution that would force the union to back locals
opposing labor-management cooperation.
   Later this week, Tucker said, New Directions will push for
unionwide, rank-and-file election of officers.
   Approval would scrap the representative form the UAW will use to
re-elect Bieber to a third three-year term as leader of the
1-million-member union. Bieber is unopposed.
   New Directions represents the most serious dissident movement in
the 54-year-old UAW since the factionalism of the union's first
decade. Walter Reuther solidified control of the union after taking
office in 1946.
   In his keynote address before the debate on delegate seating,
Bieber blasted the New Directions movement without mentioning the
group by name.
   ``To be frank,'' Bieber said, ``I think those who say that
workers don't want change in the workplace, who insist that the old
ways were always the best ways, are insulting the intelligence of
UAW members.''
   He defended his leadership, saying the union will keep management
at arm's length even while involving itself in joint programs with
automakers.
   ``So let me assure you, and let me warn any employers who may
have formed the wrong idea of where this union is heading,'' he
said. ``Where the power of persuasion fails, we will use the
persuasion of power without hesitation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
