<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Europarliament-Britain 1stLd-Writethru   06-19 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europarliament-Britain, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0504,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Camp Snubbed in Europarliament Balloting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with later returns. Pickup 11th,
`In a...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Europarliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
Party was trounced today by socialists in elections for the European
Parliament.
   The Labor Party, inflicting Mrs. Thatcher's first defeat in a
national ballot since she won power 10 years ago, seized Tory
districts across the country and won a solid majority of British
seats in the European Economic Community's assembly.
   ``The results were disappointing, but we shall renew our efforts
for next time,'' Mrs. Thatcher said in a letter to Conservative
Party Chairman Peter Brooke.
   With the economy in trouble, Labor's big 10.4 percent swing
against the government fueled charges that Mrs. Thatcher's
free-market revolution isn't working any more.
   ``We've not done well,'' Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson
acknowledged. ``This is a warning to the government.''
   Labor leader Neil Kinnock burst into song in Welsh as he arrived
at the party's London headquarters in the early hours. Results
pouring in showed socialists posting gains from Scotland to the
Tories' southern English heartlands.
   Labor won 45 of the 78 seats allocated to mainland Britain
compared with its previous total of 32. The Conservatives fell to 32
seats from 45. The Scottish National Party retained its one seat.
   Results were expected later today from the three seats in
British-run Northern Ireland where voting splits along Protestant
and Roman Catholic lines.
   The Tory share of the vote slumped to 34.15 percent, compared
with 42 percent at the 1987 general election when Mrs. Thatcher won
a third five-year term and 40.8 percent in the last European
elections in 1984.
   Labor had 40.23 percent, up from 30.8 percent in the 1987 British
election and up from 36.5 percent in the 1984 European elections.
   In a meteoric performance, Britain's tiny Green Party scooped up
15 percent of the vote, partly at the expense of the centrist Social
and Liberal Demoratic Party whose share collapsed to 6 percent.
   However, the British Greens will get no seats. Unlike in other
West European countries, only coming first in a district counts and
seats are not allocated according to vote share.
   Although only about one-third of eligible Britons voted, as is
traditional in European elections, government leaders acknowledged
that Kinnock had succeeded in turning the ballot into a referendum
on Mrs. Thatcher.
   ``We have got to get inflation under control. We have got to
stick together. We have got to make sure the electorate understands
the consequences of electing a Labor government,'' said Parkinson.
   For Labor, which has lost three general elections in a row, the
major boost was pushing its vote above the 40 percent it needs to
oust Mrs. Thatcher at the next general election. This must be held
by mid-1992.
   ``These are winning ways and there is more to come,'' Kinnock
told reporters.
   Fuelled by a credit boom and high wage settlements reminscent of
the pre-Thatcher era, Britain's 8.3 percent inflation rate is among
the highest in the EEC. Union militancy is also growing.
   Reluctant to raise taxes, the Thatcher government is trying with
no sign of success to curb inflation by increasing interest rates _
now at 14 percent and hitting home-owners and businessmen.
   The defeat also increased fears within the party that her
combative stance with other members of the EEC is losing votes as
the 1992 deadline for turning the community into a single market
approaches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
