<FIRST>r i PM-PuertoRico     06-19 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode at Bank of Boston, U.S. Army Recruiting Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pipe bombs exploded early today
outside a Bank of Boston branch and a nearby U.S. Army recruiting
office, police said. No injuries were reported, and damage was
slight.
   There have now been four bombings in Puerto Rico since Friday,
when a Senate panel opened hearings in San Juan on a proposed vote
on the Spanish-speaking island's future political relationship with
the United States.
   Los Macheteros, an extremist pro-independence group, claimed
responsibility for the explosions today in Bayamon, a town 15 miles
outside San Juan.
   In a typewritten letter delivered to The Associated Press bureau,
the group said it planted the bombs to protest, among other things,
the ``farcical plebiscite'' planned for 1991, and the imprisonment
of a Macheteros member in the $7 million robbery of a Wells Fargo
depot in Hartford, Conn., in 1983.
   The group said the campaign of violence would continue until the
United States ended its military, political and economic presence in
Puerto Rico.
   The two explosions today occurred within an hour of each other,
said police spokeswoman Maria del Pilar Bon. She said one bomb
slightly damaged the bank building's fascade and shattered windows
of a nearby bus terminal. The other blast shattered windows of the
recruiting office.
   On Sunday, a pipe bomb exploded at a Chase Manhattan Bank branch
in Caguas, in the north-central part of the island, causing an
estimated $4,000 damage but no injuries. On Friday, a pipe bomb went
off in a U.S. customs office in the southern city of Ponce, causing
no injuries and only minimal damage.
   No group claimed responsibility for the explosions Sunday and
Friday.
   The U.S. Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee is holding
hearings in San Juan on the proposed vote on whether Puerto Rico
should remain a U.S. commonwealth, become the 51st U.S. state or
seek independence.
   The Caribbean island of 3.2 million people, which Spain ceded to
the United States in 1898 following the Spanish-American War, has
been a U.S. commonwealth since 1952. Residents in 1967 voted to
remain a commonwealth.
   On Thursday, a federal court in Hartford sentenced a Puerto Rican
nationalist and Macheteros member, Juan Segarra Palmer, to 65 years
in prison and fined him $500,000 for his part in the Wells Fargo
attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
