<HEAD>Indiana Killer of Army Chaplain Wins Death Row Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of name to Streett sted Street in 3rd and
4th grafs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today set aside the death
sentence of convicted Indiana murderer Michael Daniels, killer of an
Army chaplain who lived in Indianapolis.
   The justices told the Indiana Supreme Court to restudy Daniels'
case in light of their June 12 decision in a South Carolina case
that juries in capital cases may not be told about a victim's
personal characteristics.
   Daniels' appeal did not challenge his conviction in the Jan. 16,
1978 slaying of Allan Streett.
   Prosecutors said Daniels was one of several men who staged a
series of armed robberies at Indianapolis homes that day. Streett
was shoveling snow with his son from the family home's driveway when
he was shot down.
   The case is Daniels vs. Indiana, 88-6729.
