<HEAD>Miners, Police Clash; 48 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BRU1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 miners protesting the
planned closure of Belgium's last two pits by 1993 clashed with
police Monday while trying to march to parliament and the royal
palace, and 48 people were injured.
   A security force of 2,500 used tear gas, water cannon and mounted
police to keep the miners away from the legislature, palace and
diplomatic missions in central Brussels.
   Thirty policemen were injured _ two seriously _ when they were
pelted with stones and hit by sticks and steel bars, a police
official said. At least 18 miners were hurt.
   The miners were allowed to march through Brussels' business
district, but changed course near parliament. They fought through a
barricade of 400 policemen but were later dispersed, the official
said.
   Last week, 28 police were injured in fighting in northeastern
Hasselt, near the pits.
   Authorities decided to close the pits and center on reconversion
industries in the mining region of northeastern Limburg. In 1986,
the management of the KS mines shut down four mines and cut the work
force from 18,300 to 6,800. KS lost $310 million that year.
