<SECOND>AM-BRF--Germany-Soviet,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Siemens to Deliver 300,000 Personal Computers to Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German electronics company
Siemens will deliver 300,000 personal computers to the Soviet Union
in a deal worth about $750 million, a company spokesman said Monday.
   The contract was signed in Moscow on Friday, one day after Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev concluded a four-day visit to West
Germany, said Siemens spokesman Eberhard Posner.
   Siemens signed the contract with the Soviet Ministry of Higher
and Secondary Education and a Soviet electronics concern, Orbita.
   The computers will be delivered in the next three years, Posner
said.
   The West German company also will train Soviets and transfer
enough of the technology and know-how for the Soviets to start
manufacturing some computer components, he said.
   The Munich newspaper Sueddeutsche Zeitung said the Soviets were
financing the purchase through sales of chemicals to the British
Afro-Arab trading group.
   The computers will be used in Soviet research institutes and will
serve as a basis for the Soviets to develop their own software and
large computers, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
