<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-LegalFees     06-19 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Legal Fees,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court OKs Payment of Legal Fees in Kansas City Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a victory for civil
rights lawyers and their clients, today upheld the award of more
than $4 million in legal fees to lawyers who won a Kansas City, Mo.,
school desegregation suit.
   The justices, voting 8-0, ruled that paralegals, law clerks and
recent law school graduates are entitled to compensation at the
market rate for their work.
   By a separate 5-3 vote, the court said states that lose such
cases may be forced to pay extra money to civil rights attorneys as
compensation for a delay in payment.
   State and city officials were held responsible for segregation in
the Kansas City school system and were ordered in 1985 to spend
$87.7 million to improve and integrate the schools.
   A federal judge then ordered the state to pay more than $1.7
million to Arthur A. Benson II of Kansas City, the lead attorney for
students who sued, and $2.3 million to the NAACP Legal Defense Fund
for its work.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the attorneys' fees
last year under a federal civil rights law that awards them to
lawyers who win such cases.
   Missouri officials argued the legal fees were inflated illegally
to compensate Benson and the others for waiting years to be paid.
   Justice William J. Brennan, in his opinion today, said the
additional compensation is not barred by a constitutional provision
that protects states against some lawsuits.
   He was joined in that part of his opinion by Justices Byron R.
White, Harry A. Blackmun, John Paul Stevens and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   Dissenting on that issue were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall did not take part in the ruling.
   The case is Missouri vs. Jenkins, 88-64.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
