<FIRST>r i AM-India-Bomb     06-19 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Bomb,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested for Fatal Railroad Station Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested three Sikh militants
and charged them with planting a bomb that killed 10 people at New
Delhi's main railroad station last week, a news agency reported
Monday.
   The three extremists were arrested June 17 in Amritsar in Punjab
state, the birthplace of Sikh separatist movement for an independent
homeland, according to the Press Trust of India, which did not
identify its sources. The blast occurred June 12.
   The three were identified as Nishan Singh, Gurdeep Singh and
Baldev Singh, and they belonged to the Bhindranwale Tiger Force of
Khalistan, a known militant group.
   The news agency quoted sources as saying that Nishan Singh put
the time bomb, hidden in a plastic bucket, near the ticket counter
at the entrance of New Delhi's main railroad station.
   The other two had helped make the device that blew up in a crowd
of 600 people, most of whom were vacationers waiting to board trains
or lined up to buy tickets, the news agency said.
   The blast, which also injured 50 people, was the first attack by
Sikh extremists in nearly a year.
   The militants told interrogators that they had planned to place
the bomb outside a Hindu temple in the busy market place at Chandni
Chowk in north Delhi, according to the news agency.
   But, ``deterred by the presence of a large number of people in
the crowded Chandni Chowk, they kept the bomb at the station and
left for Amritsar ... by train,'' the news agency said.
   Some New Delhi residents also were involved in the plot and
police were trying to identify them, the news agency reported.
   Police had earlier said that another militant group, the Babbar
Khalsa, was responsible for the blast that came a week after
militants observed the fifth anniversary of an army raid on the Sikh
Golden Temple in Amritsar.
   The raid, aimed at flushing out armed militants entrenched in the
shrine, left 1,200 people dead, including Jarnail Singh
Bhindranwale, founder of the Sikh separatist campaign.
   Sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for a homeland in
Punjab, claiming they are discriminated against socially and
culturally by the country's Hindu majority.
   Sikh separatists have been blamed for at least 850 killings in
Punjab this year.
</TEXT>
