<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Parliament     06-19 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Parliament,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Begins Hearings on Cabinet Appointees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet parliament began confirmation hearings
Monday for the Cabinet of Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov amid
indications that some of the appointees would face tough
questioning, Tass said.
   In contrast to the initial work of the Congress of People's
Deputies and the parliament, or Supreme Soviet, which captivated
audiences across the country for days, the hearings were not
televisied and were closed to foreign reporters.
   Among those going through the hearings were Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze, Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov and KGB
Chairman Vladimir Kryuchkov, Tass said.
   After the questioning of Ryzkhov by members of the parliament
about economic policies, ``each of his 13 deputies and more than 50
ministers are now to go through the same `parliamentary purgatory'
as well,'' the official news agency said.
   ``And all indications are that some of them will find the going
pretty tough,'' it said.
   It cited the case of Gennady Bogomyakov, Ryzhkov's candidate for
minister of the oil and gas industry, who was accused in the
government newspaper Izvestia last week of ignoring the environment
while he was Communist Party chief in the Tyumen region of Siberia.
The Tyumen area is Siberia's main oil and gas region.
   Hearings will continue for at least a week, Tass said. They are
to be followed by a 40-day session of the full 542-member Supreme
Soviet, which will confirm the appointees and begin drafting
legislation.
   Speaking to the Supreme Soviet on June 10, Ryzhkov said the
number of ministries would be slashed to streamline the government.
   The Congress of People's Deputies is a new 2,250 member
parliamentary body that elected Mikhail S. Gorbachev to a new, more
powerful presidency and chose the Supreme Soviet in its initial
session that lasted from May 25-June 9.
   Soviets eagerly watched the daily live telecasts in which
Congress deputies challenged Communist Party authority, questioned
Gorbachev and other top officials, and openly criticized such
previously untouchable organizations as the KGB.
   The Supreme Soviet replaces a 1,500-member parliament of the same
name that rarely challenged Kremlin authority.
</TEXT>
