<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Mayors-Redevelopment Bjt   06-19 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayors-Redevelopment, Bjt,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Shows Off Redevelopments That Aren't Ugly</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tours of the historic district are a main
attraction in this elegant port city where the Civil War began, but
the hot ticket this week has been a tour of its poorest
neighborhoods.
   Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. displayed for his counterparts from
around the country how Charleston not only preserved and revitalized
its downtown but extended the same emphasis on preservation and
thoughtful urban design into such often-dreary needs as parking and
public housing.
   ``In the '60s, the question was, `Are the cities going to die?'
'' said Riley. ``We found out that they aren't.
   ``The question now is, `What kinds of quality are our cities
going to represent?' What we have to be very careful about is
realizing we are building our country's civilization in the cities,
and we have to do that with quality.''
   Riley, host of the annual meeting this week of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, is known among mayors for his success at urban
redevelopment _ and for obtaining the federal grants that made it
possible.
   He showed off that success Sunday when he led three busloads of
mayors and other urban leaders on a tour of his city of 80,000.
   The city's poor East Side is still blighted by dilapidated
buildings, and Riley says Charleston needs more public housing. But
the housing the city has built for its poor is attractive and is
scattered throughout neighborhoods.
   Low-income housing was built, not in big projects or bleak boxes,
but in renovated homes that date to the 1880s and in reproductions
of them. Each is in the unique style native to the city:
one-room-wide homes fit onto narrow lots with porches along the side.
   ``We believe so strongly in Charleston that nothing has to be
ugly, and certainly nothing the city builds should be ugly,'' said
Riley, 46, mayor since 1975.
   The emphasis has been on preserving individual buildings and the
feel of neighborhoods. The cost, he insisted, was no more to
renovate old homes than it would have been to tear down and build
anew.
   ``Usually when you demolish something, it is a sign of failure,''
Riley said. ``Our goal is to take every old dilapidated structure in
the city and turn it into housing for our low-income citizens.''
   In downtown Charleston, King Street was dying a decade ago, he
said. Now it's thriving, from its old storefronts to the new $78
million Charleston Place complex of hotel, shops and convention
center where the mayors are meeting.
   The complex was completed three years ago, assisted by $14
million in Urban Development Action Grants and other federal aid.
   The hotel was scaled back from original high-rise plans and
designed with curving bricks and balconies that blend smoothly with
the city's old homes and buildings.
   Riley also showcased downtown parking garages that have been
given tasteful disguises: retail shops on the first floor, and
louvers on the upper levels.
   He also took the mayors through the muck of a waterfront park
still under construction. It affords a view of Fort Sumter, where
the first shots of the Civil War were fired, and will become a major
attraction in an area that has been abandoned and unattractive for a
century.
   No detail is too small to escape the city's beautification. The
city spent $5,000 to convert one traffic island from pavement to a
mini-park with grass and Palmetto trees.
   On a bigger scale, the abandoned city incinerator was turned into
a community center, giant smokestacks still standing out front.
   Parks in poor neighborhoods were reclaimed, with chain-link
fencing replaced by landscaping touches.
   ``Quality design and construction was their right as well,''
Riley said of the residents of poor neighborhoods.
   But while Riley was showing mayors how redevelopment can succeed,
he also made the point that it would be difficult for other cities
to repeat. The UDAG program that has pumped $25 million into the
city to attract private investment is ending, and federal aid for
housing and other programs is dwindling.
</TEXT>
