<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Martyrs     06-19 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Martyrs,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Using Slain Soldiers in Propaganda Blitz</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is increasingly portraying soldiers
who helped crush the pro-democracy movement as heroes and martyrs,
focusing heavily on grisly descriptions and grieving families.
   China's hard-line leadership has been using state-controlled
media to encourage sympathy for the military by focusing on gruesome
instances in which soldiers were slain or wounded.
   ``Li Guorui was thrown off this bridge early on the morning of
June 4,'' a People's Armed Police officer said Monday at Beijing's
Fuchengmen intersection.
   Wreaths of multicolored paper chrysanthemums lined the bridge in
memory of the 20-year-old from Inner Mongolia. A photo of Li was
draped in black ribbons, and offerings of fruit and drinks were laid
before it.
   At Fuchengmen and elsewhere, displays of wreaths show where
soldiers fell.
   Banners pay tribute to them, offering sympathy and praise from
schoolchildren, workers, the Communist Party and fellow soldiers.
   ``Li broke his right leg, cracked his skull and bled to death,''
the police officer told an American journalist before another
officer told the reporter he had to stop interviewing and taking
photographs because it violated martial law orders.
   The Chinese media have given much attention to Li, 25-year-old
Liu Guogeng and Cui Guozheng. The three were killed during the June
3-4 offensive by the People's Liberation Army against pro-democracy
protesters in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   Liu was beaten and burned on Changan Avenue as the army shot its
way toward Tiananmen in the pre-dawn hours of June 4, and Cui was
thrown off a pedestrian bridge at the Chongwenmen intersection and
set on fire.
   Western intelligence estimates and Chinese sources say up to
3,000 people were killed during the march on Tiananmen. The
government says fewer than 300 died, about half of them soldiers.
   For the last several days the media has shown wounded soldiers,
citizens thanking troops, and eulogies for the three martyrs.
   Premier Li Peng, who imposed martial law May 20, and Qiao Shi,
who is apparently being eased into the post of Communist Party
chief, were shown on evening television news meeting the grieving
families of the three dead men on Monday.
   ``We are deeply pained by their glorious sacrifice. I thank you,
fathers and mothers, for raising such fine soldiers,'' Li told
relatives. ``Their deaths have also awakened thousands upon
thousands of people in seeing through the brutal nature of the
rebels.''
   A day earlier, President Yang Shangkun, a former general who
Chinese sources say ordered the raid on Tiananmen, met with the
families.
   ``They are the glory of your families, the glory of the army and
the glory of the nation,'' Yang said in the People's Liberation Army
Daily.
   A few hundred yards west of Tiananmen on Changan Avenue, a few
dozen wreaths surround a photo of Liu, a second lieutenant.
   A large poster describes how he joined the army in Shandong in
1983, was made platoon leader in 1987, applied for Communist Party
membership and was preparing to get married.
   ``On June 4, during the struggle to calm the
counter-revolutionary turmoil, he made a heroic sacrifice,'' the
poster reads.
   ``Going to the aid of comrades surrounded by crowds, he was
beaten with steel poles and bricks,'' it says. ``Hoodlums beat him
as he lay in a pool of his own blood, and poured gasoline on him and
set him on fire. Covered in flames and blood, Liu Guogeng tried to
stand up but they beat him again. They cruelly hung his body on the
remains of a burned-out bus.''
   Cui's story is just as gruesome: beaten by ``hooligans,'' he was
thrown off the pedestrian bridge, doused with gasoline as he lay
groaning, and set on fire. His body was strung up by the neck.
   Officials have conceded in recent days that there were some
civilian casualties that were accidental. But there are no public
memorials to students or bystanders slain in the violence, which
witnesses and doctors say include the elderly and young children.
   There are signs the relentless propaganda campaign is working.
   A group of third graders from an elementary school near Li's
memorial came by to give popsicles to soldiers and People's Armed
Police. ``We just came for the fun of it,'' said one.
   ``People are beginning to understand the army,'' said a
shopkeeper a few steps away from the flowers.
   ``It's like the Chinese saying: the army and the people are like
fish and water,'' she said. ``They are one.''
</TEXT>
