<FIRST>r a PM-Skinner-Controllers     06-19 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skinner-Controllers,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Workers Get Raises at Some Airports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES PLAINES, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner today said about 2,100 air traffic controllers, technicans
and safety inspectors at some of the nation's busiest airports will
get raises of up to 20 percent.
   The raises for Federal Aviation Administration employees at 11
sites in the New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and Oakland, Calif.,
areas are part of a five-year program to retain and recruit workers,
he said.
   The FAA has said it is difficult to staff those sites because of
the high cost of living and the tough workload.
   The raises will mean ``some of the highest paid people in the
federal government'' will be working for the FAA, Skinner said.
   At a news conference near the nation's busiest aiport, O'Hare
International, Skinner said a controller on the top rung of the
seniority ladder makes at least $60,000 a year, including overtime.
The raises will be added to base pay.
   Transportation Department officials said the cost of the program
would be about $5 million a year.
   In addition to being short of help, New York, Chicago, Los
Angeles and Oakland have many workers who are near retirement. But
since the raises were proposed a few months ago, controllers in
other areas of the country have applied for transfer and some who
were ready to retire want to stay, Skinner said.
</TEXT>
