<FIRST>r a AM-Mosquitoes 1stLd-Writethru a0590 06-19 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosquitoes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brandon Area Faces Mosquito Situation With Gallows Humor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `This year's...' to clarify location of problem.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRANDON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs of a community under siege:
   ``Danger, Mosquitoes.''
   ``Yes Mosquitoes. No Refunds.''
   ``Don't Be Bugged: Choose From a Wide Variety of Repellants.''
   This year's mosquito population in parts of west-central Vermont
evokes Alfred Hitchcock's ``The Birds,'' a film in which flocks of
normally benign birds attack humans.
   Just ask Sue Strutz, who moved to Vermont from Michigan City,
Ind., two years ago. Her husband's the one who put up the danger
sign outside their home.
   ``On a really bad day, you can see them on the kitchen window,
just swarming,'' she said as she waved a few away. ``You walk out
and you're covered.''
   Mosquitoes thrived this year because an unusually wet spring
followed two dry years. As a result, residents are swatting three
years worth of mosquitoes at once, according to Arthur Doty,
chairman of the Brandon Leicester Salisbury Insect Control District.
   Some businesses say they've been hurt by the infestation, with
some tourists cutting short their vacations at Lake Dunmore. The
'skeeters have chased children off playgrounds and picnic areas.
Attendance at Branbury State Park, where Lake Dunmore is located,
has dropped drastically.
   Gloria Currie, a park attendant who flits in and out of her toll
booth to collect user fees while winged opportunists hover nearby,
said motorists don't need to see the sign warning of the infestation.
   ``They roll down the window and the mosquitoes fly in,'' she
said. They then ``roll up the window and make a U-Turn to leave.''
   Lake Dunmore lifeguard Jeff Boltz has worked with long pants and
a beekeeper's veil.
   ``You can see clouds of mosquitoes around here,'' he said. ``You
can hear the angry hum.''
   Some store owners say their suppliers can't keep up with the
demand for insect repellant. Booth's Junction Store in Forestdale, a
village in Brandon, has sold 25 cases of the stuff.
   T-shirts featuring a group of mosquitoes and bearing the slogan
``I gave in Vermont'' sold out immediately, said clerk Carol
Constantine of Leicester.
   Most downtown merchants have a caricature of Gov. Madeleine Kunin
showing her with the body of the accursed insect and a stinger.
   Residents don't seem to place all the blame on the state,
however. Many grumble about the environmentalists who lobbied to
stop the spraying of insecticides like DDT because of health hazards.
   Tasks like mowing the lawn or working in the garden require
planning and courage.
   ``You feel like a prisoner in your own house,'' said Laura
Peterson as she wheeled her 14-month-old son through town in a
stroller equipped with mosquito netting. ``Barbeques are kind of out
of the question. It's no fun anymore.''
   Merchants fear the publicity will hurt business even more.
   ``Vermont is a tourist state,'' said Ian Booth, owner of Booth's
Junction Store in Forestdale. ``It isn't good avertising.''
   The governor announced Thursday she would call on the state
Emergency Board to appropriate $100,000 for a mosquito abatement
program. The money will pay for a mosquito specialist and an
assistant to help determine where the insects are breeding.
   On a recent mild afternoon, many residents seemed hopeful. They
said the problem seemed to be tapering off, and noted that another
insecticide spraying truck has been purchased.
   Gradually rising temperatures also may ease the situation. With
any luck, things will heat up before the Independence Day parade
scheduled for July 1. Key additions to this year's roster of honored
vehicles are two pesticide trucks.
   Bugged as they are, Brandonites haven't lost their sense of
humor. Tucked amid the articles and cartoons in the latest edition
of Dateline Brandon was a recipe for the Swat Sandwich: ``Butter two
slices of bread, step out into the door yard and slap...''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Economy     06-19 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Economy,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korea Lowers Economic Goals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Monday announced
measures to try to revitalize the economy and overcome the impact of
widespread labor unrest, soaring wages and lagging production.
   President Roh Tae-woo told a special Cabinet meeting that strong
measures were needed to ensure economic growth and avoid political
unrest. He said the government would not be swayed by public
opposition.
   ``If this indiscretion and disorderliness continues, it would be
impossible to revitalize the economy with economic policies alone
... (the Cabinet must) do its utmost to restore social order and
stability,'' Roh told the meeting.
   To recover lost competitiveness on exports, officials said the
government would stabilize the won's exchange rate against foreign
currencies. There would be no more appreciation of the won against
the U.S. dollar and the won might be devalued by about 3 percent
later this year, they said.
   Under American pressure, the won went up 15.8 percent against the
dollar last year and has gained 2.5 percent so far this year. The
United States has been seeking a strong won to offset its $9 billion
trade debt with Seoul.
   Tax breaks to encourage investment and savings, and some price
controls on utilities and other items were announced.
   The administration would lower its economic growth target for
1989 to 7.5 percent, down from an initial goal of 8 percent. The new
target would be the lowest in four years.
   The annual export goal was lowered from an original $70 billion
to $68 billion, while the annual import target was revised to $64
billion, down from the original $65 billion.
   In the first five months of this year, South Korea ran a trade
deficit of $11 million, in sharp contrast to a surplus of $3.3
billion during the same period in 1988.
   Roh and economic officials stressed the need to end a recent
round of raises demanded by workers. The economy has been hit during
the past two years by strikes and demands for large raises.
   The government says strikes and labor unrest have caused $4.5
billion in lost production this year.
   Deputy Prime Minister Cho Soon said the economy also had been hit
by inflation, a decline in investments and savings, and diversion of
funds to luxury consumer items.
   Wages had increased the past two years by an average of 62.5
percent and had to be slowed, Cho said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
