<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Guyana     06-19 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Guyana,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Hoyte for Tough Economic Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guyana President Desmond Hoyte emerged from the
White House on Monday with praise from President Bush for the tough
economic measures Hoyte has instituted in his South American nation.
   ``I tried to impress upon President Bush our own earnestness in
trying to put our economic house in order,'' said Hoyte, who is
visiting the United States to promote business investment in Guyana.
   Despite a steep devaluation of the Guyanese currency and cuts in
price supports for such commodities as rice, flour and gasoline,
Hoyte's government managed to embark on its austerity program in
April without the riots that ensued when Venezuela struck a similar
course.
   ``President Bush expressed deep appreciation for our efforts,''
Hoyte said.
   A White House official said Bush expressed his admiration to
Hoyte ``for taking the tough steps he has done.''
   ``Bush told him he appreciates how tough it is to implement such
an austerity program,'' said the official, who insisted on
anonymity. Bush also applauded ``the tough line Hoyte has taken on
combating narcotics.''
   Hoyte, speaking with reporters outside the White House, said he
thanked Bush for U.S. economic assistance and expressed the hope
that ``this assistance will continue to be flexible.''
   On drugs, Hoyte said he has introduced ``pretty Draconian
legislation'' providing long jail sentences and the confiscation of
property from drug traffickers.
   ``We think that no individual country can tackle this mess of
narco-trafficking. It has to be a regional and international
effort,'' said Hoyte.
   Hoyte said he was encouraged by improvements in the business
outlook for his country, including ``no less than 10 overseas mining
corporations exploring for gold in Guyana.''
   ``Most significant of all has been the return of Reynolds
(Aluminum) to Guyana,'' he said. ``In 1975, we nationalized
Reynolds' holdings in Guyana. I think it is a most eloquent
testimony of the changed policies and the confidence that investors
have in the climate at the moment that Reynolds has returned.''
   Reynolds has signed an agreement to open a bauxite mine that will
produce 2.6 million tons of ore annually.
   ``The signs are very encouraging,'' said Hoyte, who was touring
major cities across the Midwest _ Chicago, Indianapolis, Toledo,
Ohio; St. Louis and Milwaukee _ to preach the gospel of investment
in Guyana.
   ``I don't know what is going to arise really from these contacts,
but ... it makes good sense to make Guyana known to as many business
people and business communities as possible,'' he said.
   Guyana has already signed agreements with its neighbors Venezuela
and Brazil to cooperate on the interdiction of drug trafficking
``and generally to join forces in combating this evil,'' he said.
   An agreement will be signed later this year with Suriname, he
added.
</TEXT>
