<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     06-19 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>50,000 Homeless Following Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major river swollen by heavy rains
spilled over its embankment, washing away thousands of huts and
leaving 50,000 people homeless, officials said Monday.
   The River Gumti breached the mud embankment in four places since
Sunday in Comilla, inundating several thousand acres of crops, said
Alim Hussain, a Comilla district official.
   The deluge swept away thousands of mud-and-straw houses in about
100 villages of the district, 55 miles southeast of Dhaka, according
to a Comilla official who arrived in Dhaka on Monday.
   Many people were marooned on the roofs of houses and hundreds
camped on roads and along the unbroken portions of the embankment
while rain continued Monday, he said.
   A senior official at the Relief Ministry said the ministry was
planning to help the affected areas in Comilla and Rangpur on
Tuesday.
   Officials at Water Development Board said some areas of the
neighboring Rangpur and Lalmonirhat districts also were flooded by
water from the River Teesta.
   They said the Brahmaputra and the Ganges, the country's two major
rivers, will keep rising in the next 24 hours.
   Bangladesh has hundreds of rivers that form the deltas of the
Brahmaputra and the Ganges. Last year, floods killed 1,400 people
and left 2.3 million homeless.
</TEXT>
