<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1454EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-MspiElections 1stLd-Writethru a0594 06-19 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mspi Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks in Eight Judicial Races; Constitutional Changes Also on Ballot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 9th graf to CORRECT to eight, sted nine year term.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two years after a judge ruled
that Mississippi's method of electing judges violated the federal
Voting Rights Act, eight blacks are on the ballot in elections
Tuesday that could more than double the number of blacks on the
bench.
   Also on the ballot are three proposed constitutional amendments.
One would eliminate the racially motivated, and long-since
unenforced, poll tax law.
   Judicial elections are being held this year because of a federal
court order forcing judicial districts to be redrawn.
   In April 1987, U.S. District Judge William H. Barbour Jr. of
Jackson ruled that the state's judicial districts discriminated
against blacks. The ruling, which was the first to apply a section
of the 1965 federal Voting Rights Act to judicial elections, was
upheld by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Barbour ordered some districts redrawn to create minority
subdistricts so that black voters would have a better opportunity to
elect black candidates to judicial posts.
   The ruling and the appeals process put judicial elections in the
state on hold until this year, when all 69 circuit and chancery
judgeships are being filled.
   Party primaries were held in April, and the winners of Tuedsay's
races will take office July 3.
   Mississippi now has only four black judges among the 78 Supreme
Court, Circuit Court and Chancery Court judges in the state _
Supreme Court Justice Reuben Anderson, Circuit Judges Fred L. Banks
Jr. and Lillie Blackmon-Sanders, and Chancery Judge Isaac Byrd.
   Each was appointed to fill a vacancy, but Anderson went on to win
a full eight-year term in 1986. Byrd did not seek election to a full
term this year, and the other two are seeking regular terms Tuesday.
   Blackmon-Sanders is opposed by a Republican. Banks and one other
black Democrat, Isadore W. Patrick, are unopposed in the general
election.
   In other cicuit court and chancery court cases, three black
candidates are facing incumbents, while two others are vying for
open judgeships where neither candidate is an incumbent.
   Chancery courts handle civil lawsuits while circuit courts handle
criminal cases.
   One proposed constitutional amendment on the ballot would delete
references to the levying of a poll tax as a requirement to register
to vote. It also would eliminate the four-month school year and a
county common school fund, which were to be financed from the poll
tax collections.
   The poll tax was aimed at keeping blacks off voter rolls. It has
remained on the books in the state even though it was struck down by
the U.S. Supreme Court in 1966.
   Another proposed constitutional amendment would remove the
prohibition against out-of-state businesses operating a railroad in
Mississippi _ all but unenforceable with the demise of local
railroad companies. The third would allow the Legislature more
flexibility in how it proposes future constitutional amendments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
