<FIRST>u a AM-DoubleSearch Bjt   06-19 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Double Search, Bjt,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Searches for Her Mother and Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS HOPKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosalyn Taylor O'Neale was moving steadily toward
middle age as a fast-track career woman when her brother whispered
to her something that gave her pause.
   He told her she was adopted.
   The news hit hard. It got her thinking, not only about the woman
who gave her up, but about herself. O'Neale had given up a daughter
for adoption when she was 19.
   ``It's very bizarre growing up thinking you are biological and
everyone else, even cousins, know,'' O'Neale, 39, said in a
telephone interview from her home in suburban Acton.
   So, for two years _ since her brother divulged the news while
their mother was undergoing heart surgery _ she has been conducting
the unusual search for both her mother and her daughter.
   ``It's an odd feeling, like I'm a single person in the world. I
want to be with people that look like me,'' said O'Neale, a human
relations specialist at the Digital Corp. headquarters in Maynard.
   Mary Byrne, senior program director for Boston Children's Service
Association, said that in her 35 years of working with adoptions she
knows of only one other case like O'Neale's.
   Born June 21, 1950, in Louisville, Ky., O'Neale was adopted by
the social worker handling the case when her mother gave her up at
the age of 18 months. She was distressed she had not been told about
the adoption as a child, but she is close to the family who raised
her, and they're helping in her search.
   O'Neale signed the adoption papers for her own daughter five days
after giving birth Sept. 9, 1969, to the girl she called Katherine
Elaine.
   She said she doesn't regret it _ ``I was too young'' _ but
learning of her own adoption has heightened O'Neale's concerns about
her daughter. Often while speaking at colleges as a volunteer for
the Urban League, she wonders if her daughter is in the audience,
she said.
   ``It's emotionally complex,'' she said. ``You are never
disconnected from that child. I want her to know that I knew I would
have been a bad mother.''
   She said she feels a need to tell her mother she ``turned out
fine,'' and find out if her daughter received a good home.
   O'Neale has made hundreds of phone calls, written repeatedly to
government agencies, hired people to assist in her search, and spent
thousands of dollars in the process. Recently she ran a classified
ad in USA Today.
   ``I am determined that before I grow older, those women and I
will get together, and we will know each other immediately,'' said
O'Neale.
   O'Neale's adoptive mother, who lives in Kentucky, has a different
last name and asked that it not be used. She said O'Neale was not
told she was adopted because ``we wanted to prevent conflict between
her and the natural son. I always treated her like she came from my
womb.''
   Now she is helping in the search. And the Kentucky government
agency that handles adoption records has sent along the name and
background on her biological mother, Loraine Ash, the names of Ash's
parents, and most important for O'Neale, proof of a beginning.
   ``Before, I felt like I dropped out of nowhere,'' said O'Neale.
``I ran around the house showing my footprint to my friends.''
   Now she knows she shares with her biological mother an allergy to
tomatoes, and had tonsillitis in early childhood. O'Neale said the
records show her name at birth was Roseline Elaine. Her adoptive
mother changed it to Rosalyn Katherine, and O'Neale changed her name
five years ago to Rosalyn Taylor O'Neale, because, she said, it
sounds distinguished.
   She says her use of Elaine as the middle name for her daughter,
when it was also her original middle name, is coincidental.
   Armed with background on her mother, O'Neale believes she will
soon be successful in half of her search. But she notes that,
apparently, she got the names by mistake.
   After yet another lead did not pan out recently, O'Neale
collapsed into tears and decided she would give up the search for a
while.
   But three days later, the Kentucky agency suddenly responded to
one of her many letters by sending records. Someone in the agency
apparently slipped, unaware of the confidentiality rules.
   ``It's where the system breaks down and it helps adopted
people,'' she said. ``It's what I needed. I feel reinspired now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
