<FIRST>r a AM-RoughRescue     06-19 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rough Rescue,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Crew Battles Rough Seas to Rescue Boater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STEINHATCHEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Coast Guard pilot set his helicopter
down in rough seas Monday to rescue a boater who apparently had
suffered a heart attack, officials said.
   ``It was terrific airmanship,'' said Lt. Jeff Karonis, Coast
Guard spokesman in Miami.
   Raymond Tjotta, 47, of Tampa, was airlifted to Shands Hospital in
Gainesville, where he was in fair condition, a spokesman there said.
   The rescue effort began after Tjotta's 30-foot sailboat, the
Viking Wolf, broadcast a mayday 11 p.m. Sunday, Karonis said. He
said a Coast Guard jet located the sailboat in the Gulf of Mexico 17
miles from the mouth of the Steinhatchee River.
   After the H-3 helicopter reached the sloop at 3 a.m., the crew
made several attempts to hoist Tjotta and a companion from the boat
in a basket.
   A crewman then was lowered onto the boat, and Lt. William Moore,
the pilot, landed the helicopter in seas that were running up to
eight feet.
   ``A water landing is always more difficult because of the
swells,'' Karonis said. ``The waves are not constant. And that was
compounded by the fact that it was at night.''
   A line was used to pull Tjotta, his companion and the crewman
from the boat to the helicopter, Karonis said.
</TEXT>
