<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Rights     06-19 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Rights,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,500 March For Human Rights in Prague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 Czechoslovak activists
took part in a silent march for human rights in downtown Prague on
Monday, sources said.
   The march was organized by the unofficial ``Helsinki Czechoslovak
Committee'' led by Jiri Hajek, a former foreign minister during the
1968 ``Prague Spring'' period of liberalization, according to the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonimity.
   Among the demonstrators was Vaclav Maly, vice-president of the
committee.
   Five other independent organizations called the march last week
after Czechoslovak authorities banned an unofficial meeting
occasioned by a human rights conference in Paris.
   The month-long conference, which opened May 30, is aimed at
reviewing human rights progress by the 35 nations, all signatories
of the 1975 Helsinki Final Act. It has also taken to task nations
accused of specific human rights abuses, including Bulgaria and
Romania.
   Police made identity checks but otherwise did not interfere with
the march, which lasted about a half-hour, the sources said.
</TEXT>
