<FIRST>r a AM-Graduation-Drugs     06-19 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Graduation-Drugs,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Volunteers, School Officials Betrayed by Graduation Drugs, Drinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School officials canceled the all-night
graduation party they planned when they found drugs and alcohol
during a search of buses in the middle of the night.
   School Superintendent Timothy Monahan said the disappointing turn
of events does not mean the program will die.
   ``I am certain that the Class of 1990 will have Celebration
Graduation if they desire,'' he said Monday, but he said more
parents must participate.
   ``The amount of parents over the years has dwindled
considerably,'' he said. ``We need your help and support if the
program is to continue.''
   School and police officials held a news conference Monday to sort
out what led to the decision to call off the celebration and direct
about 400 students to call their parents for a ride home at about 2
a.m. Saturday.
   Police said that 40 to 50 of the 400 students were involved.
   Volunteer coordinators and school officials said they felt
betrayed that students smuggled drugs and alcohol into the
celebration and even smoked pot on a bus.
   ``The more we found out about the situation, the more betrayed we
felt,'' a disappointed project coordinator, Susan Anderson, said.
``It was clear that these students set out to test the program and
violate it.''
   After some chaperones smelled what they suspected was marijuana
being smoked on a bus, police searched all 11 buses and found
marijuana, cocaine, beer and whiskey on three buses.
   The buses were taking students from a pizza parlor to a bowling
alley and movie theater. No one was arrested, though police said
they were continuing interviews this week and might make arrests
later.
   After the discovery, Principal David Matthews canceled the rest
of the activities _ including a dawn breakfast and the awarding of
prizes, including a car _ and ordered all the students back to
school, where parents were called.
   ``I think we made a very clear statement by terminating the
program and we had to do that. We had to be very uncompromising,''
she said.
</TEXT>
