<FIRST>r w AM-Mosbacher     06-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Defends Get-Tough Approach to Opening Foreign
Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher on Monday
defended the administration's get-tough approach to opening foreign
markets to American products, saying that the effort must be made to
correct huge trade imbalances.
   In an address at the Johns Hopkins Foreign Policy Institute,
Mosbacher called last year's U.S. trade deficit of $120 billion
unacceptable and said more has to be done to reduce the imbalance.
   ``Increasingly, national economic power depends on the ability to
compete effectively in world markets,'' Mosbacher said. ``The growth
of commerce, both nationally and internationally, is the key to
guaranteeing that America's most productive and prosperous days are
still ahead.''
   Mosbacher defended the administration's decision last month to
target Japan, Brazil and India for erecting barriers to sales of
American goods.
   If the countries do not agree to remove the barriers, the
administration has the power under the new trade law to retaliate by
imposing 100 percent tariffs against selected imports from those
countries.
   Other nations have complained that the administration's decision
was high-handed and risked plunging the world into a global trade
war.
   But Mosbacher said that the administration's decision in
targeting the three nations was done ``not in defiance of the ...
multilateral trade system but to expand it by opening foreign
markets.''
   Mosbacher, who was one of the leading proponents of the more
aggressive trade stance within the administration, said that the
United States needed such an effort to whittle down the huge trade
imbalances that currently exist.
   ``We firmly reject any slide toward protectionism,'' Mosbacher
said. ``But there are disturbing trends in the trade picture.
Subsidies, distribution systems, industrial policies and even the
economic structure of some countries have led to a reliance on
exports without a willingness to import.''
   Mosbacher said, however, that he was encouraged by recent talks
he held with officials of the European Economic Community over how
American companies will be treated once a unified European market is
established in 1992.
   He said he had received a commitment that U.S. products will be
treated equally with European products for testing and certification
and the European standard-setting committees will consider the
comments made by American companies before drawing up final
regulations.
   Mosbacher hailed these comments as an ``important step forward''
in an area of major concern to U.S. companies, who had feared that
the standards would be drawn in such a way as to keep American
products off European store shelves.
   ``We believe that (the economic unification of Europe) will be
good for Europe and that it can be a positive force for the United
States and the rest of the world, if implemented in the open manner
being discussed by European leaders,'' he said.
</TEXT>
