<FIRST>u i AM-Greece Bjt   06-19 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece, Bjt,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rightists Offer Coalition With Leftists to Investigate Socialists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative leader Constantine Mitsotakis
offered Monday to form an interim government with rival leftists for
the sole purpose of cleaning up scandals left by the regime of
Premier Andreas Papandreou.
   Mitsotakis' center-right New Democracy party finished first in
Sunday's elections, defeating Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement, but failed to win a majority needed to govern.
   A leftist-communist coalition, which finished third, has emerged
as the likely power broker in the battle to form a coalition
government.
   Both Mitsotakis and Papandreou earlier said they would reject
support from the coalition, but both made conciliatory overtures to
the group after the balloting.
   The possibility remained that Papandreou, despite Sunday's
second-place finish, could return as premier if Mitsotakis cannot
form a government.
   Papandreou met Monday with President Christos Sartzetakis, the
ceremonial head of state, and submitted his resignation. But he was
asked to remain as caretaker premier until a new government was
formed.
   Mitsotakis meets with the president on Tuesday to receive a
three-day exploratory mandate to form a government. If he fails,
Papandreou will receive the same opportunity to build a coalition.
   If neither can form a majority, the president is to appoint a
caretaker government to prepare for new general elections.
   But Mitsotakis, at a news conference, proposed leading an interim
governing coalition that ``would last only a few months'' before new
elections are held.
   ``... The express purpose of this government would be the
punishment of those guilty of the scandal of the century
unprecedented in recent Greek history,'' said Mitsotakis, referring
to a multimillion-dollar banking scandal that plagued Papandreou's
government.
   Mitsotakis said he would be prepared to ``include one or two
representatives'' from the Communist alliance in his interim cabinet.
   Mitsotakis said ``because of political differences with the left
parties, this government will not be able to tackle issues like a
new bases agreement with the United States.''
   A pact that allows the United States to maintain military bases
in Greece expired in December and the nations have been trying to
negotiate a new accord for two years.
   Mitsotakis said the interim government, if it is formed, also
would not be able to deal with a U.S. demand for the extradition of
alleged Palestinian terrorist Mohammed Rashid, wanted for
involvement in the bombing of a Pan Am jetliner over Hawaii in 1982.
   ``The government will have a strictly limited mandate to carry
out the catharsis and cannot face such issues,'' he said.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said composition of the eventual Greek government ``is a choice that
the people of Greece must make. Our alliance with Greece is
important.''
   Leaders of the leftist coalition had no comment on Mitsotakis'
offer and were expected to meet to weigh their options.
   Papandreou, beset by financial scandals, a highly publicized
divorce from his American wife and a backlash over an extramarital
affair with a woman half his age, was trying to win a third straight
four-year term in office.
   The premier and ranking members of his party were accused of
involvement in a scandal in which $200 million allegedly was
embezzled by the chairman of the Bank of Crete, George Koskotas.
   Papandreou has rejected Koskotas' charges that he and members of
his socialist administration masterminded the embezzlement. Koskotas
is in a Massachusetts jail awaiting an extradition hearing.
   Members of Papandreou's party met Monday to decide if they would
try to retain power by proposing a coalition with the leftists.
   Papandreou's party dropped from 154 to 125 seats in the
300-member Parliament after Sunday's election. New Democracy
captured 144 seats, seven short of a majority.
   The Coalition of the Left and Progress, an alliance of the
Moscow-oriented Greek Communist Party and the Greek Left Party, took
29 seats and could play power broker.
   Leftist coalition chief Harilaos Florakis said before Mitsotakis
made his offer that the coalition would ``fight against the
conservative policy of New Democracy and any other conservative
policy.''
   Papandreou thanked his supporters on Monday for denying ``an
absolute majority to the forces of conservatism.'' He hinted at a
possible coalition offer, noting that the socialists and the leftist
coalition together would form a majority.
   Papandreou came to power in 1981 on an anti-American platorm and
vowing to pull Greece out of NATO and the EEC. The realities of
ruling altered his positions.
   Mitsotakis, an advocate of supply-side economics and less
government interference, favored closer cooperation with the United
States and Western industrial interests.
</TEXT>
