<FIRST>r w AM-Fiske 1stLd-Writethru   06-19 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fiske, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0581,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican Senators Urge Bush Not To Nominate New York Attorney</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 15th graf pvs, bgng: `The letter,'
to UPDATE with Orrin Hatch absent from letter. Picks up 16th graf: `Fiske's
contribution'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen Republican senators, including the
ranking GOP member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, questioned the
party loyalty of New York attorney Robert B. Fiske Jr. and urged
President Bush on Monday not to nominate him as deputy attorney
general.
   ``It does not appear that Mr. Fiske shares the basic approach to
matters of legal and judicial policy which you so effectively
articulated in your winning campaign for president,'' the senators
said in a letter to Bush.
   ``We therefore respectfully urge you to reconsider this matter
and select a nominee with a demonstrated commitment to your
principles, and those of the Republican platform, in these important
areas,'' the senators said.
   The letter was signed by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the ranking
GOP member on the Senate Judiciary Committee and 13 other senators.
   It is unclear whether the letter will persuade Bush not to
nominate Fiske. But it signals that Fiske would face tough
questioning from some Republican senators during Senate confirmation
hearings before the Judiciary Committee.
   On Friday, well after the Republicans began circulating the
letter to collect signatures, Bush appeared to endorse Fiske, who
has been recommended by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
   At a gathering of federal prosecutors at the White House, Bush
noted that his administration included several former U.S. attorneys
in key positions.
   ``We hope to see yet another _ Bob Fiske of New York _ joining
our ranks here soon,'' the president said without elaboration.
   The 14 mostly conservative senators said they had ``serious
concerns'' about Fiske based on his tenure as chairman of the
American Bar Association's Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary,
according to the June 14 letter that was released Monday.
   The senators contend that during Fiske's chairmanship, the panel
``improperly applied ideological criteria to thwart the nominations
of various well-qualified candidates'' that then-President Reagan
had nominated to the federal bench.
   The senators said Fiske, a pillar of the New York legal
establishment who onced served as U.S. attorney in Manhattan, gave
liberal organizations the names of people under consideration for
judgeships.
   ``Such leaks permitted groups opposed to the president's judicial
philosophy to attack the candidates and prevent their nomination,''
the letter said.
   Fiske and the ABA have acknowledged that two liberal
organizations were given the names of prospective nominees for the
purpose of determining if the candidates had ever shown bias against
women or minorities.
   But the ABA denies that it ever used ideological criteria to
determine a lawyer's professional fitness to serve as a judge.
   The letter also was signed by Sens. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., Kit
Bond, R-Mo.; Dan Coats, R-Ind., Jesse Helms, R-N.C., James McClure,
R-Idaho; Conrad Burns, R-Mont.; Bill Armstrong, R-Colo.; Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., Steve Symms, R-Idaho; Charles Grassley, R-Iowa,
Trent Lott, R-Miss.; Connie Mack, R-Fla.; and Thad Cochran, R-Miss.
   A signature noticeably absent from the letter was that of Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who is an outspoken critic of ABA judicial
screening and also is a member of the Judiciary Committee. Hatch
spokesman Paul Smith said the senator decided against signing the
letter after meeting recently with Fiske.
   ``Though he didn't like what Fiske did in the beginning, he still
thought he ought to hear what Fiske had to say'' about his judicial
screening role, Smith said. Hatch ``didn't make a commitment for or
against'' Fiske, Smith said.
   The Justice Department has said Fiske would play no role in
selecting judges for the federal bench if he became the department's
No. 2 official.
   Fiske's contribution of $1,000 to the 1988 Democratic primary
campaign of a U.S. senate candidate in Vermont also reinforced ``our
doubts about Mr. Fiske's commitment to our party's philosophy,'' the
senators said.
   Fiske donated the money to the campaign of William Gray, a former
U.S. attorney in Vermont, with whom he served in the Justice
Department. Gray has been described by Justice Department officials
as an old friend of Fiske.
   Gray lost to then-Rep. Jim Jeffords in last fall's election.
</TEXT>
