<FIRST>r w AM-Yost-Spill     06-19 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yost-Spill,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Commandant: Oil Spill Still May Need More Manpower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleanup of Alaskan beaches three months after
the Exxon Valdez oil spill is progressing well, but more manpower
and double shifts still may be needed, Coast Guard Commandant Paul
A. Yost told Congress on Monday.
   ``The beaches are not going to be crystal pure at the end of this
summer,'' said Yost, testifying on the Bush administration's
proposed $3.47 billion Coast Guard budget for fiscal 1990. Yost was
in Alaska inspecting the cleanup earlier this month.
   He told the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee
that some oil has seeped two to three feet deep into cobble and
gravel along the shore and it could take five to seven years for
Mother Nature to deal with the damage.
   Yost said Exxon is spending $100 million a week on the cleanup.
   ``It's progressing well,'' he said, but added that progress was
slower on beaches outside Prince William Sound.
   The Valdez spilled 10 million gallons of oil after running into a
reef in the sound on March 24. The ship's captain, Joseph Hazelwood,
faces several charges in connection with the spill.
   Yost said Exxon has pledged to clean up enough miles of beach
each week to complete the work by the end of the summer. He said if
the company lags behind the schedule, he would call for additional
manpower and hours.
   Yost said the administration's budget request, except for $244
million to build a new icebreaker, amounts to a 3.6 percent increase
over fiscal 1989 appropriations.
   The icebreaker is needed to increase the U.S. fleet to three,
which still would be two below the number of such ships in the fleet
in 1987.
   ``We cannot carry out the vital missions of this country in the
Arctic and the Antarctic with just two icebreakers,'' he said.
   Yost said he had no objection to a proposal by some members of
Congress to lease, rather than buy, an icebreaker, as long as the
$40 million annual lease payments came from a separate
appropriation. The proposed 30-year lease would put long-term cost
of the ship at $1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
