<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     06-19 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Accuses Nicaragua of Limiting Numbers of Electoral Observers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department accused Nicaragua on
Monday of attempting to restrict outside monitoring of its electoral
process by imposing visa requirements on American citizens.
   ``If Nicaragua wants to hold elections which will enjoy respect,
both internally and in the international community, it should not be
restricting access but should be expanding it,'' department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said.
   ``Right now the question of the new visa requirement inevitably
inspires is, `What do you have to hide?'''
   Americans had been exempted in recent years from from visa
requirements as part of a Nicaraguan effort to draw tourists and to
obtain hard currency in other ways.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega announced the new visa
requirement on Friday, saying the measure was necessary to prevent
the United States from meddling in Nicaraguan internal affairs.
   ``The Yankee have reached the extreme of wanting to direct the
electoral process in Nicaragua. They want to come to do what we
Nicaraguans must do. We can't permit this,'' he said.
   Nicaragua is scheduled to hold presidential elections next
February.
