<FIRST>r w AM-US-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0627 06-19 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Defends Decision to Reject Chile's Request for Extradition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 5, bgng ``A State,'' with comment by official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday defended its
decision to reject Chile's request for the extradition of Sergio
Buschmann, a Chilean guerrilla leader.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the
administration concluded that the U.S. government did not have the
ability to proceed in obtaining an arrest warrant from a U.S. court
to detain Buschmann based on the Chilean preventive-detention
request.
   ``The offenses for which his preventive detention were sought
were not extraditable under the specific terms of the 1900 treaty,''
she said.
   The spokesman at the Chilean Embassy here was not immediately
available for comment.
   A State Department official, insisting on anonymity, said Chile
wanted Buschmann extradited for illegally importing arms into the
country. The official said U.S. legal experts contended there was no
legal basis for approving the extradition and that Chilean
authorities were very disappointed by the U.S. decision.
   Buschmann, wanted in Chile in connection with an assassination
attempt against President Augusto Pinochet in 1986, was en route
from Australia to Sweden when he was arrested June 12 during a
stopover at Anchorage, Alaska. He was arrested at the request of
Interpol, the international police agency.
   He was released Friday along with a countryman and both were
permitted to leave the United States under escort, officials said.
   Buschmann has been a spokesman for the Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic
Front, Chile's principal leftist guerrilla group. Two years ago, he
escaped from a prison in Chile, where he faced arms-smuggling
charges.
   The Chilean government sought Buschmann's extradition while he
was in Australia. But the Australian government deported him on
grounds he engaged in ``unacceptable activities.'' In Australia, he
was raising funds for the guerrilla group and publicly called for
the assassination of Pinochet.
   The United States has been attempting unsuccessfully for more
than 10 years to obtain the extradition from Chile of three security
officers wanted in the 1976 slaying of Ambassador Orlando Letelier,
an outspoken critic of Chile's military government.
</TEXT>
