<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTUMWA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roseanne Barr was a little bit bashful as
she appeared in her boyfriend's hometown, joining him on stage and
joking that the two might get married.
   Barr, star of the television runaway hit ``Roseanne,'' was coaxed
onstage to close a show headlined by comedian Tom Arnold, an Ottumwa
native.
   ``It surprised me that she acted a little bashful,'' said
Penelope Boger, one at the Saturday night performance in the lounge
of a hotel.
   ``I think a lot of it had to do being with Tom in front of his
friends and family,'' said audience member Diane Olson. ``I think
she did very well considering that.''
   After two shows at the hotel, Barr and Arnold entertained at the
Wild Side tavern, run by Arnold's sister, Lori Stockdall. ``It was
so packed in here that I was lucky to see her on the stage,'' said
bartender Randy Davis.
   Barr, 36, is legally separated from her husband, Bill Pentland.
As Barr's marriage has unraveled, she and Arnold, 30, have become an
item on the cover of supermarket tabloids.
   The local newspaper, the Ottumwa Courier, said most of Barr's
onstage remarks were ``R-rated.'' In one show, Arnold whispered in
Barr's ear to get her started on a monologue about the different
``cycles'' that women go through ranging from ``Dragon Lady'' to
``martyr.''
   ``Maybe I'll marry Tom so I can keep the material,'' Barr said at
the end of the monologue.
   Arnold has written some of Barr's stand-up comedy material and
now is a scriptwriter for her show.
   For television fans, Ottumwa, population 27,000, has another
claim to fame: It's the hometown of the fictional Radar O'Reilly of
``M-A-S-H.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television stars don't usually like to talk
about scene-stealing and jealousy among the cast members of a TV
series, but Dinah Manoff of NBC's ``Empty Nest'' comes right out
with it.
   ``Enough with the dog!'' she said in the June 24 issue of TV
Guide. ``Everyone wants to know about the dog. What is the dog, John
Travolta?''
   The actress said her mother, actress-director Lee Grant, warned
her of the perils of playing opposite dogs and children. She
discovered the truth of that on her first job, in ``Raid on
Entebbe.''
   ``I had a scene where a terrorist is threatening me. I'm carrying
a little dog, and I give the dog to another child, and my line is,
`Take care of him and don't let him get cold or anything,''' she
said.
   Next day, she recalled, the producer said: ```Dinah ... Diiinaaah
... the dog is wonderful.' That's what's happening to me now. `The
dog is wonderful.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Garry Trudeau, who often spoofs the
ritual of college commencement in his ``Doonesbury'' strip, urged
Stanford University graduates Sunday to challenge cherished
assumptions and ask tough questions.
   ``The impertinent question is the glory and engine of human
inquiry,'' Trudeau told 3,500 graduates and their families at the
university's 98th commencement.
   ``History's movers framed their questions in ways that were
entirely disrespectful of conventional wisdom,'' said Trudeau, 40,
who cited as examples Albert Einstein, Charles Darwin, Thomas
Jefferson and Pablo Picasso.
   America's political system depends on ``its noisy dissent, its
raucaous squabbles, its competing visions of how it should work,''
he added.
   Although Trudeau's talk was generally serious, the Pulitzer
Prize-winning cartoonist on occasion drew laughter from the audience
of 25,000.
   ``The chief function of the graduation speaker has always been to
prevent graduating seniors from being released into the real world
before they've been properly sedated,'' said Trudeau, who apologized
for taking 15 minutes of the students' time.
   ``It will go faster if you think of it as the equivalent of four
videos,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans of Jerry Lee Lewis were
disappointed when the veteran rocker suddenly canceled a weekend
appearance at Chattanooga's Riverbend Festival, but not all of them
were surprised.
   ``It makes me feel pretty bad,'' said Grayson Goebel, one of
several thousand people who jammed the banks of the Tennessee River
on Sunday night expecting to see the man known as ``The Killer.''
   ``Of course, mother told me as soon as she heard who the slate of
people was, she said, `Well, Jerry Lee Lewis won't show.' I think he
is a close kin of No Show George (Jones).''
   Lewis, 53, canceled the Sunday night show because of swelling in
a leg that had put him in a hospital earlier in the week, according
to Riverbend officials.
   Lewis ``had an abscess on his leg. And something happened to that
and the doctor recommended he not go on. That's all we know,'' said
Margaret Culpepper, a Riverbend organizer.
   The singer, known for such 1950s rock classics as ``Whole Lotta
Shakin' Goin' On,'' had attended a party Saturday night in Memphis
promoting the new movie about his life, ``Great Balls of Fire.''
   After learning about Lewis, Riverbend officials persuaded country
singer Ronnie McDowell, who was performing at Lake Winnepesaukah in
nearby Fort Oglethorpe, Ga., to replace him.
   ``Somebody called me and said, `Hey, Ronnie, Jerry Lee's not
going to make it,' '' McDowell told the Riverbend crowd. ``And you
know what I said? I said, `What's new?'''
   Later, however, McDowell said he was just kidding. ``I know he's
cried wolf a lot of times, but it's the truth this time.''
