<FIRST>r a AM-ChemicalFire     06-19 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Fire,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Lab Fire Caused by Arson, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHANY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a chemical plant early Monday
forced the evacuation of up to 200 residents and sent nearly 50
people to the hospital, officials said.
   Investigators found an unexploded Molotov cocktail near Carbolabs
Inc. after the fire, said state police Sgt. Robert Slattery.
   The blaze started around 3:45 a.m., and was brought under control
around 6:30 a.m., but flared briefly an hour later, state police
said. Smoke wafted into the air throughout the morning.
   About 15 people, mostly firefighters, were treated at Yale-New
Haven Hospital for respiratory problems, said hospital spokeswoman
Cathy Zaorski. A volunteer firefighter who lives near the plant was
hospitalized, she said.
   Thirty-four firefighters were taken to the hospital for
precautionary examinations, Zaorski said.
   Authorities had a list of hazardous chemicals stored in the
one-story, aluminum building, and put a disaster plan into effect as
soon as the fire was reported, said Bob Forster, fire inspector in
this town of about 4,620 people.
   ``The pre-planning saved a lot of lives,'' he said.
   Authorities evacuated as many as 200 residents living up to a
half-mile downwind of the plant, said area Red Cross disaster
coordinator Marge Gilbert. Route 63, which runs by Carbolabs, was
closed.
   The road was reopened at 11 a.m. and evacuees were allowed to
return to their homes around noon.
   The blaze destroyed about half the plant, said Deputy Fire Chief
Herbert Howard.
   Carbolabs produces extremely small quantities of chemicals for
research laboratories worldwide, said lab manager Bill Hampp. The
plant has seven full-time employees, Hampp said.
   Symptoms from some chemicals don't appear for up to 72 hours, and
hospital spokeswoman Zaorski urged people living near the plant to
be alert for chest pains, shortness of breath and other effects for
the next couple of days.
   The state Department of Environmental Protection were called in
to direct the clean-up. The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms joined state and local police in investigating the fire.
</TEXT>
