<FIRST>r a AM-WelchVerdict     06-19 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welch Verdict,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts `Moochie' Welch In Slaying Of Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David ``Moochie'' Welch was convicted
Monday of the 1986 pre-dawn rampage that left his former girlfriend
and five other people dead.
   The Alameda County jury, which got the case a week ago, found
Welch guilty of breaking into the home of 17-year-old Dellane
Mabrey, his former girlfriend and the mother of their young son, and
shooting her to death with an Uzi assault rifle.
   Welch immediately asked that the jury be polled and that the
verdicts be set aside, claiming there had been jury tampering. He
offered no evidence to support the contention. Superior Court Judge
Stanley Golde polled the jurors, then immediately denied the request
to reject their verdict.
   Also killed in the Dec. 8 attack were Sean Orlando Mabrey, 21;
Dwayne Miller, 4; Kathy Walker, 34; Darnell Mabrey, 20; and Valencia
Morgan, 3.
   Welch also was convicted of two counts of attemped murder in the
wounding of the couple's 3-month-old son, Dexter Mabrey, and Leslie
Morgan, 21, Mabrey's current boyfriend and the father of Valencia.
   Welch and a woman companion, Rita Lewis, were arrested later in
the day after a four-hour standoff. Lewis pleaded guilty to six
counts of murder in a deal that hinged on keeping her off death row.
She was sentenced a year after the massacre to 51 years to life in
prison.
   The jury also ruled that special circumstances were involved,
which under the state's death penalty law means they can choose
between the death penalty and life in prison without parole during
the penalty phase of the trial, scheduled to begin June 26.
   Deputy District Attorney James Anderson, who prosecuted the case,
said he would ask for the death penalty.
   Attorney Spencer Strellis, one of two court-appointed lawyers who
helped Welch in his defense, declined to comment.
</TEXT>
