<HEAD>New Advisory Committee Appointed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Louis Sullivan named a new
Social Security advisory council Monday and instructed members to
review financing of the health and long-term care needs of the
elderly and disabled.
   The panel is appointed every four years to examine issues
affecting the Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid programs.
   In announcing the 13 members of the new council, Sullivan
directed that they make recommendations for ``more stable health
care financing'' for the elderly, disabled, poor and uninsured.
   The panel also should review the long-range financial status of
the Social Security program and the role of Social Security in
overall U.S. retirement income policy, Sullivan said.
   The council will be headed by Deborah Steelman, 34, a lawyer,
Bush campaign adviser and former associate director of the Office of
Management and Budget.
