<FIRST>r w AM-Trouble-Shooting     06-19 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trouble-Shooting,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Teen-Agers Win Automotive Trouble-Shooting Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In just over 36 minutes on Monday, two recent
high school graduates from Washington state assembled a car
distributor, found a fault in the new assembly and fixed it,
repaired a fuel-injector cap, got a faulty headlight to work and
made instrument and dashboard lights work properly.
   For that they picked up a $2,500 scholarship each and a trophy
that marks them as the best high school auto technicians in the
country.
   Mike Seresun, 17, and Walter Yagen, 18, of Ingraham High School
in Seattle beat out 49 other state finalist teams in the 40th annual
trouble-shooting contest, sponsored jointly by the American
Automobile Association and Plymouth. It was the second consecutive
victory for a Washington team.
   They were followed, in order, by teams from Iowa, Pennsylvania,
Texas, Connecticut, Alabama, Missouri, Arkansas, Rhode Island and
Oregon.
   Each team got to the finals by winning a series of local and
national written examinations and hands-on competitions. The written
examinations provided 40 percent of the final score but the real
test was the repair work done in the shadow of the Capitol.
   Fifty brand-new Plymouths, identically bugged, were put before
the teams, along with a work order that listed customer complaints:
``Engine won't start,'' ``faulty headlights,'' ``Check-engine light
on'' and ``inoperative instrument and dash lights.''
   It didn't take the young mechanics long to find that one reason
the engine wouldn't start was because it lacked a distributor. On
request, the teams were handed a distributor disassembled and in a
plastic bag.
   Ah, but there was a rub. One of the parts in the bag, a
distributor pick-up plate, was faulty and the mechanics had to find
and fix that, too. The headlight problem, too, was a trick. The low
beam on the bulb was broken and some of the kids merely replaced it
without checking and finding that a fuse controlling the high beam
was defective, too.
   T.J. Rebert, a trainer for Goodyear's training center and one of
the judges, gave demerits to a Utah team that installed a gasket
improperly. He said the car would run well, but would have trouble
5,000 miles later when moisture got into places it shouldn't.
   In fact, he said, pointing to the last car still under repair, if
that car wasn't fixed at all the mechanics would come out ahead of
the ones who put that gasket in wrong because it's better to tell
customers that the car isn't ready than to send them on the road
with one that will break down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
