<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-19 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanks Join Shelling at Souk el-Gharb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian troops battled with
tanks and mortars in hills above Beirut Monday while Syrian
artillerymen shelled the coastline of the Christian enclave north of
the capital.
   A police spokesman said no casualties were reported.
   At least 373 people have been killed and 1,450 wounded since the
Syrians and Christians began shelling duels March 8.
   Both sides have ignored a cease-fire called by the Arab League
three weeks ago to end the latest round in the 14-year-old civil war
between Moslem and Christian forces.
   A communique from Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's
office accused the Syrian army of firing at a Christian garrison in
the hilltop town of Souk el-Gharb, southeast of Beirut, with tanks
and 130mm mortars.
   ``Our garrison struck back with similar weapons at the sources of
fire around Souk el-Gharb,'' the communique said.
   It said the Syrians also fired artillery barrages at the
presidential palace in suburban Baabda, where Aoun lives in an
underground bunker, but there were no direct hits.
   Souk el-Gharb, an abandoned mountain resort, is atop a network of
roads leading from the Syrian-controlled Druse heartland in the
Chouf region southeast of Beirut to Christian zones north and
northeast of the capital.
   Beirut newspapers have reported the possibility of a Syrian
offensive to capture Souk el-Gharb and open the way for an attack on
Baabda if Arab League efforts to stabilize the cease-fire fail.
   In Damascus, the Syrian capital, Vice President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam told the opening session of an Arab lawyers' congress that
Syria supports efforts by a three-member Arab League committee to
end the civil war within six months.
   Leaders of the committeee, formed during last month's Arab League
summit in Casablanca, are King Hassan II of Morocco, King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia and Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid.
   ``The system in Lebanon must be changed, sectarianism must fall,
and reforms are needed so that all citizens become equal,'' Khaddam
told the lawyers.
   He was referring to Moslem demands for an equal share of power
that would end the Christians' traditional supremacy in Lebanon.
   Aoun belongs to the Maronite Catholic church, and Maronite
leaders have dominated the country since independence from France in
1943 when Christians were considered the majority. Moslems now make
up an estimated 55 percent of Lebanon's multi-faith population.
   Khaddam also indirectly attacked Iraq, Syria's main Arab foe, for
backing Aoun's mostly Christian troops.
   ``Those encouraging the small minority who is dealing with Israel
should know that the Lebanese people have already defeated Israel
altogether,'' he said.
   Iraq has declared its support of Aoun's ``war of liberation''
against 40,000 Syrian troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Police said Monday's coastal bombardment came from Syrian
positions in and around Moslem West Beirut and was aimed at the
Christian ports of Jounieh, Byblos and Amsheet.
   The shelling has preventing ships carrying food, fuel and arms
from reaching the Christian enclave, where Aoun's 20,000 troopers
are based.
   The latest round of fighting began two days after Aoun's units
blockaded ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut. Aoun
said the ports were illegal and denied the state treasury about $100
million annually in customs fees.
   The Syrians retaliated by blockading the Christian enclave where
an estimated 1 million people live.
</TEXT>
