<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Mayors     06-19 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayors,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Says HUD Scandals Won't Affect His Goals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mayors-Redevelopment Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp told the
nation's mayors Wednesday that the scandals at his department won't
affect his pledge to fight poverty and bring opportunity to blighted
inner cities.
   ``I want to assure you that I am going to work continuously for
these great goals, and we're going to reform the U.S. housing ...
agency from stem to stern, simultaneously,'' Kemp said. ``That's my
pledge to you.''
   Kemp, secretary of Housing and Urban Development, appeared before
more than 200 of the nation's city leaders gathered for the annual
U.S. Conference of Mayors meeting.
   He repeated his pledge to clean up his department, which has been
beset by allegations of fraud, embezzlement and political influence
peddling. Kemp described his department as engulfed by headlines and
said he had taken steps to remove politics from decisions on where
federal urban aid will go.
   ``Democrats and Republicans need to read my lips _ It's open to
everybody on the basis of need, as opposed to greed, as it existed
in the past,'' Kemp said.
   Speaking to reporters later, Kemp refused to comment on whether
his predecessor, Samuel Pierce, who served as HUD secretary
throughout the Reagan administration, was responsible for the
problems at the department.
   ``I'm not going to make a political judgment about any past
secretary because I think it's unseemly of me,'' Kemp said.
   Kemp said reform of the agency would be added to his goals of
encouraging home ownership and resident management of public
housing, moving aginst homelessness, fighting drugs in housing
projects, and using urban enterprise zones to create jobs in cities.
   Kemp followed Republican National Chairman Lee Atwater, who
delivered a partisan pledge to push GOP candidates for mayor,
particularly in New York, and to recruit blacks as candidates for
city offices.
   ``If we can establish a political beachhead in a city like New
York, that's going to be a shot heard around the country,'' Atwater
said, referring to the race against Democratic Mayor Edward Koch.
   Atwater's remarks stirred strong reaction among some in the
overwhelmingly Democratic crowd of mayors.
   Philadelphia Mayor Wilson Goode, a black and a Democrat, called
Atwater's remarks ``insulting'' and said: ``We're not here for a
partisan campaign speech. We need to hear what the Republican Party
intends to do about the issues facing the cities.''
   Atwater said the Republican Party is ``not opposed to spending
more money on the cities. We just want to be careful to spend
taxpayers' money on projects that work.'' He offered no further
specifics.
   New Orleans Mayor Sidney Barthelemy questioned Atwater's remarks,
noting that they were delivered in a hotel and convention center
financed in part with federal Urban Development Action Grants _ a
program that the Reagan administration succeeded in having killed.
   ``I don't understand which programs he's talking about because
the ones that worked, they killed,'' Barthelemy said in an interview.
   Atwater singled out for introduction one black Republican mayor,
James A. Garner of Hempstead, N.Y. _ but mistakenly first said
Garner was from Schenectady, N.Y.
   Garner said later he was not embarrased by the gaffe. ``Chairman
Atwater knows my name and who I am,'' he said.
   Trenton, N.J., Mayor Arthur Holland later quipped: ``I think Lee
Atwater assumed that we had arranged a recruitment opportunity for
him.''
   Holland, who is retiring after 26 years as mayor because of
illness and is stepping down as president of the U.S. Conference of
Mayors, was given the conference's distinquished public service
award.
   President Bush's absence from the meeting has been a subject of
debate among mayors, and Kemp pledged to do all he could to get Bush
to the mayors' next meeting in January.
</TEXT>
