<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     06-19 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Captures All But One Seat Open to Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity captured eight of nine seats
open to the opposition in runoff national elections, and voters
rejected several prominent Communists, according to unofficial
returns Monday.
   Progressive Communists beat hard-liners in several races Sunday,
further shattering the ruling party's prestige after the independent
union movement's victories in the first round of voting June 4.
   ``The party is faced with the most serious problems in its whole
history,'' Politburo member Leszek Miller said in an interview
Monday with the Communist Party newspaper Trybuna Ludu.
   ``The post-election shock has brought about a need for a deep
analysis of the situation,'' he said.
   Sunday's elections were for Communists and allies who failed to
win the 50 percent of votes necessary to claim seats reserved for
them in the June 4 elections.
   Of 295 seats being decided in the Sejm, or lower house of
parliament, only one was open to the opposition.
   Eight undecided Senate seats, all open to the opposition, also
were contested Sunday. Solidarity won seven of the seats in the
freely elected Senate, building its dominance in the new chamber to
99 of 100 seats.
   Only the victory of rich fodder farmer Henryk Stoklosa denied
Solidarity a clean sweep in the Senate. Stoklosa waged Poland's most
expensive election campaign, plastering his province with
advertisements and hosting picnics with free beer and sausages.
   Solidarity Union clinched the last of 161 Sejm seats available to
independent candidates, according to results provided by local
election commissions to local Solidarity Citizens' Committees.
   Andrzej Wybranski, the lone Solidarity candidate for the Sejm who
did not win June 4, appeared sure of victory.
   The Senate has veto power over laws passed in the Sejm. But
because Solidarity won all seats alloted it in the Sejm, that body
will be unable to generate the two-thirds majority needed to
override a Senate veto.
   Several Communist hard-liners, including Warsaw party leader
Janusz Kubasiewicz, Manfred Gorywoda of the southern industrial
region of Katowice, and Construction Minister Bogumil Ferensztajn,
failed to win Sunday.
   Top party activist Hieronim Kubiak lost in Krakow to a
little-known Communist ally, as did Politburo member Wiktor Pyrkocz
in the central industrial city of Lodz.
   But two party reformers won, state television reported. They are
Politburo member Marian Orzechowski and Ireneusz Sekula, deputy
prime minister in Katowice.
   Some Communist-allied candidates backed by Solidarity committees
did well, including new Sejm legislators Tadeusz Fiszbach, a former
Gdansk party leader who signed the 1980 agreements that first
legalized Solidarity; and Andrzej Bratkowski, brother of a prominent
opposition journalist. Solidarity tried to build its power by
endorsing the most reform-oriented Communist allies.
   In Warsaw, however, only nine of 18 Solidarity-supported
Communist coalition candidates won, Warsaw television reported.
   The National Election Commission said it will publish official
results Tuesday afternoon, PAP state news agency reported.
   Under a pre-election deal between Communist authorities and
Solidarity, the Senate was entirely freely elected. Only 35 percent,
or 161 seats, in the 460-seat Sejm were open to opposition
candidates.
   The new Sejm consists of 299 Communists and their allies,
including an unknown number sympathetic to Solidarity, plus 161
Solidarity-backed deputies. The State Election Commission estimates
only 25.31 percent of eligible voters turned out Sunday for a
postwar low. Turnout was higher only in the six provinces with
Solidarity candidates.
   Lowest previous turnout was 56 percent for June 1988 provincial
council voting, but there have not been nationwide runoffs before.
Turnout was 62 percent for the June 4 parliamentary voting that was
the freest in Eastern Europe since World War II.
   Empty polling stations around the country indicated many voters
considered the second round unnecessary because they made their
views about Communist rule and the staggering economy known June 4.
   The government took another unpopular move Monday, announcing
sugar prices are increasing from 11 cents to 19 cents a pound
starting Tuesday, state television reported. The price increase
comes as Poles prepare for their traditional annual jam and fruit
preserving.
   The elections are among the political, economic and union
freedoms negotiated during two months of unprecedented talks between
the Communist government and the opposition.
   Solidarity, the first independent union in the Soviet bloc, was
outlawed in 1982 and relegalized in April.
</TEXT>
