<FIRST>r a AM-Skinner-Controllers     06-19 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Controllers,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Personnel at Difficult Airports to Get More Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES PLAINES, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FAA is giving pay hikes of up to 20
percent at the busiest airports and traffic control centers to
encourage employees to work there, U.S. Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner said Monday.
   The program, which took effect Sunday, gives raises to about
2,100 workers at 11 Federal Aviation Administration centers in the
New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and Oakland, Calif., areas.
   The agency has had difficulty staffing those facilities with
qualified personnel because living costs, complex operations and
other factors make them unattractive places to work, FAA officials
said.
   The 5-year demonstration program will become permanent if it
succeeds, and air traffic controllers in the busiest centers will be
some of the highest paid people in federal government, Skinner said
at a news conference near the nation's busiest airport, O'Hare
International.
   A top-level air traffic controller makes $60,000 to $65,000 a
year, including overtime, before the raises, he said.
   ``I've been to those centers and frankly I think those jobs
deserve that kind of compensation,'' Skinner said.
   In addition to controllers, safety inspectors and technicians who
service and maintain air traffic-control computers and other
equipment are getting raises.
   The program will cost about $5 million a year, with the funds
coming out of the department's budget and resulting in minor
cutbacks in other programs, Transportation Department officials said.
   The program is a start in solving some of the problems in the air
traffic system, said Tony Dresden, a spokesman for the National Air
Traffic Controller Association.
   ``It will address short-term problems,'' Dresden said. ``We would
hope that the FAA would look at fair compensation for all
controllers.''
   He said union representatives at facilities affected by the
program indicate it is already working. The FAA has received a lot
of applications since the program was announced in March, and those
applying are highly skilled.
   NATCA was certified as the representative of the nation's 7,000
air traffic controllers in 1987, replacing the Professional Air
Traffic Controllers Organization, which was decertified in 1981
after a nationwide controllers' strike.
   The pay-raise program survived attempts by Congress to restrict
it to FAA workers at O'Hare and to limit raises to up to 10 percent
of base pay, department officials said.
   In addition to being short of help in New York, Chicago and Los
Angeles, many of those working at the affected facilities are
nearing retirement, Skinner said.
   The secretary also used the news conference to blast the airlines
and local governments for not adequately planning for a doubling of
air traffic in the past eight years.
   While the federal government also can be blamed for air traffic
conditions, he said it was up to the airlines to come up with
schedules that take into account airport capacities and to develop
new facilities.
   The FAA facilities affected by the incentive plans include air
traffic control centers in Aurora, Ill., and Ronkonkoma, N.Y.; and
the O'Hare and Los Angeles international airport towers and terminal
radar approach control facilities.
   The program also covers approach-control facilities at Westbury,
N.Y., Santa Ana and Oakland, Calif.; and flight standards district
offices in Los Angeles; Farmingdale and Valley Stream, N.Y.; and
Teterboro, N.J.
</TEXT>
