<DOCNO> AP890619-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-US     06-19 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Asks Cardinal To Petition Bush For U.S.-Nicaragua Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega asked the
archbishop of Managua on Monday to petition President Bush for talks
aimed at normalizing U.S.-Nicaraguan relations.
   Ortega diclosed this after a 1{-hour meeting with Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo at the archbishop's offices.
   The development comes after Ortega's leftist Sandinista
government has had to deal with two strikes in the last three weeks
and after it made last week the most drastic devaluation of the
Nicaraguan currency so far this year.
   Obando y Bravo said in a brief statement that regarding Ortega's
request, ``we are going to think about this and will give an
answer.'' He did not say when an answer would come and declined to
talk further with reporters.
   Ortega said, ``We came to talk about the critical economic
situation in which the country dwells.''
   With Obando by his side, the president said he told the
archbishop he is ``worried about the lack of understanding from
economic sectors'' regarding the government's program and about the
ensuing ``polarization'' of society here.
   ``Also the role the Americans could play is important,'' Ortega
said.
   He said U.S. policy toward Nicaragua ``does not contribute to the
strengthening of a climate of peace in Nicaragua.''
   The United States cut off all financial aid to Nicaragua in 1981
and began supporting the anti-Sandinista rebels known as Contras. It
accused Nicaragua of backing rebels elsewhere in Central America and
of failing to fulfill its pledges of democracy.
   Ortega noted with appreciation on Monday the letter sent this
year to the United States by about 800 Latin American bishops,
asking that Washington lift the economic embargo imposed on
Nicaragua in 1985.
   ``We are willing to develop a dialogue with the North American
government so foundations can be laid for normalizing relations
between Nicaragua and the United States,'' Ortega said.
   ``I have asked Cardinal Obando y Bravo to ... take steps and
mediate with President Bush so that a fluid dialogue can develop.''
   Ortega declined to answer reporters' questions.
   The last U.S.-Nicaraguan meeting on normalization was in June
1984 in Manzanillo, Mexico. Washington declared an economic embargo
on Nicaragua in 1985, forbidding any U.S. enterprise from doing
business with the small Central American country.
   Nicaragua announced Friday that for the first time, Americans
will need visas to enter Nicaragua starting July 1.
   The State Department accused Nicaragua on Monday of trying to
restrict outside monitoring of its electoral process with the visa
requirements.
   Nicaragua is to hold presidential elections next February.
   On May 26, Nicaragua expelled two U.S. diplomats, accusing them
of inciting labor unrest to undermine the country. The action came
during wildcat strikes by teachers demanding higher pay and improved
working conditions.
   Prices for nearly all goods doubled after the cordoba was
devalued on June 12 for the 20th time this year, coupled with a 110
percent rise in the price of gasoline. That made the official
exchange rate 20,000 cordobas to the dollar instead of 9,500. Gas
rose from 17,700 cordobas a gallon to 37,200, or $1.86.
   Taxi drivers struck, saying they could not survive with the new
gas prices. Some returned to work after progress was made on a
compromise over the weekend.
   Ortega toured 10 European countries in April and May seeking $250
million in aid just for this year. He returned with $50 million.
   On Jan. 30, he announced austerity measures aimed at combating
hyperinflation, which surpassed 20,000 percent in 1988. Measures
included massive layoffs of public employees, slashing new credit
and investment, and pay freezes.
   According to government figures, the fight against inflation was
succeeding, but the measures also created a recession just at the
start of the planting season _ a factor of prime importance for a
country that derives most of its hard-currency earnings from
agricultural exports.
</TEXT>
