<DOCNO> AP890619-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FederalJobs     06-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Federal Jobs,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workin' Ain't Easy, Students Find</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four student interns from Arkansas, working for
Sen. David Pryor, learned that it's not easy to apply for a federal
government job.
   One intern, John David Walt of Dumas, had an information window
shut in his face. Libby Schnipper of Hot Springs had her employment
questions rebuffed by a secretary, who insisted everything was on
the application form.
   Mary McLoed of Little Rock was told by a federal worker that her
application may never surface on a government computer and that
obtaining an interview would be difficult.
   ``When I asked him how he got his job he smiled and said, ``I'm
lucky. I know people,'' McLeod told a congressional hearing Monday.
   Walt, Schnipper, McLoed and a fourth intern, Rebecca Slaven of
Little Rock, told their experiences to the House Governmental
Affairs civil service subcommittee, headed by Pryor, D-Ark.
   ``Nothing can be more discouraging and frustrating to a young job
seeker than finding no one able or willing to answer questions about
federal job opportunities and the application process,'' Pryor said.
   Walt, who plans to attend the University of Arkansas Law School
in the fall, said he visited the Office of Personnel Management, the
government's personnel agency, to get information about federal jobs.
   He said he got in line about 2:30 p.m., and minutes later, the
woman at the information desk announced the man in front of him
would be the last to be helped.
   ``When I reached the desk, the woman pulled the partition,'' he
said. ``Two other men were desperately trying to request a form. She
ignored them too.''
   Schnipper, a senior at the University of Arkansas, was given two
job application forms and a job description.
   ``I started asking questions about the job and application
process,'' she said, and was interupted by a federal worker who
said, ``All the answers are on the green form.
   ``I tried one more time to ask a question and she took the green
form out of my hand and said, `I don't know any more than what is on
the form.''
   McLeod, a senior at the University of the Ozarks, originally was
told by a federal worker she would ``possibly never'' hear about her
application because she wasn't applying for a specific position.
   ``I then asked for an application for some sort of clerical
work,'' she said. ``He gave me another form. ... He told me that it
would still be difficult to get an interview.''
   Slaven, a senior at Vanderbilt University, said she had to reach
four different people in order to get job information. The employee
she finally reached told her to ``Be quiet and quit interrupting,''
and referred her to the Office of Personnel Management.
</TEXT>
