<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     06-19 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Rebel Charged with Murder in Killing of U.S. Colonel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he was a member of an
elite communist assassination team was charged Monday with murder in
the killing of U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe.
   Rowe was slain by gunmen on April 21 as he was en route to his
office at the Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group in suburban
Quezon City.
   Charges of murder and attempted murder were filed against Donato
Continente, 27, an employee at the University of the Phlippines.
Continente was arrested Friday at the university.
   Continente was presented at a news conference Monday. He said he
was a member of a five-man team of communist rebels assigned to kill
Rowe, and the group had kept the colonel under surveillance since
late January.
   But Continente insisted he did not kill Rowe of McAllen, Texas, a
decorated veteran of the Vietnam War. Rowe's Filipino driver was
wounded in the attack.
   Charges have been filed against six other suspects, but they
remain at large.
   The communists' New People's Army asserted responsibility for
Rowe's death. The guerrilla group has said it will continue to
attack American military personnel because of U.S. support for
President Corazon Aquino's counterinsurgency campaign.
   The charges against Continente were filed with the Quezon City
prosecutor, who will determine if there is sufficient evidence to
obtain an indictment.
   Continente was employed in the business department of the
Philippine Collegian, the student newspaper of the state university.
   Friends of Continente said he was seized on the university campus
Friday by armed men who drove him away in a car.
   On Sunday, Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos ordered the military to
investigate the incident and ``effect the safe recovery (of
Continente) and apprehend the perpetrators.''
   But police Col. Victor Tiangco said early Monday that Continente
had been arrested by agents of the military's Criminal Investigation
Service.
   At the news conference Continente said he joined the communist
rebels in 1985 and was a member of the political assassination team
of the Alex Boncayao Brigade, the Manila wing of the New People's
Army.
   He described the assassination team as an ``experimental unit''
organized in October to target diplomats and foreigners involved in
the counterinsurgency campaign.
   ``My role had been in surveillance, but I did not have any
knowledge of the actual killing (of Rowe),'' Continente said.
   Rowe's killing was the second attack by the rebels on U.S.
personnel since Mrs. Aquino took office three years ago.
   In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino
civilian in coordinated ambushes outside the U.S.-run Clark Air Base
north of Manila.
   On Saturday, rebels in central Luzon renewed warnings that they
will attack American personnel stationed at the six U.S. military
bases in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
