<FIRST>r i AM-Dominican-Strike     06-19 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dominican-Strike,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Shoot at Striking Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wrier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and police
fired bullets and tear gas to disperse protesters Monday at the
start of a two-day general strike for higher wages and better
services.
   Two youths were wounded by gunfire, but the circumstances of the
shootings were unclear, police said. They said they arrested at
least 50 people.
   President Joaquin Balaguer met with Roman Catholic Church
officials trying to mediate with strikers. Neither side commented
afterwards.
   Most stores were closed, and bus services halted, leaving the
streets of the usually bustling capital of 1.6 million people nearly
deserted.
   Banks and government offices were open under police and military
guard, but most government employees stayed home to support the
unions and student, professional and neighborhood groups that called
the strike.
   Protesters in poor northwestern neighborhoods of Santo Domingo
set ablaze a truck and fruit stand, and threw up barricades of
burning tires and debris.
   Security forces said they fired tear gas to break up gangs of
protesters roving the city.
   The 48-hour strike was called to press the government over rising
costs and deteriorating living conditions in this impoverished
Caribbean nation of 6.5 million people.
   Annual inflation is running at 60 percent, and the country is
plagued by electrical blackouts and water shortages.
   The protesters are demanding better services, price stabilization
and a doubling of salaries of government workers who earn an average
$68 a month.
</TEXT>
