<HEAD>Actor William Hurt Denies He Ever Considered Dancer His Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY35, NY37</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor William Hurt testified Monday he never told
his former live-in lover, the mother of his son, that he considered
her his wife, but she contended that he told her they had ``a
spiritual marriage.''
   Hurt, 39, said he told Sandra Jennings after they started living
together in 1981 that he was put off marriage by ``the pain of it
not working out with Mary Beth'' _ his wife, actress Mary Beth Hurt,
who divorced him.
   Jennings, 32, a former ballerina with the New York City Ballet,
contends a common-law marriage exists between her and Hurt because
of their three-year relationship. She is trying to ``divorce'' him
and get half of everything he has earned since Dec. 9, 1982, when he
learned his divorce from Ms. Hurt was final.
   In March, Hurt married Heidi Henderson, daughter of bandleader
Skitch Henderson. Jennings' lawyer, A. Richard Golub, claims that
made Hurt a bigamist.
   Jennings, who left Hurt in 1984, is basing her claim on the four
weeks she lived with the actor in Beaufort, S.C., from Dec. 9, 1982,
to Jan. 10, 1983, while he was filming ``The Big Chill.'' South
Carolina recognizes common-law marriages, while New York, where they
lived most of the time, does not.
   Hurt, whom Jennings' lawyer estimates is worth about $itual marriage,''
Jennings said when
the trial broke for lunch. ``he told me we were married in the eyes
of God.''
   She said Hurt told her he considered their type of union more
sacrosanct than a legal union, and that he introduced her to others
as his wife.
   Jennings said she gave birth to Alexander Devon Hurt, now 6,
because she thought her relationship with Hurt was permanent. Hurt
has been paying $65,000 a year in child support, his publicist says.
   In court papers, Jennings said she left Hurt because he was
physically and verbally abusive. She claimed he once slapped her
while she held their then-5-day-old son. On another occasion, after
a drinking binge, she says, he urinated on their couch.
   ``He threw things at me, spit at me and tried to strangle me
once,'' she said during the lunch break.
   Under questioning, Hurt insisted he never referred to Jennings as
Mrs. Hurt and never called her his wife.
   Golub produced a medical form from Hurt's union that the actor
acknowledged was filled out in his handwriting. On it, he had
checked the box which designated Jennings as his spouse.
   On the line which said ``marital status,'' Hurt had written
``mated.'' The actor defined mated as ``two members of the same
species and their progeny.''
   Hurt, however, said the issue of common-law marriage ``never
entered my mind.''
