<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-737Engines     06-19 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-737 Engines,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Wait to Hear What Went Wrong With 737-400 Engines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen Boeing 737-400 jetliners operated by
British airlines remained grounded Monday while investigators
studied what caused some of their engines to crack.
   ``We are waiting to see what investigators find out at the
factory,'' Anne Noonan, spokesman for Britain's Civil Aviation
Authority, told The Seattle Times in a telephone interview from
England.
   The engines are manufactured by CFM International, a joint
venture of America's General Electric and Snecma, of France. Two of
the CFM56-3C engines were sent to Snecma's factory near Paris last
week for investigators to look at.
   Britain grounded the 737-400s after planes operated by British
Midland Airways and DanAir made emergency landings when fan blades
broke in their engines.
   Boeing and CFM International last Tuesday recommended that
airlines operating planes with such engines ground the aircraft
until the engines could be replaced, or until they were adjusted to
operate at lower thrust levels.
   The Federal Aviation Administration issued a similar order the
next day for U.S. airlines. The only U.S. planes affected were five
operated by USAir, and those planes have been given new engines. The
28 other affected 737-400s are operated overseas.
   The -3C engines are rated to operate at 23,500 pounds of thrust.
A similar engine, the CFM56-3B, operates at 22,000 pounds of thrust,
and the FAA said there have been no engine failures at that level in
more than 6 million hours of flight.
   On Friday, Britain's CAA confirmed a Times of London report that
cracking had been found in the engines as well as in the fan blades.
Noonan said the new cracking was found on an engine of a British
Midland plane not involved in the in-flight incidents that prompted
the original grounding.
   Boeing spokesman Craig Martin said any new 737-400s delivered to
airlines with -3C engines would have the engines adjusted to 22,000
pounds of thrust before the planes leave Boeing assembly plants near
Seattle.
   Other foreign carriers that operate the affected 737-400s are
Icelandair, Hapag Lloyd of Germany, Asiana of South Korea, Braaten
of Norway, Nortjet of Spain, and Istanbul of Turkey, Martin said.
   Fixes have been made on many of those planes, and they have
returned to service, Martin said.
   A British Midland 737-400 crashed after developing engine
problems in January, killing 47 people. No cause has been determined
for that accident, in which investigators said the pilot reported
problems in one engine but mistakenly shut down the other engine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
