<FIRST>r a AM-DruggedGambler     06-19 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugged Gambler,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gambler Claims Casino Used Drugs, Alcohol to Coerce Him to Gamble</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Shmuel cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-roller who contends he lost more than
$200,000 in a two-week spree at an Atlantic City casino was plied
with drugs and alcohol that left him reeling while he placed bets,
his attorney claimed Monday.
   ``He was without his senses,'' attorney Steven Goldman said
during opening arguments in a lawsuit filed by his client, Shmuel
Aboud, 44, of New York. ``He was literally unconscious at the table
several times.''
   The Golden Nugget Casino filed a lawsuit in 1985 against Aboud
seeking payment of gambling debts totaling $27,000 that Aboud
amassed at the casino in February 1985.
   ``Mr. Aboud is using the litigation process ... in an attempt to
avoid a just debt that he incurred,'' said Stephen N. Dratch, an
attorney for the casino. ``Mr. Aboud wanted to be at the Golden
Nugget.''
   But Aboud, an Israeli citizen, filed a counterclaim against the
casino. He said he was ``deprived of his reason and understanding''
after the casino ``fraudulently, intentionally and maliciously''
offered him alcoholic beverages while he gambled at a blackjack
table.
   At the time, Aboud was taking Percodan, a pain-killer prescribed
by two physicians called by the casino to Aboud's hotel room after
he complained of back pains sustained in a 1977 car accident,
Goldman said.
   ``They were offering him cognacs and drinks to wash it down,''
Goldman argued before U.S. District Court Judge Mitchell Cohen.
   Goldman said Aboud suffered from intoxication ``to the point of
unconsciousness,'' but casino officials pressured him to continue to
gamble.
   ``You're not going to hear tales of drowsiness. You're to hear a
tale of unconsciousness,'' Goldman said as Aboud, a short, balding
man, sat tensely behind him, occasionally biting his lip.
   Attorneys involved in the trial, which is expected to last about
a week, say the outcome could set a precedent for the state's casino
industry.
   ``It would open the door to an exorbitant amount of fraudulent
claims by patrons who lose,'' said Steven Horne, who also represents
the Golden Nugget. ``It would turn the casino industry on its head.''
   Goldman said Aboud lost more than $200,000 during his stay in a
$1,000-a-day, complimentary hotel room supplied by the casino. Aboud
had recently received a $395,000 insurance settlement from the car
accident, the attorney said.
   ``This case is about a fishing expedition,'' Goldman told the
eight jurors hearing the civil case. ``They hooked him and they
didn't let him go until they took every penny from him.''
   Dratch said Aboud only lost about $72,000 during the spree and
netted winnings of about $70,000. He said Aboud took advantage of
complimentary offers provided by the casino and requested that he be
flown home to New York to withdraw funds from his bank accounts.
   ``He wants this jury to deal him a better hand than he could
obtain on his own,'' Dratch said. ``His defense is frivolous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
