<FIRST>u i AM-Palme 1stLd-Writethru a0621 06-19 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widow of Swedish Leader Identifies Assassination Suspect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with statements from defense attorney,
details; edits to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENE MURDOCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Prime Minister Olof Palme
pointed her finger at defendant Christer Pettersson on Monday and
identified him as the man confronting her husband the instant he was
assassinated.
   ``I'm absolutely certain,'' Lisbeth Palme told the hushed
courtroom when asked if Pettersson was the man she saw a few feet
away as Palme crumpled to the street with a fatal bullet wound.
   Palme, the leading figure in Swedish politics for more than a
decade, was shot and killed Feb. 28, 1986, as he and Mrs. Palme were
leaving a late movie downtown. Mrs. Palme was slightly wounded.
   Pettersson has declared his innocence.
   Mrs. Palme said she clearly saw Pettersson's face but didn't look
at his hands to see if he had a gun.
   An autopsy report said Palme was shot from a distance of about
eight inches, and investigators said only Palme, his wife and the
killer were in the immediate vicinity.
   Mrs. Palme's testimony was a breakthrough for the prosecution,
which had suffered repeated setbacks since the trial began two weeks
ago. Several witnesses had backed away from earlier statements
implicating Pettersson.
   Pettersson, 42, was arrested in December. He has a long criminal
record, which includes a conviction for manslaughter, and a history
of drug and alcohol abuse.
   ``It will be difficult to let him go after this. If the court
lets him off, they will have to justify their decision,'' said Clas
Borgstom, a criminal lawyer not directly involved with the case, in
an interview with Swedish Radio.
   Defense attorney Arne Liljeros told a news conference after the
hearing that his client felt ``distressed'' after Mrs. Palme's
testimony.
   He did not discuss Mrs. Palme's statement that she did not see a
gun, but indicated he would concentrate his defense on how the
suspect was identified during the investigation and the time that
has passed since the killing. He was asked if he considered Mrs.
Palme's testimony reliable and replied, ``I will return to that.''
   Liljeros said his client ``maintains his position (of innocence)
in all ways.''
   Mrs. Palme, who came into the courtroom supported by her son,
Joachim, walked sideways to hide her face from the 60 reporters in
the room.
   She had said she would testify on condition that no taped record
be made of the session, that it not be broadcast, and that reporters
be excluded from the courtroom. The court agreed to the first two
conditions but allowed the press inside.
   She also had asked that Pettersson not be present during her
testimony. He was not in the room while she testified but was
brought in after a short recess and Mrs. Palme was still on the
stand.
   Prosecutor Anders Helin asked if she could identify the man she
saw seconds after her husband had been shot. Mrs. Palme pointed at
the defendant, sitting 30 feet away.
   ``I'm certain,'' she said.
   ``If Olof Palme in his heaven could have heard this, he wouldn't
have liked it,'' said Pettersson, breaking in over the objections of
Judge Carl-Anton Spak. ``If you believe in what you're saying, it's
OK. But otherwise, it's not,'' Pettersson added before guards took
him from the room.
   Mrs. Palme made no reply.
   Under cross-examination, Mrs. Palme admitted she was uncertain
about details of the killer's clothing on the night of the slaying.
But she stressed several times that his face was lit by streetlights
and that she had seen it clearly.
   ``I'm trained in my job to observe things,'' said Mrs. Palme, a
psychologist by training.
   ``My state of shock made me even more observant,'' she said.
``That's why I remember his face so clearly.''
   During police interrogations she has repeatedly refered to
Pettersson's eyes as ``piercing and unforgettable.''
   Mrs. Palme also lashed out at the news media on the stand, saying
they had ``tried their best to destroy the investigation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0168 </DOCNO>
