<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0642 06-19 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0642,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Promises `Iron Fist' in Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with settler violence, military appointments.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARIEL, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
responded Monday to the stabbing death of a U.S.-born settler by
promising to smash violence in the occupied territories with an
``iron fist.''
   Hundreds of settlers demonstrated in Jerusalem, Tel Aviv and the
West Bank after the weekend slaying of Frederick Steven Rosenfeld, a
former U.S. Marine.
   ``How many Jews have to die before something is done?'' some
chanted.
   Late Monday, settlers in 50 cars drove to a road junction near
Ariel, in the West Bank near Nablus, and threw rocks at Arab-owned
vehicles, smashing windshields, Israel radio reported.
   The settlers demanded the government take harsher measures to
quell the 18-month Palestinian uprising in which 524 Palestinians
and 23 Israelis, including Rosenfeld, have died.
   Shamir called the death ``another link in the chain of blood of
violent actions carried out against us ... by murderers and rioters
who believe that by these actions they will put an end to our
settlement and our existence.''
   ``Israel's security forces will uproot this violence with an iron
fist.''
   Shamir did not elaborate.
   Israel's military command said Monday it will extend the closing
of West Bank schools for another month, ignoring pleas from the
United States and human rights groups.
   The 1,194 schools have been closed for all but a few weeks since
Feb. 3, 1988, affecting 320,000 pupils. Israel says the schools,
including 145 kindergartens, are rallying points for rioters.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, Arab doctors said troops wounded 12
Palestinians in clashes Monday at three refugee camps, including a
15-year-old girl shot in the head. The army said it knew nothing of
the shootings.
   In Jerusalem, 80 Jewish settlers blocked the entrance to
Parliament to protest Rosenfeld's slaying. Fistfights broke out when
guards ordered the protesters to disperse, army radio said.
   West Bank police commander Chaim Malka said police suspect
Palestinians in the killing, but are investigating all possibilities.
   Palestinian shepherds found Rosenfeld's body Sunday on a hill
between the Arab villages of Salfit and Burkin, said Avivi Shalom,
security chief at Ariel settlement, in an interview.
   Rosenfeld, 48, had been missing since Friday night. He liked
hiking and apparently walked to the barren area from Ariel, Shalom
said.
   ``It seems as though the assailants surprised him and hit him on
the head,'' Shalom said. He said Rosenfeld's empty pistol holster,
map, binoculars and two spent cartridges were found near the body.
   The Maariv daily said it appeared the settler fired in the
direction of the assailants.
   Ariel officials said Rosenfeld was a former resident of
Washington and emigrated to Israel in 1968. He fought in Israel's
army and edited technical manuals in Tel Aviv before becoming a
settler 18 months ago.
   Shamir is under increasing pressure from hawks in his right-wing
Likud bloc to lay aside his plan for elections in the occupied lands
and first put down the revolt.
   ``I don't see any peace process unless terror and violence will
be stopped by Israel,'' Trade Minister Ariel Sharon said Monday on
Israel Radio.
   About 200 protesting settlers honked their horns at 3 a.m.
outside the Tel Aviv home of Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin,
chanting ``Rabin, resign!''
   An additional 150 settlers converged on Ariel
   Rabin on Monday appointed Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, a tough
paratroop officer, as commander of troops in the West Bank.
Mordechai, now chief of the army's southern command, has been in
charge of the Gaza Strip during the rebellion.
   He replaces central command head Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, who has
been responsible for the West Bank and now will go on study leave.
   Mitzna has been under fire by right-wing politicians and by
Jewish settlers for what they termed a liberal attitude toward the
uprising.
   The army said Maj. Gen. Matan Vilnai, now in charge of army
personnel, will succeed Mordechai as southern command chief.
</TEXT>
