<FIRST>u i AM-Greece-Mitsotakis     06-19 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Mitsotakis,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Leader Succeeds Only in Part</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ATH8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative opposition leader Constantine
Mitsotakis twice has tried to unseat an old foe.
   He failed in 1985, when Premier Andreas Papandreou's Panhellenic
Socialist Movement handily defeated him in national elections.
   And he achieved only partial success Sunday, defeating Papandreou
but failing to garner enough votes to win the post he coveted for so
long.
   Mitsotakis, a lawyer, immediately took the offensive Monday,
using the skills as a party infighter and strategist that have
earned him a reputation as an effective parliamentarian.
   He appealed to the Coalition of the Left and Progress to join him
in an interim government to punish the officials responsible for
scandals that led to the resignation or firing of eight Cabinet
members.
   The worst is a $20 million scandal involving the collapse of the
Bank of Crete. Mitsotakis has contended Papandreou is responsible,
but the premier denies wrongdoing.
   Before the election, Mitsotakis had said he would not accept
support from the Communists, the coalition partner of the Greek Left
Party.
   But that was to form a government. This, he says, would be a
brief partnership to deal with the ``catharsis'' or cleansing of the
government.
   ``He's very tolerant. He'll listen to anything and not reject it
before giving it a good amount of thought,'' his 21-year-old son,
Kyriakos, said in a recent interview.
   But Mitsotakis' appeal also demonstrates his political savvy:
acting to offer a temporary solution before Papandreou and his
Socialists can forge a more lasting alliance with the coalition.
   In contrast to the charismatic Papandreou, who rarely attended
parliamentary debates, Mitsotakis has shown more talent in the
300-seat, single-chamber body than as a speaker exciting crowds from
a podium.
   He was elected to lead the New Democracy party in 1984 because
conservatives felt he was the only man capable of dealing with
Papandreou.
   His personal feud with Papandreou dates back to the 1960s, when
both men were members of the Center Union party led by George
Papandreou, Andreas' father.
   Papandreou accuses Mitsotakis of being involved in political
intrigues that led to the collapse of the Center Union government
and triggered the 1967-1974 military dictatorship.
   During the junta, Mitsotakis fled to exile in Paris.
   Eventually, he joined the New Democrats and held the foreign and
economic portfolios in the 1974-81 governments.
   His political career began when he was elected to Parliament in
1946 at the age of 28 in his native Chania, on Crete.
   He was known on the island as a resistance fighter and organizer
who twice was sentenced to death by the Nazis.
</TEXT>
