<FIRST>u i AM-Greece-Papandreou     06-19 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Papandreou,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Loses Election, But He Could Keep Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Greece, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou may have lost
his bid for a third term, but it's too early to write off the man
who brought Greece's first socialist government to power.
   ``The people punished the thieves,'' trumpeted the mass
circulation newspaper Apogevmatini, referring to financial scandals
that triggered the dismissals and resignations of eight members of
Papandreou's Cabinet.
   But despite opposition charges he was involved in the corruption,
the charismatic premier attracted 39 percent of the vote and could
retain office to lead a coalition government.
   ``I am used to opposition ... I revel in it,'' Papandreou, 70,
joked before Sunday's election, referring to the 1974-81 period his
party spent in the opposition.
   The center-right New Democracy party of Constantine Mitsotakis
got 45 percent of the vote, but failed to win a parliamentary
majority. That raises prospects of a coalition or new elections.
   ``The progressive forces have a majority in Parliament. ... We
remain on the battlements with optimism and certainty of final
outcome,'' Papandreou said Monday when he conceded Mitsotakis would
finish ahead of him.
   The former U.S. economics professor brought Greece's first
socialist government to power in 1981 with promises of a welfare
state and calls to close U.S. military bases in Greece and withdraw
from NATO and the European Economic Community.
   Reality softened his hard-line stance, and an ailing economy
forced his government to implement conservative monetary policies.
   Greece remained in NATO, became a staunch European Community
supporter and signed an agreement to keep U.S. bases.
   The last six months of his second four-year term were marred by
allegations of widespread corruption, multimillion-dollar scandals,
a messy divorce from his American-born wife, Margaret, and his open
affair with a woman half his age.
   Papandreou was born on the Aegean Sea island of Chios. He studied
law at Athens University and emigrated to the United States in 1939
after a military regime expelled him because of his leftist leanings.
   He remained an American citizen for more than 20 years and served
in the U.S. Navy in World War II.
   Papandreou obtained a doctorate of philosophy in economics from
Harvard, taught at several universities and was professor of
economics at the University of California at Berkeley.
   His political career began in 1959 when he returned to Greece and
renounced U.S. citizenship. He first was elected to Parliament in
1964 as a deputy on the ticket of his father's center party, former
Greek Prime Minister George Papandreou's Union Party.
   The younger Papandreou served as a Cabinet minister and deputy
minister in 1964 and 1965.
   He was expelled a second time by a military dictatorship that
ruled from 1967 until democracy was restored in 1974. Papandreou
founded his socialist party in 1974.
</TEXT>
