<HEAD>BBC Reporter Says She Was Hit by Bullet in Beijing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BBC journalist Kate Adie said Monday she was grazed
by a bullet that killed a man next to her as she watched Chinese
troops crush pro-democracy student protests in Beijing this month.
   ``I was hit by a bullet on my arm. It killed a man in front of
me. I fell over his corpse,'' Miss Adie said on British Broadcasting
Corp. TV after returning to Britain.
   ``I did not know what to do. I crawled out with a (film) cassette
I foolishly had with me of our coverage that night, and ran for my
life.''
   Asked if she was frightened by killings in central Beijing's
Tiananmen Square, she said: ``Panic-stricken at one point.''
   Miss Adie said she was ``roughed up'' by soldiers during the June
3-4 violence as she carried the film back to her hotel.
   The BBC said Monday that BBC Asian correspondent Brian Barron and
his television crew will be allowed to leave China, one week after
they were arrested and their passports seized.
   ``All the documents have been returned and we are expecting them
back on the first available plane,'' said a BBC spokesman, speaking
anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   He said Barron ``has been told he can return to China.''
