<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms, From The Gulf To The Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms spread across the South and north to
the Great Lakes on Monday, with heavy rain causing flooding in
Alabama, and temperatures reached record highs across the western
Plains.
   Afternoon showers and thunderstorms extended from northwestern
Florida across southeastern Louisiana and north into Wisconsin,
Lower Michigan, Indiana and Ohio. Showers and thunderstorms also
were scattered over southern Florida and western Texas.
   A storm poured rain on eastern Alabama at a rate of more than 1
inch an hour, sending creeks across rural roads and forcing
officials to open flood gates on the Lake Martin reservoir on the
Tallapoosa River for the first time since 1984.
   Some roads were washed out, state police reported.
   Lightning during the storm sparked minor fires at two houses in
Dadeville, which received 6 inches of rain, the National Weather
Service said. Montgomery got 1.85 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT.
   In Houston County, authorities said high wind downed trees and
power lines at Cottonwood and in the community of Webb.
   In Florida, }-inch-diameter hail fell northeast of Tallahassee
and wind gusted to 76 mph at the Tallahassee airport.
   Thunderstorm wind gusts caused damage near Whitmire, S.C., at
Webb and Cottonwood, Ala., and near Sharon, Ga., the weather service
said.
   Locally heavy rain also fell in the central Lower Michigan
counties of Isabella and Montcalm, with as much as 2.61 inches at
Blanchard during a four-hour period, the weather service said.
   Elsewhere, showers developed over the northern Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures reached 90 degrees and hotter by early afternoon
from Minnesota across North Dakota.
   Across the western Plains, reports of record highs included 94 at
Colorado Springs, Colo.; 98 at Denver, and 102 at Scottsbluff, Neb.
Denver's previous record of 96 had stood since 1880.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees at Seattle to 110 at Tucson, Ariz. Monday's low temperature
for the Lower 48 states was 37 degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from New
York state across southern New England, and from New Jersey and
Pennsylvania across Florida, Alabama, southeastern Mississippi and
southeastern Louisiana. Showers were forecast along the northern
Pacific Coast.
   Highs were predicted in the 60s from western Montana across the
northern Pacific Coast; near 90 over the Mississippi Valley and
North Dakota; in the 90s in Florida, from South Dakota across Texas,
from much of Wyoming across New Mexico, and in the central section
of southern California; 100 degrees and hotter from inland
south-central Texas across western Texas and the Texas Panhandle;
from 100 to near 120 from southern and western Arizona across
southeastern California and southern Nevada. Temperatures were
expected generally in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the
nation.
