<FIRST>r w AM-BoatFatalities     06-19 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat Fatalities,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boating Fatalities Reach Record Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recreation boating fatalities continued a
steady decline in 1988 to a record low of 946 deaths while the
number of registered boats increased, the Transportation Department
said.
   Coast Guard Capt. Bill Griswold, the service's top boating safety
officer, attributed the decline to increased awareness of the danger
of drinking while boating.
   Fatalities declined to 946 in 1988 from 1,036 in 1987, 1,066 in
1986 and 1,116 in 1985, the department said. The 1988 figure, which
amounted to 5.5 deaths per 100,000 boats, was the lowest since the
Coast Guard began keeping track of boating fatalities 28 years ago.
   The Coast Guard estimates that there were 17.3 million boats on
the nation's waterways in 1988, an increase of 400,000 over the
previous year.
   Griswold said about 50 percent of boating accidents are linked to
alcohol use. Alcohol is also a factor in about half the traffic
fatalities on the nation's highways.
   The number of injuries in boating accidents decreased only
slightly, from 3,501 in 1987 to 3,476 last year. The number of
accidents was at 6,746 in 1987 and 6,718 last year.
   Property damage in boating accidents reached $24.33 million last
year, about $3 million more than the year before, the department
said.
</TEXT>
