<DOCNO> AP890619-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Architects-Copyright     06-19 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Architects-Copyright,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copyright Protection Sought for Architecture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Copyright Office recommended Monday
that the same copyright protections guaranteed by other nations for
their architects' creations be extended to works of architecture in
the United States.
   U.S. copyright law prohibits unauthorized copying of
architectural plans, sketches and models but does not prevent
``copycat'' construction of actual buildings.
   The law includes buildings in the same legal category of such
``useful articles'' as alarm clocks, toasters and automobiles, which
are not afforded copyright protection.
   The Copyright Office of the Library of Congress on Monday
published a lengthy report of a 14-month study of the issue,
conducted at the request of Rep. Robert W. Kastenmeier, D-Wis., and
Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
   Kastenmeier, who received the report at a news conference at the
Library of Congress, said he soon would introduce proposed
legislation aimed at assuring that ``the best of American creativity
is respected and protected.'' He gave no details.
   In a move intended to hasten a government decision, the Frank
Lloyd Wright Foundation submitted copyright applications for two
buildings designed by the late architect, the Guggenheim Museum in
New York City and Beth Shalom Synagogue in Elkins Park, Pa., a
Philadelphia suburb.
   The American Institute of Architects endorsed the Copyright
Office's view that federal law needs to be made ``more clearly
consistent with the Berne Convention,'' the world copyright treaty
which the United States joined on March l.
   Under that treaty, virtually every other signatory nation
guarantees copyright protection to works of architecture, but
legislation passed by Congress last year providing for U.S.
adherence to the treaty failed to provide similar guarantees for
American architects. Instead, the U.S. Copyright Office was asked to
study the issue and make recommendations.
   The Copyright Office report did not recommend specific action but
outlined several options. One would be to amend federal law to
exclude unique architectural structures from the ``useful article''
exemption, thus allowing copyright protection for certain
exceptional buildings but not, for instance, tract housing.
   The AIA said current law has proved only partially effective in
helping resolve an increasing number of lawsuits challenging
unauthorized construction of look-alike buildings using pirated
copyright plans.
   Ralph Oman, the register of copyrights, said his office would
decide in a few months whether to register the two buildings
designed by Frank Lloyd Wright. He indicated that the limitations of
existing law would influence the decision, but said a decision would
be delayed if a consensus developed in Congress to amend the law to
extend copyright protection to architectural works.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Floods     06-19 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Floods,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monsoon Mudslides Kill 16, Leave Thousands Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Incorporates AM-Bangladesh-Floods, a0606</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mudslides caused by rivers swollen in the
summer monsoon killed 16 people and left thousands homeless in a
remote, hilly state, news reports said Monday.
   United News of India said 10 people and four soldiers were buried
in landslides Thursday in West Kameng district of Arunachal Pradesh
state, about 900 miles east of New Delhi.
   Two people died Friday in the neighboring Bomdilla district in
floods caused by heavy rains since the monsoon came earlier this
month, the news agency said.
   It said the homeless are being cared for in relief camps in
Arunachal Pradesh and nearby Assam state, where the Brahmaputra
River had topped the danger mark.
   In neighboring Bangladesh, the River Gumti spilled over its
embankment and swept away thousands of mud-and-straw huts in about
100 villages, officials said Monday.
   About 50,000 people were left homeless, they said.
   The deluge inundated several thousand acres of crops in the
district, 55 miles southeast of Dhaka, according to a provincial
official who arrived in the capital Monday.
   Many people were marooned on roofs of houses and hundreds are
camped on roads and along unbroken portions of the embankment while
rain continued Monday, he said.
   Bangladesh, a low-lying country, is crossed by hundreds of rivers
that form the deltas of the Brahmaputra and the Ganges, the two
major rivers of the Indian subcontinent.
   Officials said Monday the two rivers will keep rising in the next
24 hours.
   Floods triggered by the summer monsoon are a seasonal disaster in
India, Nepal and Bangladesh.
   Last year, floods inundated about four-fifths of Bangladesh and
at least 1,400 people were killed. At least 2.3 million people were
left homeless.
</TEXT>
