<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Plane 1stLd-Writethru a0644 06-19 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Struggle Led to Crash of Afghan Jetliner; 6 Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT that co-pilot shot in shoulder,
not eye; UPDATES with IRNA reporting dispute, miners rescued survivors,
details on victims, one suffered fatal heart attack. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A struggle between the co-pilot and an
armed security guard caused an Afghan airliner to crash in eastern
Iran with the loss of six lives, Tehran radio said Monday.
   The broadcast quoted Deputy Prime Minister Ali Reza Moayyeri as
denying earlier Iranian and Afghan reports the plane was hijacked.
   In Kabul, Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani
said the plane was hijacked by two gunmen who forced it to fly into
Iranian airspace.
   Moayyeri, heading an official investigation into Sunday's crash
outside the city of Zabol near the southern Afghan border, said the
plane was carrying 39 people. He said it crashed near a mine and
that miners ran to the site and rescued the 33 injured survivors
from the wreckage.
   Moayyer said the guard, who was not identified, had a
long-standing dispute with Khayr Mohammed Sadar Khayl, 26, the
co-pilot of the Ariana Afghan Airlines turbo-prop plane.
   The guard entered the cockpit, closed the door and during an
argument he shot the co-pilot in the shoulder, according to Moayyer.
He said the guard then opened the door to return to the cabin.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said the dispute involved an
incident when the co-pilot had refused to take on board a cargo
shipment that had arrived late.
   IRNA said the guard went into the cockpit with a passenger
identified only as Dr. Bashir and the shooting followed.
   The Soviet-built An-26 was flying from Kabul, the Afghan capital,
to the southern city of Zaranj when it entered Iranian airspace and
crashed in the desert, Tehran radio said in a dispatch monitored in
Cyprus.
   State-run Iranian TV showed film of the wrecked twin-engine plane
that apparently buckled as it hit the ground and split apart.
   Moayyeri said the difference in air pressure as the cabin door
swung open caused the pilot, Mir Weis Hajai, to lose control of the
plane.
   He said Hajai, 50, was not certified to fly the Antonov, a
short-haul aircraft adapted from a military transport. He said a
qualified pilot could have landed safely at Zabol.
   The plane went down 15 miles from Zabol, 700 miles southeast of
Tehran in Sistan-Baluchistan province.
   Four people died on impact and two others died in Zabol hospital
from ``severe injuries and advanced age,'' Tehran radio quoted
Moayyeri as saying.
   IRNA said three men and one woman were killed in the crash and
two elderly passenger died in a hospsital, one from injuries and the
other from a heart attack.
   On Sunday IRNA had identified the pilot as Mirvis Paktia.
   The control towers at Zabol and the provincial capital, Zahedan,
100 miles to the south, prepared for an emergency landing when the
plane entered Iranian airspace around midday Sunday, according to
Tehran radio.
   But they did not monitor a distress call from the pilot, it added.
   In Kabul, Nabi said earlier Monday that the plane had been
hijacked and people held hostage, but later said Iranian officials
reported there were no hostages.
   He and IRNA said an Afghan delegation left for Zabol on Monday to
investigate the crash and arrange for returning the casualties and
the dead to Afghanistan.
   Afghanistan and Iran do not have diplomatic relations, but
maintain missions in each other's capitals.
   Iran supports Moslem guerrillas in Afghanistan who have been
fighting the Soviet-backed Kabul government for 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
