<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Britain     06-19 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Britain,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Told Hong Kong Needs Calming</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official said Monday Britain will have
trouble governing Hong Kong if it does not calm anxieties over the
colony's reversion to Chinese rule in 1997 by giving people here the
right to live in Britain.
   Lydia Dunn, a member of the Executive Council (Cabinet), spoke
before she left to try to persuade London to change its mind on the
issue. She and Allen Lee, of the Legislative Council, will meet with
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey
Howe and members of Parliament.
   Mrs. Thatcher told Hong Kong Gov. David Wilson in talks this
month that giving right of residence to the 3.25 million British
passport holders in Hong Kong was politically impossible. British
news reports said up to 250,000 people may be accepted, mostly
current and retired civil servants.
   Hong Kong's 5.5 million people have been alarmed about their fate
when China regains control over the island when Britain's lease
expires in 1997. They intensified demands for right of resettlement
after the June 3-4 bloodshed in Beijing and China's crackdown on the
pro-democracy movement through mass arrests and intimidation.
   Hong Kong natives are entitled to British passports, but the
passports do not allow them to live in Britain.
   ``Without the commitment of the people and their confidence in
staying here, investing here or working here, then Hong Kong becomes
vulnerable. ... This is the case we will be presenting,'' Mrs. Dunn
told a news conference.
   ``I would say it would be very difficult for the British
administration to run this place, (a) population who are not only
anxious about the future but resentful of being deprived of the one
thing which would give them an assurance and which is entirely in
the power of the British government,'' she said.
   She said Britain need not fear a mass influx.
   ``What we're trying to impress on people is that ... people do
not wish to leave Hong Kong. This is our home.
   ``To stay, our anxieties must be allayed. Our anxieties can only
be allayed if there is an assurance that there is a right of abode
in Britain if things do not work out.''
   She said Britain had ``a moral obligation and a constitutional
responsibility'' to grant this.
   A large majority of Hong Kong people responding to recent polls
believe Britain should give the passport holders the right of
resettlement, the Inrasia Pacific Ltd. polling organization said
Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
