<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     06-19 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Win Right to Challenge British Blasphemy Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Moslem group seeking to prosecute writer Salman
Rushdie won the right on Monday to challenge a court ruling that
Britain's blasphemy laws apply only to Christianity.
   The Moslem Action Group, which represents Moslems throughout
Britain, wants to bring Rushdie and Viking Penguin Publishers to
trial under blasphemy laws for his novel, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``We will now seek to show that any religion, including Islam,
can be included in the offense of blasphemy,'' said Ali Azhar, a
lawyer for Moslem Action.
   Many Moslems believe the book blasphemes Islam, but Rushdie
maintains it does not. The British author, born of Moslem parents in
India, has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when the late Iranian
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini decreed he should die because of
his book.
   High Court Justice Michael Nolan granted Abdal Choudhury, a
spokesman for Moslem Action, permission to challenge the Bow Street
Magistrates Court's refusal to issue summonses on the grounds that
the laws of blasphemy applied only to Christians.
   Nolan decided a full hearing should be by three High Court
judges. No date was set.
   David Pannick, lawyer for Viking Penguin, opposed the application
for High Court review of the magistrate's decision. Rushdie was not
personally represented in court.
   Azhar said Moslem Action now will be seeking the whereabouts of
Rushdie to serve him with legal documents. Lawyers might request the
court's help in locating Rushdie, he said.
   Nolan said an application for assistance could be made, but he
did not indicate what form of aid could be granted or whether
Rushdie's whereabouts would have to be revealed.
   Anti-Rushdie demonstrators cheered at a prayer meeting outside
London's Law Courts after the justice's ruling.
   Supporters waved photographs of Khomeini and banners proclaiming
``Criminal Must Be Brought to Justice'' and ``Satan Rushdie Must be
Punished.''
   Violent demonstrations have been held in several countries,
including Britain, and 19 people died in anti-Rushdie rioting in
India and Pakistan in February.
</TEXT>
