<FIRST>r a AM-LandingDelay     06-19 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landing Delay,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA's New Landing Systems Delayed Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Skinner-Controllers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A production dispute has forced the Federal
Aviation Administration to put on hold its plan for bringing a new
generation of landing systems to the nation's airports.
   The FAA installed its first microwave landing system at Lebanon
airport in a highly publicized ceremony April 6, and the Laconia and
Manchester airports were scheduled to get the state-of-the-art
system by late summer.
   However, earlier this month, the FAA took a step toward
terminating its contract with Hazeltine Corp., its prime contractor
for the system, FAA spokesman John Leyden said late last week.
   As the agency looks to other electronics firms for the new
technology, it must sell the new system to reluctant air carriers,
who say it isn't much better than the instrument landing system now
in use.
   Leyden said the FAA remains committed to an international
agreement to make the microwave system standard at airports
worldwide by 1998, and has not changed plans to equip all U.S.
airports with the new system by the year 2000.
   The system, which uses high-frequency microwaves to direct planes
to landings, is virtually immune to weather. It allows planes to
make curved and steeper approaches, which increases an airport's
flight capacity and helps planes avoid residential areas.
   The FAA contracted with Hazeltine in 1984 for 178 systems at $79
million, but the Commack, N.Y.,-based firm said the price was too
low and ``entered an unauthorized work-slowdown last August,'' said
Dick Arnold, head of the FAA's microwave landing system program.
   After nearly six months of fruitless negotiations, the FAA on
June 2 sent Hazeltine a letter saying the company's actions could
lead to termination of the contract. Hazeltine has until Thursday to
respond.
   Hazeltine officials were phoned for comment, but refused to say
anything about the issue.
   Leyden said cancelling the Hazeltine contract won't mean
scrapping the FAA's installation program. He said the agency plans
to buy 26 systems from other sources.
   But the cancellation will lead to further delays in the
installation program. Jerry Casavant, the FAA's associate program
director for the microwave landing system in New England, said it
already was at least 3{ years behind the original schedule.
   Leyden said that with installations at Laconia and Manchester put
on hold, the FAA is considering redirecting early installations to
more high-profile, high-volume airports, such as Kennedy
International in New York City.
   The three New Hampshire airports would have been part of the
first phase of planned U.S. installations, which included Boston's
Logan airport and Kennedy International.
   The idea was to equip an entire hub-and-spoke network so that the
airlines that serve those airports would see the benefit of
equipping their planes with the expensive receiving systems.
   The second phase of the FAA's plan, if approved by Congress, is
for 750 systems. That would mean complete replacement of the more
than 700 instrument landing systems in use in the nation's airports
as well as installation of microwave systems at sites unsuitable for
the old system.
   The program's delays have dampened much of the initial enthusiasm
among carriers, Casavant said.
   That's due partly to improvements in the instrument landing
system since the microwave system was first introduced. The
improvements make the instrument system less expensive and more
sophisticated, which makes the switch to the new system less
imperative, state Aeronautics Director Harold Buker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DrugTesting     06-19 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Testing,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>NLRB Issues First Decisions On Drug Testing</HEAD>
<HEAD>California, Minnesota Cases Set Precedents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private employers cannot unilaterally begin
testing union workers for drug and alcohol use but can test job
applicants regardless of whether unions object, the National Labor
Relations Board said Monday in its first decisions on the
controversial issue.
   The board, however, said that if employers test applicants for
drug and alcohol use they cannot deny unions information about those
who are offered jobs but do not accept them, including those who
refuse to submit to tests.
   In rejecting attempts by employers to unlilaterally implement
drug and alcohol testing of current workers represented by unions,
the board said testing is an issue that falls under collective
bargaining and therefore must be the subject of union-management
negotiations.
   But the board said there is no such protection for job applicants
and said employers do not need to negotiate with their unions if
they want to subject applicants to drug and alcohol testing.
   That decision, long awaited by employers and business groups,
could result in a proliferation of applicant-testing policies,
attorneys familiar with labor law said Monday.
   The precedent-setting NLRB decisions came the same day the
Supreme Court ruled that railroads may require tests for workers
without bargaining with unions over the issue. Railway and airline
workers are covered under the Railway Labor Act, not the National
Labor Relations Act that the NLRB is empowered to enforce.
   Attorneys and union officials familiar with drug testing cases
said the Supreme Court decisions would have limited impact outside
the rail and airline industries, where drug testing is common,
particularly in positions with direct impact on public safety. But
they predicted the issues in the cases decided by the NLRB on Monday
could ultimately end up before the high court.
   In the first case, involving the Johnson-Bateman Co. of Etiwanda,
Calif., the NLRB said the company violated its collective bargaining
agreement with the Machinists union when it, in December 1986,
informed employees that it would require drug and alcohol tests for
any employee injured at work.
   ``We conclude that drug (and) alcohol testing of employees who
require treatment for injuries received while on the job is a
mandatory subject of bargaining,'' the board said.
   The board ordered the company to negotiate with the union if it
wanted to adopt such a testing policy for its union-represented
production and maintenance employees.
   Attempts to reach company officials for comment were not
immediately successful. A receptionist said none of the company
owners was in the office, and the lawyer who represented the company
also was not at his office Monday afternoon.
   In the second case, the board reversed an administrative law
judge's decision that pre-employment drug and alcohol testing by the
Star Tribune of Minneapolis was an issue the newspaper needed to
negotiate with its union.
   ``We find that drug and alcohol testing of applicants for
employment is not a mandatory subject of bargaining,'' the board
said.
   John Dennison, the newspaper's vice president for labor
relations, said the Star Tribune was gratified by the decision.
   Dennison said the newspaper has received numerous inquiries about
the status of its case and speculated that ``people who had been
taking a sit back and wait approach may now go ahead'' with
applicant-testing policies.
   The board did say the newspaper violated the National Labor
Relations Act by ``refusing to furnish the union with the requested
information relating to the drug and alcohol testing of prospective
employees.''
   The board said the union, The Newspaper Guild, was entitled to
the information to monitor Star Tribune hiring practices for any
signs of discrimination.
   The union, as part of its challenge of the policy, said male
applicants were allowed to provide urine samples without being
observed while female applicants were required to give the samples
partially unclothed and in the presence of a nurse.
   The NLRB ordered the newspaper to provide the Guild with the
names, addresses and telephone numbers of all applicants to which it
conditionally offered employment in Guild-represented positions
since January 1987 and to identify all those in that group who
refused to submit to drug and alcohol screening.
   The NLRB, adopting reasonining similar to its decision in the
Johnson-Batemen case, upheld the judge's 1988 ruling that the
newspaper violated its collective bargaining agreement with the
Guild by trying to unilaterally implement a drug testing policy for
current workers in January 1987.
   Dennison said the newspaper had not enforced the policy and that
the issue was the subject of current negotiations with the Guild.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2007EST</FILEID>
