<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     06-19 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Shuffles Top Economic Posts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist government made
changes in its four top economic posts Monday, one day before
Premier Ladislav Adamec is to address Parliament on the state of the
nation's economy.
   The official CTK news agency CTK gave no reason for the changes.
   Observers said it appeared they were made in line with the
government's declared drive to boost productivity and revive the
stagnant economy.
   Czechoslovakia's relatively high standard of living has helped
the orthodox Communist leaders keep political peace since the 1968
Prague Spring reforms were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion.
   Economic problems are increasing, but the government has not
followed the Soviet Union, Hungary and Poland in adopting reforms.
   These changes were announced in the economy hierarchy:
   Karel Julis, 6O, will leave the recently created ``super
ministry'' for engineering and metallurgy to head the State
Commission for Science, Investment and Technology.
   Julis replaced Pavel Hrivnak, 58, who was nominated June 15 to be
premier of Slovakia. Hrivnak succeeded Ivan Knotek who was given the
economic portfolio in the Communist Party Central Committee.
   Ladislav Vodrazka, 57, a deputy foreign trade minister, took over
Julis' job as chief of the Engineering and Metallurgy Ministry.
   Jaromir Zak, 47, who headed State Pricing Office, became chief of
the State Planning Commission and banking official Alfred Sebek, 49,
replaced Zak in the pricing office.
   CTK said First Deputy Premier Bohumil Urban, 55, lost his post at
the planning commission but retained ministerial rank.
   Julis, at a Communist Party conference last week, presented a
gloomy report on the country's scientific and technological progress.
   ``Our economic productivity amounts to only 5O percent of
productivity in advanced industrial countries ... and the average
machine used in our industry is 18 years old,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
