<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CreditDelinquencies     06-19 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Credit Delinquencies,238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers Keeping Up With Loan Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers fell behind on their loan payments
less frequently at the end of March than three months earlier, a
trade group reported Monday.
   The American Bankers Association said the delinquency rate on
seven kinds of loans at the end of the first quarter was 2.39
percent, down from 2.49 percent at the end of December. A delinquent
loan is defined as one in which at least one payment is past due for
30 days or more.
   ``Lower delinquencies indicate that consumer balance sheets are
still reasonably strong,'' ABA Chief Economist Robert Dugger said in
a statement.
   Despite the most recent decline, the delinquency rate is still
higher than a year ago when it hit a three-year low of 2.19 percent.
   The District of Columbia reported the lowest delinquency rate,
1.16 percent, followed by South Carolina, 1.19 percent, and
Wisconsin, 1.26 percent. The highest rates were in Puerto Rico, 4.98
percent; Louisiana, 4.75 percent, and North Dakota, 4.40 percent.
   The seven types of loans included in the quarterly survey are:
personal, direct auto, indirect auto, mobile home, recreational
vehicle, property improvement and closed-end home equity.
   The lowest delinquency rate was reported on home equity loans,
which fell to 0.64 percent, down from 0.68 percent three months
earlier. The highest rate was for personal loans, which dropped from
3.34 percent in December to 3.20 percent in March.
   Americans had nearly $693 billion in consumer credit outstanding
at the end of the period.
</TEXT>
