<FIRST>r a AM-Voyager-Neptune     06-19 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Voyager-Neptune,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Hurricane-Like Storm Found On Neptune; Like Jupiter's Great
Red Spot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A giant spot roughly 6,200 miles wide has
been discovered on the planet Neptune by the Voyager 2 space probe,
and scientists said Monday it looks like a storm similar to the
Great Red Spot on Jupiter.
   ``It's huge,'' said physicist Edward Stone, Voyager project
scientist for NASA and a vice president of the California Institute
of Technology. ``It would be reasonable to suspect this is a large,
hurricane-like storm system similar to the Great Red Spot.''
   However, Stone said Voyager 2 still is too far from Neptune to
determine if winds are swirling within the gargantuan spot, which
measures about 6,200 miles in diameter. Jupiter's Great Red Spot
contains 250 mph winds.
   Scientists haven't yet named Neptune's spot, but are calling it
``the dark spot'' because it appears darker than the surrounding
blue-greenish atmosphere, he added.
   The color of the spot isn't yet known because scientists haven't
processed a complete set of pictures through different color
filters, said Andrew Ingersoll, a Caltech planetary scientist.
   Voyager 2 is hurtling at more than 42,000 mph toward its Aug. 24
close encounter with Neptune. At that time, the hardy spacecraft
will zip within 3,000 miles of the gaseous planet's cloud tops _ by
far the closest of any of Voyager's planetary flybys. Five hours
later, it will fly within 25,000 miles of Triton, one of Neptune's
two known moons.
   By Tuesday, Voyager 2 will be nearly 2.66 billion miles from
Earth and 58.98 million miles from Neptune, traveling at a speed of
42,216 mph, said Mary Beth Murrill, a spokeswoman for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   The Neptune encounter will be Voyager 2's fourth and final
planetary flyby since the probe was launched from Cape Canaveral in
1977. It explored Jupiter in 1979, Saturn in 1981 and Uranus in 1986.
   Neptune's dark spot is located at about 25 to 30 degrees latitude
in the planet's southern hemisphere, Ingersoll said, adding that
Voyager also discovered a much smaller, rapidly changing white spot
_ about half the size of the dark spot _ at about 70 degrees south
latitude.
   Stone said Neptune's dark spot first was clearly recognized in
still photographs taken by Voyager 2's television cameras in April,
and can be seen faintly in pictures taken as early as January.
   It isn't as large as Jupiter's Great Red Spot, which is 16,000
miles across at its widest point _ large enough to contain three
Earths. But the dark spot is just as large relative to Neptune _
about a fifth of the planet's diameter _ as the Great Red Spot is
relative to Jupiter.
   Jupiter's Great Red Spot was discovered more than 350 years ago.
Ingersoll said it is believed to be red because of organic
chemicals, or possibly sulfur or phosphorus, trapped within it.
   Besides the Great Red Spot, Jupiter also contains dozens of
smaller storm systems, which appear as white spots, and Saturn also
has similar storms, although they are less visible, Stone said.
   The major mystery of Jupiter's Great Red Spot is how the storm
has remained intact for centuries, while Earth's hurricanes break up
after a week or two, Ingersoll said.
   The absence of continents on giant gas planets like Jupiter and
Neptune may explain the persistence of the spots, he said, adding
that continents may help dissipate hurricanes on Earth.
   Computer simulations suggest smaller storms combine to form giant
storms such as the Red Spot and Neptune's dark spot, Stone and
Ingersoll said.
   Neptune is the solar system's fourth largest planet and usually
is the eighth planet from the sun. But because Pluto's elongated
elliptical orbit sometimes brings it closer to the sun, Neptune
currently is the ninth and most distant planet from the sun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
