<FIRST>r i AM-Iceland-US     06-19 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iceland-US,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Apologizes After in Icelandic Flags Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States apologized to Iceland
for the behavior of three U.S. soldiers who were arrested and
accused of cutting down and stealing 17 Icelandic flags, the Foreign
Ministry said Monday.
   It said the U.S. Embassy also apologized to the ambassadors of
China, Czechoslovakia and East Germany whose flags were also cut
down and stolen last Saturday, the 45th anniversary of Iceland's
independence and its national day.
   The ministry said the three newly arrived soldiers also were
charged with driving while intoxicated.
   Police said the three, who were not identified, were arrested
Saturday night near Hafnarfjoerdur, about 12 miles south of
Reykjavik, while allegedly drunk and speeding. The flags, cut from
flagpoles all over Reykjavik and some neighboring communities, were
found in their car, police said.
   ``This is an insult to Iceland,'' said Foreign Minister Jon
Baldvin Hannibalsson.
   Prime Minister Steingrimur Hermansson condemned the incident and
said, ``This is bound to affect people's attitude toward the defense
force.''
   Under the NATO treaty, the United States is responsible for
Iceland's defense and about 3,300 American servicemen based here
comprise the Iceland Defense Force.
   Hannibalsson said the three would probably be court martialed and
could face six months in jail, dishonorable discharge, and lose
their pay for a year.
   The incident follows last month's formal protest by Iceland to
the United States that a farewell speech by Rear Adm. Eric McVadon,
the U.S. military commander in Iceland, violated the U.S.-Icelandic
defense agreement and interfered in the country's internal affairs.
</TEXT>
