<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Bank     06-19 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Bank,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Brazil's Central Bank Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elmo Camoes, president of Brazil's
Central Bank, turned in his resignation Monday to President Jose
Sarne following a major stock market scandal, a bank official said.
   ``The request was informal and Camoes will deliver an official
letter of resignation on Tuesday or Wednesday,'' said the source,
who spoke on the condition he not be identified.
   He said Sarney accepted Camoes' resignation but had not decided
on a successor.
   The scandal evolved after Naji Nahas, a multimillionaire stock
market investor, bought stock worth $31 million through various
brokerage houses on June 9.
   One check for $8.8 million in local currency issued to a
brokerage house was returned for lack of funds. Trading at the stock
markets in Rio and Sao Paul, Brazil's largest, dropped sharply.
   The source said Camoes' son is the director of another brokerage
house in which Camoes has a controlling interest, and that this
house made ``a number of risky investments. The firm is in trouble
as a result of liquidity problems generated by the fall in the
market.'
   Camoes delivered a note to the news media Monday saying he would
not come to the brokerage house's rescue.
