<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Manuscripts     06-19 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Manuscripts,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illuminated Manuscripts Auctioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An illuminated 15th-century French manuscript book
sold Monday night for $2,898,500, the second-highest price ever paid
for a manuscript at auction, Sotheby's said.
   The manuscript from the collection of the late Maj. J. R. Abbey,
known as the Monypenny Breviary, was made for William Monypenny of
Ardwenny in Scotland who was an abbot in France. It was created for
him by two of the best-known French manuscript painters of the
period, a father and son named Jean and Jacquelin de Montlucon, who
worked in Bourges.
   Sotheby's spokeswoman Deste Bond said the French dealer who
bought it, a Monsieur Beres, paid the highest price for a French
manuscript. The record auction price for any manuscript was the
$12.4 million paid at Sotheby's in 1983 for the Gospels of Henry the
Lion.
   Also sold by the auction house Monday night was a manuscript
described as the last important royal English manuscript in private
hands, a book of hours, or prayerbook, made for Margaret, Duchess of
Clarence, a sister-in-law of King Henry V of England. London dealer
Sam Fogg paid $443,300, the spokeswoman said.
   It, too, was part of the collection assembled by Abbey, a
Brighton brewery owner who died in 1969. His collection of
manuscripts was so large and important that the sale by Sotheby's
has been spread over more than 20 years and divided into 11
auctions, of which this was the last.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
