<SECOND>BC-History, Adv 26,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, June 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, June 26, the 177th day of 1989. There are 188
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On June 26, 1963, President John F. Kennedy visited West Berlin,
where he was greeted by more than 1 million of the divided city's
residents. In a speech, Kennedy made his famous declaration, ``Ich
bin ein Berliner.''
   On this date:
   In 1870, the first section of Atlantic City, N.J., boardwalk was
opened to the public.
   In 1900, a commission that included Dr. Walter Reed began the
fight against the deadly disease yellow fever.
   In 1917, the first troops of the American Expeditionary Force
arrived in France during World War I.
   In 1919, the first issue of the New York Daily News was published.
   In 1945, the charter of the United Nations was signed by 50
countries in San Francisco. (The text of the charter was in five
languages: Chinese, English, French, Russian and Spanish.)
   In 1948, in response to the Soviet blockade of West Berlin, the
United States announced it would increase its daily cargo flights to
the western sector of the isolated German city.
   In 1959, President Dwight D. Eisenhower joined Britain's Queen
Elizabeth II in ceremonies officially opening the St. Lawrence
Seaway.
   In 1975, citing what she called a ``deep and widespread
conspiracy'' against her government, Indian Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi declared a state of emergency.
   In 1977, 42 people were killed when a fire, caused by an inmate
who had ignited padding material in his cell, sent toxic smoke
pouring through the Maury County Jail in Columbia, Tenn.
   In 1987, Supreme Court Justice Lewis F. Powell Jr. announced his
retirement from the nation's highest court, leaving a vacancy that
was eventually filled by Judge Anthony M. Kennedy.
   Ten years ago: Heavyweight boxing champion Muhammad Ali confirmed
to reporters that he'd sent a letter to the World Boxing Association
resigning his title, saying his third announced retirement was
indeed final.
   Five years ago: American Jewish leaders expressed outrage over
comments by Black Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan, who had described
Israel as an ``outlaw'' nation and seemed to describe Judaism as a
``gutter religion'' during a speech in Chicago two days earlier.
   One year ago: Three people were killed when a new Airbus jetliner
carrying more than 130 people crashed into a forest during an air
show demonstration flight in Mulhouse, France.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Eleanor Parker is 67. Singer Billy
Davis is 49.
   Thought for today: ``Too bad all the people who know how to run
the country are busy driving taxi cabs and cutting hair.'' _ George
Burns, American comedian (1896- ).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
