<SECOND>BC-History, Adv27,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, June 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, June 27, the 178th day of 1989. There are 187
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On June 27, 1950, President Harry S. Truman ordered the Air Force
and Navy into the Korean conflict following a call from the U.N.
Security Council for member nations to help South Korea repel an
invasion by North Korea.
   On this date:
   In 1844, Mormon leader Joseph Smith was killed by a mob in
Carthage, Ill.
   In 1847, New York and Boston were linked by telegraph wires.
   In 1880, author-lecturer Helen Keller, who lived most of her life
without sight or hearing, was born in Tuscumbia, Ala.
   In 1942, the FBI announced the capture of eight Nazi saboteurs
who had been put ashore from a submarine on New York's Long Island.
   In 1957, more than 500 people were killed when Hurricane Audrey
slammed through coastal Louisiana and Texas.
   In 1963, President John F. Kennedy spent his first full day in
Ireland, the land of his ancestors.
   In 1973, former White House counsel John W. Dean told the Senate
Watergate Committee about the existence of an ``enemies list'' kept
by the White House.
   In 1977, in a 5-4 decision, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down
state laws and bar association rules that had prohibited lawyers
from advertising the fees they charge for routine services.
   In 1982, the space shuttle Columbia roared off the launch pad at
Cape Canaveral, Fla., carrying astronauts Thomas K. Mattingly and
Henry W. Hartsfield Jr., with the shuttle's first military and
commercial payloads.
   In 1983, balloonists Maxie Anderson and Don Ida were killed
during a race when their helium-filled balloon crashed in a West
German forest.
   In 1986, the International Court of Justice at The Hague ruled
that the United States had broken international law and violated the
sovereignty of Nicaragua by aiding the contras.
   Ten years ago: In a victory for advocates of affirmative action
programs, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled employers could voluntarily
give minority workers special treatment in hiring, training and
promotion.
   Five years ago: The U.S. Supreme Court ended the National
Collegiate Athletic Association's monopoly on controlling college
football telecasts, ruling such control violated antitrust law.
   One year ago: Mike Tyson retained the undisputed heavyweight
crown as he knocked out Michael Spinks 91 seconds into the first
round of a championship fight in Atlantic City, N.J. Fifty-seven
people were killed in the collision of two trains in Paris.
   Today's birthdays: ``Captain Kangaroo,'' Bob Keeshan, is 62.
Opera singer Anna Moffo is 55.
   Thought for today: ``A little too late is much too late.'' _
German proverb.
</TEXT>
