<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--TroubledTreasurer ADV02-2Takes   06-19 0987</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Troubled Treasurer, ADV 02-2 Takes,1009</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ He's the P.T. Barnum of West Virginia politics, a
showman remembered for ridding the state of thousands of junked cars
and bringing running water to thousands of rural homes. But A. James
Manchin could lose his job as state treasurer. A state investment
firm supervised by his staff lost hundreds of millions of dollars in
the New York bond market and he faces trial by the state Senate.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A. James Manchin, West Virginia's
flamboyant state treasurer whose alliterative oratory and
distinctive dress helped make him one of the state's most popular
politicians, is in the fight of his life.
   Manchin, whose theatrics have brought him both fame and derision,
has been impeached by state House of Delegates and faces trial in
the state Senate on July 10 over the loss of hundreds of millions of
dollars from a state investment fund his office supervised.
   If two-thirds of the 34 senators vote against him, the
62-year-old former high school coach will be removed from office and
could lose his pension.
   A man who never met anyone he didn't know and who never found a
word he couldn't squeeze into a mangled metaphor, Manchin
acknowledges his reputation as something of a clown could be working
against him.
   ``So what? It made me,'' he says. ``You can't have it both ways.
   ``I think maybe I'm an easy target. And you have to understand
I've made a lot of enemies.''
   The son of Italian immigrants, Manchin has been a legislator,
teacher, state director of the Farmers Home Admininstration,
secretary of state and state treasurer.
   But it was during his tenure as director of REAP _ the
Rehabilitation Environmental Action Program, created to rid the
state of junked cars and abandoned appliances _ that Manchin became
a household name.
   He appeared on posters, made public service commercials, and was
the subject of a song. He claimed the program rid the state of
100,000 junked cars but later acknowledged the total was about
30,000.
   Wearing his traditional dark suits, bow ties and a hat, usually a
wide-brimmed white fedora, Manchin took his show on the road, posing
atop rusted junkers with a sledgehammer and proclaiming to the
assembled television cameras that he intended to ``remove these
jezebels of junkery,'' ``mash this mess of muckery'' or eliminate
``this truculent trash.''
   If he couldn't find the right word, Manchin made one up.
   ``We come to report that REAP will not relapse into a reverie of
remoteness but will press ever harder to save a world which is bent
on drowning itself in a deluge of debris,'' he said in one fit of
alliteration. On another day, he proclaimed that ``REAP will not
fiddle while Cub Scouts on a camping trip fizzle in filthery.''
   ``I was the original 30-second sound bite: `Let us do battle
against this bastion of bacteria,''' Manchin said during an
interview in his cluttered office. ``Well, you can say that in 30
seconds. Because how do you explain anything in 30 seconds?
   ``You know why people knew me? It was entertaining. `Look at that
clown.' So we've got that kind of reputation. And I don't mind it.''
   In the years since then, Manchin has toned down his rhetoric,
although he still tends to end his correspondence _ including press
releases _ with the phrase, ``May the bright morning star be a lamp
unto our feet.''
   The lobby to his office resembles a flea market, with two 9-foot
bookcases loaded with dozens of volunteer fire department helmets, a
display of different types of U.S. currency, a stack of sheet music
of the state song, and the remnants of a flea circus Manchin rescued
from the Capitol basement.
   On his office wall, along with a framed drawing of the Statue of
Liberty and paintings of his parents, Jesus and Presidents Harry
Truman and Franklin D. Roosevelt, is a plaque that quotes Teddy
Roosevelt:
   ``Far better it is to dare mighty things, to win glorious
triumphs, even though checkered by failure, than to take rank with
those poor spirits who neither enjoy much nor suffer much, because
they live in the gray twilight that knows no victory nor defeat.''
   Three months after Manchin received that plaque from his staff in
January 1987, the treasurer's investment staff ran into trouble
while living by that creed. Trying to maintain phenomenal interest
earnings on its investments, sometimes averaging 14 percent or more,
by trading heavily in the New York bond market, the treasurer's
employees began to fail _ and fail big.
   In one month, the investment staff had lost $100 million from the
$1.8 billion fund. Former Gov. Arch Moore, before leaving office
last January, said the losses eventually totaled $279 million.
Manchin says they totaled $231 million.
   Manchin says he was never told of the losses until auditors made
them public. The House of Delegates, voting 65-34 in March to
impeach him on 17 counts, said either he knew and did nothing to
stop them, or else he didn't know but should have.
   Manchin's supporters call him the people's servant, always ready
to hear their complaints about any facet of state government and do
his best to find a solution. His opponents call him a buffoon who
spends more time traveling around the state handing out cheap
trinkets and making speeches than doing his job. Testimony during
House impeachment procedings placed him out of the office up to
three out of every five days.
   ``Everybody plays on the fact that, `Well, if I had been here
more ....' I'm here as much as any public official because I take
care of my responsibilities,'' Manchin says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--TroubledTreasurer ADV02   06-19 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Troubled Treasurer, ADV 02,0967</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun., July 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHARLESTON, W.Va.: Manchin says.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``They make it look like I was out ignoring my duty. But you
understand that the office that I have always sat in as a public
servant, it extends throughout the state. In other words when I am
out there signing a loan or breaking ground, that's an extension of
my office.''
   Even his supporters, however, have had trouble defending some of
Manchin's antics.
   ``Manchin is not an intellectual giant,'' state Del. Pat Bradley,
one of the treasurer's staunchest defenders, said during the
impeachment proceedings. ``I grant you the man is Barnum &amp; Bailey
all the way through. He wears those crazy hats. The fact that the
guy is half-looney is not impeachable.''
   He's been called a buffoon more than once, but Manchin once said,
``There is not a single pickle missing from my jar.''
   Manchin traces his interest in public service to his parents in
the coal camp of Farmington, where he was born in a United Mine
Workers barracks during a coal strike.
   ``My mother cared about people,'' Manchin says. ``When anyone was
down and out in Farmington, who did they come to? They came to my
Mama Kay. If someone has trouble, they drank too much, their mother
and father couldn't handle them and threw them out of the house, who
did they come to? My mother, Mama Kay. When girls were having
trouble, some of them got pregnant out of wedlock, who do you think
they came to? So all my life we were associated with reaching out
and touching the lives of others. Where did I get started? With a
mother who cared about people.
   ``My father, Joseph Manchin Sr., was a magistrate _ in those days
it was justice of the peace. You understand I worked with him 49
years ago. That would make me what? About 13 years old. I can see
this man that people would come to his office. I'd see my father
talk to them, counsel them and turn them in the right direction.''
   After a stint in the Navy, Manchin enrolled at West Virginia
University, where he got his first taste of politics while running
for sophomore class president, campaigning from a horse and buggy.
   ``I campaigned on a famous song: `Moonlight Cocktails.' I think
it was Glenn Miller's song,'' he said, pausing to sing softly for a
few seconds.
   ``That's what I promised _ hayrides and moonlight cocktails. I
was defeated.''
   In 1948, at age 21, Manchin was elected to the House of Delegates
from Marion County, at the time the youngest legislator ever elected
in West Virginia. He blames his defeat two years later to a bill he
introduced to eliminate the state's segregated schools.
   After working as a high school teacher and coach, he was
appointed by President John F. Kennedy as state director of the
Farmers Home Administration.
   ``We brought water, pure water, to half a million people who did
not have water in their homes, who could not enjoy a good glass of
lemonade, that couldn't have a good cup of coffee, that couldn't
take a shower,'' he said. ``Half a million people. One hundred
thousand homes. And it has been said that many of them finally got
indoor plumbing, and they think of me when they flush their
commode.''
   In 1973 he became director of REAP, and resigned for a successful
run for secretary of state in 1976. Manchin was elected to two terms
as secretary of state, then was elected to the first of two terms as
state treasurer in 1984. The investment fund losses occurred in 1987
but didn't become public until December 1988, after he had been
re-elected without opposition.
   Despite his political problems, Manchin remains the man many
people want to see when they visit the state Capitol. Tour groups
make his office a regular stop, and Manchin expresses disappointment
if he is tied up on a telephone call and can't greet a group of
junior high school students before they leave for other parts of the
Capitol. His office handles hundreds of phone calls a day from
people inquiring about every type of government service from tax
refunds to road repairs. He has a full-time ombudsman on his staff.
   Whether it's network television, national magazines, local
newspapers, or public speakers, no one is safe from Manchin's
well-publicized wrath if he perceives a slur on his native state.
   ``An insult of insane proportions'' is how he once described a
magazine advertisement for hot dogs that he said unfairly depicted
West Virginians as dirty. He once said NBC faced ``the winds of
war'' because ``Today Show'' weatherman Willard Scott's map of the
United States omitted West Virginia's Northern Panhandle.
   He's been constantly criticized by lawmakers for spending his
budget on ceremonial certificates and other doodads naming
recipients ``Commodore of the Ship of State'' or ``Public Friend No.
1.'' He holds an annual ceremony so he can award his ``Order of the
35th Star'' to senior citizens.
   ``Sometimes riding on an elephant, or being on top of a junked
car, or using alliteration, clowning around _ it gets attention,''
Manchin said.
   ``The point we're trying to make is that I have a sense of humor.
I am A. James Manchin. I'm not cloned of anybody. I'm not going to
be one. I'm going to be who I am.
   ``And when they lay me away on a hill in Farmington, W.Va.,
they'll say, `Here lies A. James Manchin. He loved his God. He loved
his state. He loved his family. And he did it all and said it all.'''
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--AgHighSchool ADV02-2Takes   06-19 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Ag High School, ADV 02-2 Takes,0947</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ With enrollments in the nation's colleges of
agriculture declining at a time of strong demand for people trained
in agricultural sciences, graduates of a special high school in
Chicago are prime candidates for scholarships. Though it's located
in a big city, it's one of only two high schools in the nation
focusing on agriculture.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a high school with a livestock judging team,
a field full of vegetables and a greenhouse full of flowers.
   No football team. No cheerleaders.
   In Chicago, of all places.
   The Chicago High School for Agricultural Sciences opened four
years ago on the southwest edge of this city of 3 million, the last
stop before the suburbs and rural countryside. It's one of only two
in the nation focusing on agriculture, and university recruiters
lined up with scholarships for its first graduates this spring.
   ``If we can't find students in the country, we'll find them in
the city,'' says Roger Bruene of the Iowa State University College
of Agriculture. ``You don't have to grow up on a farm to take
advantage of these excellent career opportunities.''
   ``These ag companies are crying for people, especially
minorities,'' says horticulture teacher Ron Biondo. ``We had 19
universities here a few weeks ago recruiting our kids.''
   The first 86 graduates received their diplomas June 23 in a
ceremony at the Chicago Board of Trade, where the nation's major
farm commodities are bought and sold.
   The new school was welcomed by colleges of agriculture because
their enrollments were declining at a time when there was a strong
demand for people trained in agricultural sciences, food
engineering, finance and marketing.
   ``This is a futuristic bridge between a metropolitan area and new
job opportunities in the food and natural resource system,'' says
Allan Goecker of Purdue University.
   The graduating seniors raised and sold crops on the school's
72-acre farm, spent weekends with farm families hundreds of miles
away, and worked afternoons and summers for major agribusiness
companies.
   ``I knew I was interested in science and chemistry, but when I
got here I really got excited about agriculture,'' says Corie
Yearby, who will study agronomy at Alcorn University in Mississippi.
   ``I see all these career opportunities in agriculture and I want
to be part of it,'' said Theresa Garza, who will attend Lincoln
University in Missouri and eventually hopes to grow crops in outer
space.
   The small high school reflects the racial balance of the city's
public school system _ 80 percent of its 435 students are black or
Hispanic. They are recruited for their interest, not their grades.
   ``If Johnny can't add two and two, you don't say he can't come
here,'' says Assistant Principal Kevin McCarthy. ``You say to the
parents, `Does Johnny want to come here and do you want him to come
here?'''
   Students face a tough academic program in the longest school day
in Chicago and nearly 50 percent more class credits than other high
schools.
   But, there is no shortage of applications. For every freshman
accepted, another qualified student is turned away.
   Parents and students are attracted because the school is
relatively small and safe, and there is a likelihood of college and
good jobs later.
   ``They learn about soil, landscaping and horticulture, and they
use these skills,'' says Gloria Yearby, Corie's mother. ``It gives
them a real incentive to go on to college.''
   The students have grown up in the city and for many, Biondo's
horticulture class is the first opportunity to have flower petals
between their fingers and dirt under their nails.
   In the greenhouse, sophomore Julie Berner watered and fertilized
geraniums, some of the 50,000 bedding plants grown and sold by the
students. The sale raised $7,000 for the school.
   ``Just listening to lectures in class would be boring, but this
is exciting, hands-on experience in horticulture,'' she says.
   Outside, students fed the floppy-eared rabbits they raised and
showed in competition. Janet Martinez, a junior, won first place
with Buffy, her black Angora.
   ``I want to be a veterinarian and I know this is the right start
_ an agricultural high school,'' she says.
   Down the hall, the floral design lab was strewn with pieces of
stem from the cutting table. There were cut flowers in a cooler; a
diagram of plant parts on the wall; a chalk drawing of a celosia;
and young violets growing under lights.
   Students sell their arrangements, including many that are used at
official Board of Education activities.
   ``I had one girl with a learning disability who never had gotten
good grades,'' says Donna Theimer, who teaches floral design. ``But,
she loved this class and now she has a career goal she can actually
attain.''
   In the computer laboratory, freshman Tracy Givens and classmates
work on 34 terminals. Computer training is required.
   ``You just have a lot more opportunities here, a lot more
responsibility,'' says Miss Givens, wearing a yellow shirt and cap
advertising the ``Webberville, Mich., Corn Festival.''
   Visits with families in farm country give students a close look
at production agriculture.
   ``It was a unique experience,'' says senior Tracey Moore, who
visited a Wisconsin farm. ``I didn't expect pigs to smell so strong.
But, the farmers are so friendly and they work very hard.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
