<DOCNO> AP890619-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--AgHighSchool ADV02-1stAdd   06-19 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Ag High School, ADV 02-1st Add,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun., July 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: very hard.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Principal Barbara Valerious says a key to the success of the high
school has been the companies that provide specialized equipment for
laboratories, guest speakers for classes and jobs for students.
   Vicky Greer, a junior, spent last summer at Michigan State
University working in the animal science department, helping with
palatability tests on feed for steers.
   Senior Jerome Offord works after classes at the Chicago Board of
Trade, where he distributes literature to the public and helps
organize seminars. Like the other students with ag-related jobs, he
earns credit for high school and money for college.
   ``And, now I really understand how the markets work,'' says
Offord, who will attend Lincoln University to study agricultural
education.
   He is one of six students working at the Board of Trade,
according to Lisa Foss, education and marketing coordinator.
   One major agricultural company interested in the high school is
Dow Chemical Co., of Midland, Mich., a manufacturer of farm
chemicals and seed. Dow will provide four of the high school's
graduates with $2,500-a-year scholarships and summer jobs, says
company spokesman Garry Hamlin. He said Dow wants them to be
interested in careers in agriculture, and with Dow.
   ``We recognize a shortage of strong research-and-development
people in the field today,'' Hamlin says.
   At Purdue University, Goecker helped prepare a report for the
U.S. Department of Agriculture on demand for graduates of
agricultural colleges. He said the report concluded the schools will
turn out 44,000 students a year to fill 48,000 jobs.
   ``The bottom line is about a 10 percent shortfall in the late
1980s in terms of graduates,'' Goecker says. ``A lot of firms are in
the marketplace, aggressively trying to hire people.''
   Hamlin says, for example, Dow would pay an agricultural
researcher with a bachelor of science degree between $24,000 and
$29,000 a year to start, and would pay up to $38,000 for someone
with a doctorate.
   ``We are having trouble getting qualified people into
biotechnology research,'' says Jim Altemus of the Monsanto
Agricultural Co., a St. Louis-based chemical manufacturer. ``These
are support people who have an exposure to science, biology,
chemistry, math, and are patient, accurate and understand the metric
system.''
   Goecker says enrollment in colleges of agriculture peaked at
about 100,000 in 1976-77, then fell to a low of about 66,000 in 1987.
   Educators blame economic stress on the farm and the incorrect
notion that agriculture means only farming _ raising crops and
livestock.
   ``Ag is becoming more high-tech all the time,'' says Bonnie
Johnson of Washington State University, where agricultural
enrollments dropped 40 percent during the early 1980s. ``People have
not seen agriculture as science, food processing and finance.''
   That was one of the first problems the new Chicago high school
had to deal with.
   ``In the city, you say agriculture and people think, `dumb
farmer,''' Biondo says. ``First, farmers aren't dumb, they're smart.
Second, agriculture is much more than farming.''
   Biondo, like the other 10 teachers who came to the Chicago school
in 1985, was hired from outside the district. There simply were no
teachers in Chicago qualified to teach the agricultural courses.
There now are 43 faculty members, and all but two of the original
teachers remain on campus.
   Biondo, who was recruited after a well-publicized 1984 meeting
with President Ronald Reagan at the Will County center where Biondo
taught, liked the idea of a totally new approach to high school, and
he liked the students he would work with.
   ``There are racial and ethnic differences,'' he says. ``They are
louder, street-smart kids who don't intimidate easily. But, there
are some really bright, motivated kids here.''
   There also are some drawbacks.
   Quarters are cramped in the remodeled elementary school, despite
a 1987 addition and five modular classrooms outside the main brick
building.
   Files are piled on windowsills. One classroom is converted to a
gym by moving desks and throwing mats on the floor. Another becomes
the cafeteria when lunch is delivered.
   The students are demanding.
   ``They won't let a teacher sit around,'' says Marcia
Watman-Lauchner, who teaches agricultural communications and food
science and works on the school's curriculum. ``They want to learn
and work hard, and they demand our time and information. They'll
tell you what they want from you.''
   The racial makeup of the school also has caused a few problems in
the white, upper-middle class Mount Greenwood neighborhood.
Valerious says black students have been targets of bottle-throwing
and name-calling, though the majority of people in the neighborhood
support the school and admire the students.
   McCarthy said only three students who enrolled in 1985 dropped
out of high school, and ``that's phenomenal in four years'' in the
city.
</TEXT>
