<DOCNO> AP890619-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV02   06-19 0904</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 02,0929</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeff Gordon calls himself an ``actor-bat.''
   Eight times a week, he dives, jumps, spins, leaps, falls and
tumbles into the orchestra pit at Broadway's St. James Theater.
   And audiences gasp. His stunts provide some of the funniest _ and
most unexpected _ moments in ``Largely New York,'' a comedy without
dialogue written by, directed by and starring clown Bill Irwin.
   In the 65-minute entertainment, Irwin battles video technology _
recalcitrant remote controls, temperamental television sets,
malevolent minicams _ and loses hilariously. But the show also
features Gordon, two break dancers named Leon Chesney and Steve
Clemente, a ballerina named Margaret Eginton and a gaggle of dancers
dressed like academics in cap and gown.
   ``Bill Irwin is a pioneer in proving to the show business
establishment that clowns are very talented people,'' Gordon says.
``They are not just buffoons. They reflect human nature. There is a
pervasive American attitude that clowns are the underbelly of show
business, second-class performers. Bill is proving that you can have
roots in the circus and physical comedy and still be a
thinking-man's clown.''
   In the show, Gordon plays a character called the Dean, an
officious authority figure who leads this rubber-legged band of
graduates around the stage. His speciality is a swoon from the
stage. He plunges some 8 feet into the pit.
   ``So far, I haven't been hurt,'' says the performer, knocking on
the makeup table for luck in his St. James dressing room. But don't
worry. His dive is cushioned by a thick mat that covers the floor of
the pit. He also wears kneepads and elbow pads.
   Gordon jumps with the expertise of a high diver, which is what he
was in school. Back at Allegheny College in Meadville, Pa., he was a
four-time All-American springboard diver and an NCAA Division III
national champion.
   But what do you do after you get a degree in sociology and find
that jobs are scarce?
   ``I became a clown,'' says the 35-year-old Gordon, who grew up in
Pittsburgh.
   He was tending bar on the Delta Queen, the famous riverboat that
still makes the journey up and down the Mississippi River. On the
boat, he met several clowns who had worked with the Ringling Bros.
and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus.
   They inspired him to apply for the circus's Clown College in
Sarasota, Fla.
   ``I had an advantage over other applicants,'' Gordon says. ``I
was a little older and already had gymnastics, but the training in
Sarasota was incredibly rigorous.''
   At the school, Gordon learned clown makeup, how to sew his own
costume and to create his own clown character as well studying the
history of circuses and the fine art of clowning.
   After graduating, Gordon got a job jumping over elephants in the
Red Unit, one of two troupes Ringling sends out to tour the country.
It was hard work. There were 11 shows a week, nearly half of them
packed into a weekend. Gordon did that for a year before leaving and
joining the Big Apple Circus in New York in 1981.
   ``The Ringling Bros. circus was a three-ring circus,'' Gordon
says. ``The Big Apple Circus is one ring and much more focused. It
uses changes in lighting and music to create a mood rather than
spectacle.''
   In the Big Apple Circus, each performer gets a featured spot,
according to Gordon, and because of this individual focus, the
audience is drawn into the show rather than overwhelmed by three
rings of action.
   For the Big Apple Circus, Gordon created a special, very physical
red-nosed clown who talks in monosyllables. His name is Gordoon, a
variation on his creator's last name.
   ``Talking is not one of his featured talents, but he's been known
to lip-sync to the Supremes,'' Gordon adds. ``Gordoon is like my
best pal. Since I've been in `Largely New York,' I haven't played
him in about five months and I miss him.''
   But the performer says he is still working on new routines for
his clown character.
   ``I have a little idea book I keep by my bed,'' Gordon says. ``I
always jot down these seemingly silly ideas. They tend to pile up
and influence one another and something comes out of that.''
   ``There are basically three kinds of clowns,'' he explains. ``A
white-faced clown who is more of an effete, a kind of a straight
man; an ``auguste'' clown who is a bumbler and does a lot of
slapstick like Gordoon, and a character clown like a hobo or a
little old lady.''
   It was at the Big Apple Circus that Irwin first saw Gordon
perform. He later cast him in various productions of ``Largely New
York'' as it made its way from a New York workshop to Seattle to
Washington and on to Broadway.
   Because of his success in ``Largely New York,'' Gordon has
received some interest from film and television people.
   ``But there will always be a place in my heart for clowning,''
Gordon says. ``But I want to work. If that means working on
Broadway, doing physical comedy, film or commercial work, I'll do
it. It feels good to be versatile and a lot of that I learned in the
circus.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
