<DOCNO> AP890619-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Colombia Adv25-2Takes   06-19 0983</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Colombia, Adv 25-2 Takes,1011</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday June 25 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Colombia _ Surviving in Bloodshed</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: an accompanying story is BC-Continent-Colombia-Cocaine, b0679.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia has lived in bloodshed almost constantly
since its founding in 1819 and these days the violence is laced with
cocaine and common crime, as well as ideology. But while most of its
South American neighbors struggle for economic survival, Colombia is
striding forward even though it is again at war with itself. This is
one of a series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the
economic, social and political turbulence that has turned South
America into a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a simultaneous struggle with
guerrillas, right-wing vigilantes, drug smugglers and assassins,
Colombia resolutely survives.
   To an extent it even thrives.
   The withering crossfire of violence invites predictions of
national perdition. But a country accustomed to decades of
bloodletting goes about its politics and business.
   ``In general terms, the state not only functions, it functions
better every day,'' said Pierre Gilodes, director of the Foreign
Ministry's Institute for Higher Developmental Studies.
   ``We don't know if this is a paradox, or if there is some
relationship between what is happening in the country and the
efficient functioning of the state.''
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Gilodes said he
suspects a kind of perversely positive relationship exists.
   ``The state is pushed to function well, or it will collapse,''
said Gilodes, a French expert contracted by the government to head
the institute.
   The actions of shadowy right-wing groups may help keep some
dissent stifled, he added.
   ``The state can decide that salaries will go up less than the
cost of living and no one protests.''
   Unions that would or should raise their voices ``are under
pressure from private groups that kill labor activists.''
   In addition, he said, leftist guerrilla and right-wing violence
in the countryside is steadily driving both poor and well-to-do to
the cities, to help fuel the more productive urban-based industries
with seed money and cheap labor.
   Colombia's gross national product of about $42 billion grew 3.7
percent last year, lower than the recent annual average but enviable
to most struggling Latin American countries. Annual inflation is 28
percent, a fraction of that of neighboring nations.
   New factories go up daily and, with healthy tax revenues, the
government regularly builds new roads and launches other public
works projects.
   Illegal cocaine earnings bring home an estimated $500 milllion to
$1.2 billion a year and is believed responsible for perhaps
one-fifth of the country's eonomic growth last year.
   But, Gilodes insists, drugs can hardly be called the economic
engine for a country whose $6 billion in legal yearly exports
include coffee, oil, coal and an ever-more diverse array of
non-traditional products such as flowers. He attributes the success
to many years of ``prudent management'' of a sound free-market
economy.
   On the political side, preliminary campaigning for congressional
and municipal elections next March and presidential balloting in May
is already under way. Nobody expects any big hitches.
   Democracy is even broadening its base. Absenteeism at the polls
is shrinking each year, and the country recently celebrated the
first anniversary of the election of the country's 1,009 mayors, who
used to be appointed. All political and social camps declared the
experiment a great success.
   Colombia also thrives culturally, with nightly performances of
plays, symphonies and popular music for a people who love to dance
and can easily distinguish the beat of an inland rumba from a
coastal cumbia.
   Fueled by the works of Latin America's most popular living
novelist, Gabriel Garcia Marquez, Colombia's book industry is
booming. A national poetry contest in the industrial city of
Medellin, the dark heart of cocaine country, drew an enthusiastic
crowd of 7,000 people. A love poem won.
   To a visitor the country's troubles, the machine-gun fire and car
bombs can seem non-existent, or distant, or quickly absorbed in the
bustle of an exuberant people, like a grenade lobbed in thick jungle.
   On May 27, on a major Bogota thoroughfare, 220 pounds of
explosive went off as the chief of the country's security police,
Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, was passing in his car. He was just
bruised, but seven passersby were mortally wounded.
   Within a few hours, the rubble had been swept up and life was
back to normal.
   But then, in Colombia, death is measured by the dozen.
   Killings this year totaled 9,411 as of early June _ an average 60
a day, according to National Police Department statistics.
   That is down from a daily average of 66 last year, when killings
totaled 24,280 _ eight times the total of 2,924 in California, which
has 28 million inhabitants to Colombia's 31 million. Most adult
Colombian males are said to die by the knife, gun or garrotte.
   Most of the deaths are what police call common homicides,
unrelated to politics. But among this year's victims were 67
politicians and 86 policemen. In the last eight months, the
government insurance company has paid off death benefits to the
families of 771 armed forces members and 15 court officials.
   The police even keep a statistic for mass killings, involving
five or more victims. There have been 34 so far this year, with a
total of 175 victims.
   Occasionally, there is a sign that even expansive Colombia is
having trouble absorbing death in such big numbers.
   In the community called Palestina, on the Cauca River not far
from the city of Manizales, authorities complained that the town
graveyard can't handle all the unclaimed, bullet-riddled corpses
being pulled from the river, according to a dispatch in the Bogota
newpspaper La Prensa. It said 120 bodies had been found since late
last year.
   The country's sources of violence are manifold.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
