<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-StreetKids-Brazil Adv25   06-19 0922</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Street Kids-Brazil, Adv 25,0953</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday June 25 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activists Say AIDS Spreading Among Brazil's 7 Million Street Kids</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: a companion story is BC-Street Kids-Bolivia, b0680.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health activists fear AIDS is
spreading rapidly among Brazil's estimated 7 million street kids.
   They complain authorities are doing little to stop it.
   ``These children have frequent sexual contact, as prostitutes and
with each other,'' said Flavio Braune Wiik of the Brazilian
Interdisciplinary AIDS Association in Rio de Janeiro. ``Most don't
know what condoms are or how to use them, and they have almost no
access to health care.
   ``Of course it's spreading.''
   Brazil, with 6,421 confirmed AIDS cases overall through April of
this year, is the world's No. 3 AIDS country after the United States
and France.
   Official figures, which activists fear may be low, indicate that
140,000 youngsters living in the streets are infected with the virus.
   The situation is especially troubling in Rio de Janeiro, with
more than 1 million street kids, the highest number in the country,
and 705 confirmed cases of AIDS.
   ``The government spends very little on AIDS prevention programs
of any kind,'' said Wiik. ``And it has almost no special projects
for street kids who have little access to official campaigns.''
   The first AIDS case was reported in Brazil in 1983. But until
early 1987 the government did not place a priority on combating the
virus, arguing that malaria, tuberculosis, Chagas disease, and
numerous other maladies affected more people and thus deserved
higher priority.
   Finally, though, the government launched an anti-AIDS campaign
with public posters and television messages telling of the perils of
AIDS and discussing preventive measures.
   But Wiik said the campaign is almost completely ineffective in
reaching street kids.
   ``Even children who live at home don't learn much about AIDS from
the ads, because they appear only late at night,'' he said in an
interview. ``How are street kids supposed to see them if they don't
have television?''
   Wiik added that the language in the ads was sterilized due to
protests from conservatives and Roman Catholic Church leaders.
   ``These kids don't know what `sperm' or `anal sex' are,'' he
said. ``They only know street talk. ...''
   Making matters worse, an unprecedented economic crisis with
inflation running at around 1,000 percent annually has led to budget
cutbacks in many social programs.
   The Program for the Control of AIDS, an agency of the Health
Ministry, had its 1989 budget cut by 30 percent, to only $10.4
million. That has left the problem of combatting AIDS largely on the
shoulders of state and local governments and volunteer
organizations, and they have even less money in their budges than
federal authorities.
   Wiik said the AIDS Association, which produces educational
materials on AIDS for groups that work with street kids, runs the
only program of its type in this country of 144 million people.
   The problem of controlling the spread of AIDS among street kids
is difficult because to the life they lead.
   Drug use, especially cocaine, is widespread. But most street
youths in Brazil do not inject drugs, activists say, so the spread
of the AIDS virus via contaminated needles is not common.
   The bigger problem is sex.
   Most boys on the streets earn their money by stealing, begging or
prostitution, Juvenile Court files indicate. But, according to
activists, the only real option for girls on the streets is
prostitution.
   ``Girls as young as 9 and 10 often work as prostitutes, sometimes
for a plate of food,'' said Vera Lucia Fernandes de Souza, a
``street kids educator'' with a program organized by the mayor's
office in Rio de Janeiro.
   Many street children also have sex with their companions as well,
further increasing the risk of infection.
   ``Many know little about AIDS or sex,'' Ms. Souza said. ``I've
had girls who were pregnant and thought they `caught it,' like a
cold. And educational work is extremely difficult. It's hard enough
for street kids to remember what time it is let alone to use a
condom _ which they don't have money to buy in any case.''
   Adding to the problem, she said, is the terrible toll street life
takes on the youths.
   ``Without a real home, food, or family, many of these kids think
life has no meaning anyway. They have no hopes for the future, so
they don't think about tomorrow.''
   Street kids who live at Largo do Machado, a public plaza on Rio's
south side, showed little concern when interviewed about contracting
the AIDS virus.
   ``Luis,'' who said he was 14 but looks about 12, said he has
burglarized homes and admitted he had worked as a prostitute to
support himself. He had heard about AIDS, he said, but didn't use
condoms nor did he know anyone who did.
   ``I'm not afraid of dying or anything else,'' he said. ``I wasn't
born to live forever, and I have to eat.''
   Luis said he visits his mother in a slum neighborhood several
hours from downtown Rio every Sunday.
   ``I tell her I sell stuff on the street and beg, so she doesn't
worry.''
   ``Jose,'' an 18-year-old who has lived on the street for five
years, said, ``AIDS will kill you, but I'm going to die one day
anyway.''
   And if he knew he had AIDS would he stop any type of sexual
activity?
   ``No. I'd probably play around more to die sooner.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday June 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
