<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-19 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0831</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. unveiled its defense against a $10.7
billion unwanted takeover bid by Paramount Communications Inc.,
rejecting the bid and making its own $14 billion tender offer for
Warner Communications Inc. to succeed an earlier Time-Warner merger
plan.
   Paramount replied Friday that it would press ahead with the
unsolicited $175-a-share cash offer for Time.
   Most observers said the Time-Warner announcement only complicated
the three-way struggle Time.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court approved the bankruptcy
reorganization of A.H. Robins Co., including $2.5 billion for women
who claim they were injured by the company's Dalkon Shield birth
control device sold in the 1970s.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld on Friday all parts
of the long-awaited restructuring of Robins, which will become a
subsidiary of New York-based American Home Products Corp. in a $700
million stock swap.
   ``I think it's just tremendous news for all Dalkon Shield
claimants,'' said Guerry Thornton, attorney for the Dalkon Shield
Victims Association in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans paid more for food, clothing and
gasoline last month, pushing the Consumer Price Index up 0.6
percent, the government said.
   Analysts said Friday's report was evidence of a stubborn
inflation problem.
   Consumer prices, which rose 0.7 percent in April, have risen at
an annual rate of 6.7 percent so far this year, compared with price
increases of 4.4 percent during 1987 and 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction fell 2.1 percent in May to
the lowest level since the last recession in 1982, the government
reported.
   But analysts said Friday declining interest rates should turn the
industry around in coming months.
   Mortgage rates peaked at 11.22 percent in March and fell to 10.2
percent by last week, causing many analysts to anticipate a jump in
housing construction last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four groups say they remain in the running to
buy Northwest Airlines parent NWA Inc., as a major takeover firm was
rumored to be a front-runner.
   Pan Am Corp., oil billionaire Marvin Davis, Northwest's
machinists' union and a group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred
Checchi said they met Friday's deadline for revised bids for the
owner of Northwest Airlines, the nation's fourth-largest carrier.
   Two of those bidders, who asked not to be identified, said they
believed the New York takeover firm Kohlberg Kravis &amp; Roberts Co.
also submitted an offer. Kohlberg Kravis would not comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines has agreed to sell
its eight Philadelphia airport gates, 16 jets and other assets to
Midway Airlines for $206.5 million.
   The move disclosed Friday heads off threatened antitrust action
by the Justice Department to block Eastern's earlier proposed sale
of the Philadelphia gates and two U.S.-Canadian routes to USAir
Group Inc.
   Eastern announced the Midway deal at a federal bankruptcy court
hearing over its earlier agreement with Washington-based USAir. U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland gave Eastern permission to
terminate that agreement, but still must approve the sale to
Chicago-based Midway.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said it will consolidate
its consumer photography products and picture finishing operations,
cutting costs and hundreds of jobs.
   Four operations will be merged in the newly created Consumer
Imagery Division, company spokesman Paul Allen said Friday.
   Kodak said the move would strengthen its consumer photography
business, part of the firm's imaging segment, which made a dismal
showing when Kodak's first-quarter earnings were announced in May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. plans to cut its corporate
staff by 300, mostly through layoffs.
   The defense contractor and building controls maker said Friday
that 75 of the jobs will be lost to attrition, while the balance of
the cuts will be made with layoffs and some early retirements.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Board of Regents unanimously
banned the Channel One news service containing commercials from
being beamed into the state's high schools.
   The regents rejected Whittle Communications' program, saying they
were worried the ``active commercialization'' of the programs would
send the wrong message to high school students.
   The decision is a blow to the Tennessee-based Whittle, which has
said it wants to sign up 40 percent of the nation's 20,000 high
schools.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved ahead Friday in the heaviest trading
volume in about five months. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 11.38 to 2,486.38, but lost 27.04 points from a week earlier.
   The dollar finished higher against the British pound, Canadian
dollar and Swiss franc but lower against other major currencies.
   Bond prices edged lower.
   Live cattle futures prices posted modest gains ; energy prices
tumbled; grains and soybeans were mixed; and precious metals
retreated.
