<DOCNO> AP890619-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PointImage     06-19 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Point Image,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Brewery Aims To `Score A Few Points' With Racy Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STEVENS POINT, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small Wisconsin beer-maker is
brewing a new image with slick television ads that may be a bit hard
to swallow for some longtime Point Beer drinkers.
   The beer, once touted on T-shirts as ``not just for breakfast
anymore,'' is featured in 30-second commercials with fast-paced
music, the glossy look of national ads and quick shots of
long-legged women in short skirts.
   One shows a couple falling on a bed; each ends with an attractive
blonde and the slogan ``Score a few Points ... tonight!''
   The commercials have aired frequently since Memorial Day weekend
but only on the television stations in the Wausau-Stevens Point area.
   In that small market, Point Beer is going head-to-head with
national brands in its television campaign, said Kenneth Shibilski,
Stevens Point Brewery president.
   ``Today, more sizzle is sold than steak,'' Shibilski said last
week. ``People are drinking more of the image than the product.''
   He said about 75 percent of the private brewery's sales are
within a 50-mile area of is home in Stevens Point, a city of about
23,000 in north-central Wisconsin.
   The brewery hopes the ads can change its image as the hometown
beer that Dad used to drink to a quality, fun brew young adults will
choose for a loyal brand, said Shibilski.
   The brewery, established in 1857, also hopes the commercials can
stem a 15 percent drop in sales from three years ago, he said.
   Point, like a vanishing number of other small breweries, has to
do something to compete with bigger beer names that can price their
products lower and are better known, said Shibilski, president of
the Brewers Association of America.
   The hometown reaction to the commercials has been mostly positive
but people are a bit stunned by them, local bartenders said.
   ``A lot of people don't feel that what they (the ads) are
protraying is Stevens Point,'' said Tina Kerske, who has poured
Point from the tap for 2{ years at The Thirsty Whale in Stevens
Point.
   Women at her bar are more likely to wear jeans and T-shirts
rather than short skirts, she said.
   ``They keep saying they want to meet a woman who dresses like
that and drinks Point,'' she said.
   In Wausau, Todd Rasmussen, 33, the manager of Scott Street Steak
&amp; Pub, said: ``People like the idea of a national-looking
commercial. ... The only thing negative I heard is that they (the
commercials) are too liberal for this conservative of an area.''
   Shibilski defended the ads as spicy but not sexist.
   The couple shown falling onto a bed as a voiceover says,
``Remember, when the party's over, there are better things to do
than drive drunk'' is fully clothed, he noted.
   The Point commercials are aimed at 21- to 25-year-old men because
they are the heaviest beer drinkers, said Rick Stone, a partner at
Lindsay &amp; Stone Advertising Inc. in Madision, which created the
campaign.
   ``Our overall strategy for Point is to try to develop some fun
around the product,'' Stone said.
   Shibilski said it is still too early to tell what effect the
commercials will have on sales but that the brewery plans to run the
ads all summer and looks for results farther in the future.
   ``We want to be one of the breweries that's going to be around in
the 21st century,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
