<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Kraft-PR     06-19 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kraft-PR,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kraft Could Have Handled Car Contest Mix-up Better: Experts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Kraft realized its ``Ready to Roll'' contest
was flawed and had produced more winners than losers, the food
company should have decided on a response more quickly, public
relations experts say.
   The contest, in which hundreds or possibly thousands of people
``won'' the same $17,000 Dodge minivan, was a public relations
disaster that left Kraft officials scurrying for a response when the
error was discovered June 11.
   ``Our advice to Kraft immediately would have been to go public
with this thing,'' said Walter Mulhall, co-director of
Mulhall-Kemplin Communications. ``The way to handle things is to
offer a lot of explanation and candor, and they're certainly not
being candid.''
   Kraft, based in the Chicago suburb of Glenview and known formally
as the Kraft General Foods Group of Philip Morris Cos., offered to
make up for the mix-up by quadrupling the number of prizes, giving
away cash and adding special drawings.
   To win, a customer had to match two halves of a picture of a van,
one from packages of cheese and the other printed in newspaper
advertisements. A printing error apparently gave nearly everybody
matching pieces.
   Kraft announced Thursday it would pay $250 to everybody who was
holding a winning ticket for the van, and other cash payouts to
winners of other prizes _ bicycles, skateboards and cheese. Winners
will be eligible for a drawing for four vans.
   ``The one thing that the public understands is that people screw
up,'' said Pat Jackson, editor of PR Reporter, an industry magazine.
``Kraft should have gone public. If they carried it off with
humility, they could have gotten the public on their side. Instead,
this kind of last-minute payoff doesn't take care of all the
disgruntled people.''
   At least two lawsuits have been filed because of the botched
contest.
   Jackson said the slow response led people to believe the company
had something to hide.
   ``When Kraft ducks under the covers, it immediately sends the
message, `They are lying,''' he said. ``Facts have nothing to do
with getting people on your side. It's all a matter of perception.''
   The company also erred in not calling on top executives to
address the mix-up, many in the public relations industry said.
   ``A CEO himself has to have the guts to come out and exert some
authority, not hide behind the statements of his PR director,''
added Ted Pincus, chairman of the Financial Relations Board.
   Kraft spokeswoman Kathy Knuth would not comment Friday on the
company's handling of the contest beyond saying, ``This is my job;
it certainly has been difficult, and it has been interesting.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
