<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-19 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in quiet early European
trading today. Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said they expected trading to be calm
this week with the dollar consolidating at current levels.
   ``After a truly historic week with violent fluctuations in heavy
trading last week, the market is realistically due for a break,''
said one trader in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.45 yen to a closing 145.50 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 145.27 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday's
prices included: 1.9925 West German marks, up from 1.9915; 1.7205
Swiss francs, down from 1.7213; 6.7535 French francs, down from
6.7620; 2.2438 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2385; 1,447.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,443.50; and 1.1980 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1973.
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound,
and traders said it was due to the poor showing of the governing
Conservative Party in European Parliament elections.
   It cost $1.5352 to buy one pound on Monday compared with $1.5340
late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $362.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $363.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $363.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.85, up from $363.75 late Friday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.31 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $5.27.
   All financial institutions in Hong Kong were closed today for
official birthday celebrations of Queen Elizabeth II.
</TEXT>
