<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-19 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Down, Dollar Bounces Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell today,
while the dollar rebounded against the Japanese yen after Friday's
sharp loss.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 33,013.18, down
41.99 points, or 0.13 percent. It had closed at 33,055.17 on Friday
after rising 142.08 points.
   The dollar closed at 145.50 yen, up 0.45 yen from its close of
145.05 yen on Friday, when it fell 6.25 yen. The dollar opened today
at 144.20 and ranged between 144.15 and 145.58 yen.
   Before Friday's fall, the dollar had gained 10.65 yen since June
5.
   ``During the afternoon, stock prices stayed level except for a
temporary rise in the Nikkei Average of about 100 yen,'' Daiwa
Securities dealer Kenji Ishizuka said.
   Ishizuka said investors were paying careful attention to company
earnings and exchange rate fluctuations.
   The foreign exchange market was comparatively calm, said Toshiaki
Kakimoto, a dealer at Sumitomo Bank.
   ``Dealers are holding back after last week's extreme jumps in the
yen-dollar rate,'' he said.
   Kakimoto predicted that the dollar would stay in the 140-yen
range for the next month.
   There are no incentives to purchase dollars at more than 150 yen,
Kakimoto said.
   Moreover, concerted efforts by financial authorities to keep the
dollar under 150 yen have persuaded dealers around the world that
the dollar ought to stay in the 140-yen range, he said.
</TEXT>
