<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-19 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Soar On Dry Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices were sharply
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, buoyed
by a mostly dry weekend in the Corn Belt and forecasts for at least
a week of hot weather.
   The change from cool, rainy weather to warmer, drier conditions
is reigniting drought fears in the Midwest, which has not fully
recovered from last year's devastating drought.
   ``People are hypersensitive after last year, so that's what's got
them going this morning,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   The corn market is getting additional support from the
Agriculture Department's decision to extend the due date on loans
covering 700 million bushels of corn, keeping at least some of that
grain off the market for another six months.
   Gains in the wheat market were limited by selling linked to the
advancing winter wheat harvest.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.97} a bushel; corn was 2} cents
to 9 cents higher with July at $2.71{ a bushel; oats were 5 cents to
6 cents higher with July at $1.70{ a bushel; soybeans were 12 cents
to 16{ cents higher with July at $7.45 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were sharply higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, boosted by a monthly USDA report
issued Friday that showed far fewer cattle were placed on feedlots
in May than traders had expected.
   Live cattle were .55 cent to 1.45 cents higher with June at 72.62
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to .88 cent higher with
August at 81.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent to .90 cent
higher with June at 48.65 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.38 cent to 1.07 cents higher with July at 34.30 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Friday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
