<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon CORRECTION   06-19 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon, CORRECTION,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates Dow to noon in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted lower today in a subdued
atmosphere following Friday's ``triple witching hour.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.09 to 2,476.29
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 504 up, 745 down and
554 unchanged.
   The market held steady on Friday amid a barrage of trading by
traders completing computer-program strategies involving a group of
expiring stock index options and futures.
   Analysts noted that these quarterly witching hours are often
followed by at least a brief letdown in stock prices and trading
activity.
   In addition, brokers cited lingering uncertainty over the next
likely turn in the Federal Reserve's credit policy.
   The stream of economic data that Wall Streeters watch along with
the Fed runs dry for the next few days.
   NWA climbed 6~ to 114{ after a delayed opening. An investor group
led by Alfred Checchi of Los Angeles announced an agreement to
acquire NWA for $121 a share, apparently ending a bidding war among
several parties.
   Time Inc. fell 6 to 156{ and Warner Communications held steady at
59\. On Friday Time began a $70-a-share offer for Warner after
Paramount Communications disrupted plans for a Time-Warner merger
with a hostile bid for Time.
   Paramount shares lost 1 to 57[.
   Sea Containers Ltd. jumped 6] to 72. The company, which is
fighting a $50-a-share takeover bid by the European countries
Tiphook and Stena, said it was working on a plan for a buyout or
restructuring.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .36 to 179.23. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was off .11 at 361.72.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 61.74 million shares at noontime,
down from 155.33 million at the same point Friday.
</TEXT>
