<FIRST>s f BC-KNO-CarWars Adv25   06-19 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-KNO-Car Wars, Adv 25,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday June 25 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>International Design Battle Waged in Southern California</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY69 of June 15; Also in AP Access under KNOCARS.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If there's one thing American automakers
should be able to do better than Japanese rivals, it's knowing the
styles American drivers like.
   But Japan's automakers set out to eliminate that advantage by
establishing design shops in that car-crazed corner of America,
Southern California. They've turned out the snazzy prototypes for
bestsellers like Mazda's MX-5 Miata, Nissan's Pathfinder 4x4,
Honda's CRX and Toyota's Celica.
   The American-designed Japanese cars were so successful that
Detroit was forced to follow suit with its own California design
studios.
   As is increasingly the case in the knowledge economy, the Big
Three U.S. carmakers found that to stay in the race _ even in their
own backyard _ they have to get smarter about giving consumers what
they want.
   ``They were too insulated from the popular culture; they were
still living mentally and psychologically in the Bloomfield Hills
Country Club,'' said Tony Assenza, senior editor of Car and Driver
magazine, speaking of a wealthy Detroit suburb.
   ``In the United States, everybody looks here for trends,'' said
Hiroshi Moriyoshi, who heads Mazda's Southern California design and
research outpost. ``The whole environment is conducive to
creativity.''
   Cars are so similar in price and technology that style has become
more important than ever. Hence the 14 auto design studios within
120 freeway miles of Los Angeles.
   Detroit for years kept an eye on how Californians customize cars
and hired California-trained designers, part of a watch on trends
nationwide.
   But the Japanese were the first to actually set up shop here,
beginning with Toyota Motor Corp.'s Calty Design Research Inc. in
Newport Beach in 1973. Honda Motor Co. Ltd. followed in 1974 with a
shop in Torrance, Mazda Motor Corp. in 1976 in Irvine and Nissan
Motor Co. Ltd. in 1979 in La Jolla.
   The studios were small, low-profile, seemingly unthreatening.
   Then the 1978 Celica hit the car-show circuit, catching the eye
of auto enthusiasts who tended to look at most Japanese products as
dull compacts meant for the budget-minded.
   The Japanese companies managed to make compacts stylish, turning
out sporty, young-looking cars that young people could afford.
Detroit was left wallowing behind.
   ``It was a mind-set predicated on the fact that the main car of
interest to anybody they talked to was a six-passenger, four-door
luxury automobile roughly in the shape of a brick,'' Assenza said.
   Detroit established satellite design studios, or beefed up
informal sampling of the tastes out West.
   Chrysler Corp.'s Pacific Advanced Product Design Center in
Carlsbad and General Motors Corp.'s Advanced Concepts Center in
Newbury Park sprang up in 1983, followed a year later by Ford
Concept Center California in Valencia.
   Other Japanese makers, plus Volvo and three independents, bring
the number of design studios in the area to 14. Most employ fewer
than 50.
   The Japanese had intensely practical reasons for setting up
design shops in Southern California: The West Coast was already
their business beachhead in America, and the weather was far more
agreeable than Detroit's.
   But it turns out they landed in the most wide-open auto market in
the world, where designers can sample trends just driving to work.
   ``It's the best automotive design melting pot that I can think
of,'' said Fritz Mayhew, chief design executive at Ford Motor Co. in
Detroit, who oversees the contributions of the company's California
designers.
   Then there's California's role as a crucible of popular culture.
   ``Fads, trends, do start here,'' said Ron Hill, head of the
industrial design program at the Art Center College of Design in
Pasadena, where many car designers get their start. ``People are
less inhibited to look at the new, to express themselves in ways
they're not so capable of doing in other parts of the country or the
world.''
   Among the auto trends traced to California: Hot rods, pickup
trucks as basic commuter transportation, convertible pickups, trim
and grillwork that's painted not chromed, the new emphasis on
comfortable interiors.
   Nissan's Pulsar NX, a compact with interchangeable tops that
makes it a convertible, a pickup or a station wagon, emerged in
production almost unchanged from the design, said Gerald Hirshberg,
a former GM designer who heads the company's studio in La Jolla.
   The same was true for the company's brawny, American-looking
Pathfinder 4x4 and ``hardbody'' pickups.
   Mazda's studio employs designers from Japan, the United States
and Taiwan. Several have worked in Europe.
   Nissan's Hirshberg has found the Japanese admire their American
co-workers' willingness to take risks in design, while the Americans
are taken aback by the Japanese ability to translate a design into a
practical car.
   ``There's a kind of subtle collaboration that can only happen
when parts of both cultures are put in the frying pan,'' Hirshberg
said. ``You get a tremendous energy burst when you tap into what
each culture does better.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday June 25</NOTE>
