<FIRST>u f PM-TrustcorpMerger     06-19 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trustcorp Merger,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trustcorp to Merge With Cleveland Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled Trustcorp has agreed to
be bought by Society Corp. in a stock-swap deal valued at about $495
million, both companies said today.
   The announcement follows months of speculation that Toledo-based
Trustcorp might be a takeover target due to its financial woes,
which included writeoffs of $76 million in bad real estate loans
over the past five months.
   Trustcorp also recently added $24 million to its loan-loss
reserves.
   Under the buyout, Cleveland-based Society agreed to swap
three-quarters of of its common shares for each of Trustcorp's
shares. Society also was given the option of buying unissued
Trustcorp common shares equal to 24.9 percent of the total
outstanding shares.
   The combined bank holding company will have about $16 billion in
assets.
   Chester Devenow, Trustcorp's interim president and chief
executive officer, called the deal, ``a tremdous step forward.''
   ``We are not giving up ownership of this bank,'' he said. ``We
believe our partnership with a quality company like Society Corp.
will be in the best interest of our shareholders, our customers, our
employees and the communities we serve.''
   Society Chairman Robert W. Gillespie, chairman and chief
executive officer of Society Corp., said ``substantial additional
contributions'' to Trustcorp's loan-loss reserve would be necessary.
   He told a news conference he understood the problems Trustcorp
has had with bad loans.
   ``They're recognized. We want to put it behind us by the end of
the year. It's a chapter that needs to be closed,'' Gillespie said.
   Six of Trustcorp's top executives, including George Haigh, former
president, chairman and chief executive officer, resigned or were
fired in the wake of the losses.
   The $76 million in write-offs resulted in a drop in Trustcorp's
overall earnings in 1988, to $1.3 million, or 8 cents a share,
compared with $47.8 million, or $2.91 a share, in 1987.
   In addition, the insitution's earnings dropped nearly $5 million
in the first quarter of 1989.
   William Prebe, an independent financial consultant and University
of Toledo economics professor, said Society likely would transfer
some of Trustcorp's Toledo operations to Cleveland.
   ``If they are bottom line oriented and look to trim expenses and
costs, obviously the first place they will trim will be Toledo,'' he
said. ``They are not going to trim Society in Cleveland.
</TEXT>
