<FIRST>r f BC-Blinder     06-19 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Blinder,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Penny Stock Firm Planning Name Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blinder International Enterprises Inc.,
the parent company of the penny stock brokerage facing a series of
federal and state fraud investigations, said Friday it is planning a
name change.
   Blinder said it will ask shareholders at the company's annual
meeting next month to approve renaming the firm Intercontinental
Enterprises Inc..
   Blinder International is an umbrella company for the penny stock
empire of Meyer Blinder and includes the brokerage firm of Blinder,
Robinson &amp; Co.
   Blinder, Robinson is the target of several civil investigations
by state and federal authorities and has been named as target of a
federal grand jury in Las Vegas, Nev., investigating alleged money
laundering.
   The company's troubles with the Securities and Exchange
Commission date to 1980, and include a massive probe initiated by
the SEC in April 1987 into allegations that it defrauded customers.
   The SEC has been investigating allegations dating to 1983 that
Blinder, Robinson violated federal laws governing the sale of penny
stocks, low-priced securities sold over the counter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
