<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   06-19 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher on Monday as a steady
performance by the British currency helped the market shrug off the
slump in support for the governing Conservative Party revealed in
the European election results.
   But trading remained quiet through the day, with a handful of the
leading stocks accounting for much of the day's trading volume.
   The Conservative Party's share of the vote slumped in the
European Parliament elections, but market analysts said the election
reverse was widely forecast and didn't necessarily indicate voting
trends for the next general election, due to be held at some point
before mid-1992.
   The pound's resilience eased fears that a poor election result
would contribute to another slide in the currency and pressure the
government to raise interest rates again, said Jeffrey Thompson, an
equity analyst at the brokerage firm Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 10.8
points, or 0.5 percent, higher at 2,154.7. Volume came to 360.3
million shares, down from 513.8 million shares on Friday.
</TEXT>
