<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1458EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-WorldBank-China     06-19 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Bank-China,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Decision on Loans Must Be Made by End of Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major governments that run the World Bank, led
by the United States, must decide by the end of the month whether to
approve $700 million in easy loans they have been planning to give
China.
   The World Bank's plan calls for $2 billion in loans to China this
year, but with less than two weeks remaining before the fiscal year
ends June 30, $700 million of the total has not yet been approved by
the 22 members of its board of executive directors.
   They represent the 151 member governments. The U.S. member has
the largest voting power, more than 18 percent.
   At the bank's headquarters in Washington, the last weeks of June
see a rush of board action on loans to meet the schedule for the
current fiscal year. Spokesman Pastor Sison said it would be hard to
shift the $700 million planned for China to other borrowers.
   ``Loans take a certain amount of preparation,'' he said.
   China was due to be the bank's third biggest borrower this year,
after India and Mexico. The bank, the largest source of aid to Third
World countries, is planning to lend a total of $20 billion to $21
billion.
   On June 4, Chinese troops cleared demonstrators from the
Tiananmen Square area in central Beijing. Unofficial reports say as
many as 3,000 people were killed; the Chinese governnment says 200
to 300, most of them soldiers.
   The bank immediately pulled out all but one of its eight
permanent staffers in the Chinese capital.
   The international staff in Washington _ headed by President
Barber Conable, an American _ decided the following Thursday not to
submit to the board a proposed long-term loan of $60 million to help
farming in China's Jiangxi province. Such loans carry interest at
less than 1 percent a year.
   Sison said the Chinese government immediately promised the bank
that its obligations would continue to be fulfilled on schedule.
Zhang Junyi, a Chinese, is one of the 22 board members, stationed in
Washington. Edwin Lim _ a Filipino who heads the bank's mission in
Beijing _ has returned to his post, Sison said. Two bank officials
from Washington have joined him for talks there.
   Sison said that on June 13, the bank staff decided to hold back
two more loans from the board: one for $180 million to improve
China's electricity supply, and one for $50 million to help
technical schools.
   Attila Karaosmanoglu, the bank's vice president for Asia, told
reporters Wednesday that talks were on in Beijing about resuming
consideration of the loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
