<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-19 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Closes Limit Up On Weather, Loan Extension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most corn futures prices closed up the permitted
daily limit of 10 cents a bushel Monday on the Chicago Board of
Trade on forecasts for a week of hot, dry weather in the Midwest.
   Soybean and oat futures also rose sharply while wheat futures
finished with modest gains.
   Despite more than a month of cool, rainy weather in the Corn
Belt, soil conditions remain dry in the region's western half.
   ``Iowa still has a very substantial subsoil moisture problem,''
said Katharina Zimmer, a grain-market analyst with Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets Inc. ``If you shut off the rain, you're going to
have a major problem.''
   The corn market received additional support from the Agriculture
Department's decision to extend the due date on loans covering 700
million bushels of corn, keeping at least some of that grain off the
market for another six months.
   Gains in the wheat market were limited by selling linked to the
advancing winter wheat harvest.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.96{ a bushel; corn was 8} cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.72{ a bushel; oats were 6} cents
to 7 cents higher with July at $1.71\ a bushel; soybeans were 14
cents to 18 cents higher with July at $7.48 a bushel.
