<DOCNO> AP890619-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-China-Business     06-19 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Business,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business As Usual For Some Companies In China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some U.S. businesses are slowly resuming their
operations in China, although most are holding off as they monitor
the country's shifting political climate following the government's
bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   ``There are some Americans back,'' Martin Weil, a spokesman for
the Washington-based United States-China Business Council, said
Monday.
   ``Companies that already have investments there or urgent
business reasons to get their people there quickly _ logically
you'll expect to see them back in Beijing before others.
   ``But I think right now most companies are still in a
wait-and-see mode.''
   Hundreds of joint ventures worth billions of dollars were put on
hold or severely curtailed after Chinese troops quashed a
pro-democracy uprising, killing hundreds of its citizens, earlier
this month. Many companies evacuated their employees en masse,
particularly in Beijing.
   China's tourist trade, which earned more than $2 billion in
foreign currency annually for the Chinese, also was severely
damaged, and the outlook remains uncertain.
   A number of U.S.-based companies said most of their employees
were back to work in China and many of their operations have resumed
amid increasing signs of stability.
   ``We have told them (employees in Beijing) they can go back,''
said an official for Los Angeles-based Occidental Petroleum Corp.,
who asked that he not be identified.
   He said work also was ``continuing in its normal course'' in an
open-pit mine about 230 miles southwest of the Chinese capital.
   Meanwhile, most of the 40 expatriates who had nearly finished
erecting Shanghai's tallest building _ a $175 million 50-story
business complex _ planned to head back to work by midweek, said
A.J. Robinson, executive vice president of Portman Overseas of
Atlanta, which is overseeing the project.
   ``Those of us who are committed to China business over the long
term think whatever has happened is a temporary aberration,''
Robinson said. ``We're in this for the long haul: the next 25
years.''
   Virginia Kamsky, a New York consultant who assists companies
doing business in China, said the Chinese ``have been bending over
backwards to be more flexible than ever'' since the latest wave of
repression began.
   ``Payment under Bank of China letters of credit has been coming
in faster than ever,'' she said. ``Usually it takes U.S. exporters
11 to 14 days to get paid. But now the Chinese have cut out a step,
and payment is coming through in only five to six days.''
   Not everyone, however, was ready to continue operations in China.
   ``We're watching the situation in China on a day-by-day basis,''
said Donald N. Hanson, a spokesman for Long Beach, Calif.-based
McDonnell Douglas Corp., which recently evacuated its 50 Chinese
employees.
   ``Most of our people are in Hong Kong and trying to do work from
there in terms of getting all of the planning done and the
preparations made so that when they do get back they can pick up
where they left off.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
