<FIRST>u f AM-US-China     06-19 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Urges Americans to Continue Avoiding China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Tourism, Bjt. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said Monday that
Americans should continue avoiding China even if the turmoil there
appears to have temporarily subsided.
   At the same time, administration officials rejected a suggestion
by House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., that President Bush
intensify his condemnation of the Beijing government in view of the
recent death sentences for student dissidents.
   ``I think we've said everything we have to say on China. The
president's quite clear on that,'' deputy press secretary Roman
Popadiuk told a White House briefing.
   Overall, the Bush administration maintained its reserve about
developments in China.
   ``The president is quite anxious we not do anything that would
hurt the Chinese people,'' Secretary of State James A. Baker III
said.
   ``The United States has been speaking out. We've been speaking
out quite vigorously,'' Baker said in response to reporters'
questions.
   Popadiuk disputed a report that Bush was appalled by faulty U.S.
intelligence reports on China, including an erroneous dispatch that
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping had lapsed into a coma.
   The report, in the current issue of U.S. News &amp; World Report,
said that Bush _ who headed the CIA in the Ford administration _
intended to replace CIA director William Webster by year's end.
   ``The CIA is doing a superb job,'' Popadiuk said. ``There is no
truth to the article and the president supports Director Webster.''
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said that,
despite what she called ``a pause in anti-U.S. propaganda over the
weekend,'' the situation in China remains ``far from normal.''
   ``The department's travel advisory warning Americans against
travel to China remains in effect,'' she said. ``We are not going to
lift our travel advisory.''
   Asked if she had any advice for U.S. businesses wanting to
return, Ms. Tutwiler said: ``We cannot be encouraging Americans to
go back to China when we have a State Department policy warning
advising them not to travel in China.''
   Both White House and State Department officials said that no new
sanctions were planned against the Beijing government _ beyond the
halt in military sales announced two weeks ago by Bush _ despite a
call over the weekend by Foley for a more aggressive U.S. stance.
   ``The president has spoken very succinctly on this ... how he
views this relationship, how important this relationship is between
these two countries. He has ... said he did not want to do anything
to hurt the Chinese people, that that is where we are,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said.
   Foley, interviewed Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said Bush
should be speaking out more forcefully in opposition to the harsh
Chinese crackdown on pro-democracy dissidents.
   The speaker also said the United States should break relations
immediately with China if the Chinese use violence against the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing to seize dissident Fang Lizhi, who sought refuge
there two weeks ago.
   The U.S. decision to harbor Fang and his wife Li Shuxian has
angered the Chinese leadership, which has accused the United States
of interfering in China's internal affairs.
   Fang remains in the U.S. Embassy, officials said.
   Ms. Tutwiler would not comment on whether the State Department
had urged Fang's son against a trip to Washington. ``I'm not going
to take responsiblity for somehow maybe getting someone's personal
safety in jeopardy,'' she said.
   Ms. Tutwiler also said that tough new restrictions by China on
obtaining exit visas for Chinese who wish to leave the country _ due
to take effect on Tuesday _ had produced extremely long lines at the
visa office in Shanghai.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
