<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Trump-Atlantis     06-19 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump-Atlantis,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Issues Order Restraining Trump's Bid to Buy Casino</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge issued a
restraining order Monday to temporarily block developer Donald
Trump's $63 million bid to buy the debt-ridden Elsinore Atlantis
Casino Hotel in Atlantic City, N.J.
   U.S. District Court Judge Rosemary Gambardella issued the 10-day
order after a brief hearing, ruling that ``irreparable harm and
injury'' will result if the deal is allowed to proceed without
additional hearings.
   Creditors hold a $6.5 million mortgage on three Atlantis parking
lots. They requested the order preventing New Jersey's Casino
Control Commission, a state-appointed conservator and Elsinore Shore
Associates, owners of the boardwalk property, from transferring the
property to Trump.
   The judge scheduled a hearing for June 29. She will then consider
extending the restraining order and whether or not additional bids
should be solicited for the failing property.
   Edward J. DiDonato, a Philadelphia attorney who represents the
three creditors, said after the hearing he was pleased with the
ruling.
   ``It gives us what we originally hoped for _ that is notice to
creditors and hopefully a higher and better offer,'' DiDonato said.
   Trump plans to close the casino and convert the gaming complex
into a luxury hotel.
   Arthur Sklar, an attorney representing Donald J. Trump
Acquisitions, which is handling the purchase of the Atlantis,
declined to comment on whether the restraining order would affect
the deal. He said the sale is set for closing on July 7.
   On Friday, New Jersey gaming regulators ended a month-long
struggle over the Atlantis, approving Trump's bid by a 5-0 vote. The
Casino Control Commission said it did not believe Trump was gaining
too much power in Atlantic City when it approved the purchase by the
billionaire developer.
   Trump owns two Atlantic City casinos and has a third under
construction. If he buys the Atlantis, it would give him control of
34 percent of casino hotel rooms, 31 percent of casino floor space
and revenue, and 48 percent of casino meeting and exhibition space,
according to commission statistics.
   Sklar said Elsinore, which emerged from bankruptcy reorganization
last fall, planned to formally ask Ms. Gambardella to approve the
sale of the Atlantis, which has debts estimated at $150 million.
   DiDonato, however, said his clients did not receive adequate
notice of details of the agreement with Trump, which was announced a
day after the casino's gaming license expired.
   In April, the Atlantis became the first New Jersey gaming house
to fail to get its regular license renewed since legal casino
gambling began in Atlantic City in 1978.
   The state ordered the casino to shut down last month, ruling that
the gaming hall's financial situation was too marginal to allow it
to continue operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
