<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-19 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off; Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower against most major
currencies in dull, cautious trading Monday following last week's
selloff.
   Gold prices were higher. Republic National Bank of New York said
a troy ounce of gold was bid at $366 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up $2 from
late Friday.
   Analysts said sentiment toward the dollar remained generally
bullish, but a sense of caution prevailed Monday as traders faced
the prospect of further central-bank intervention to curb the
dollar's gains.
   ``I think people are tired. Last week probably took a lot out of
people,'' said Craig Sloane, a currency analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris, Upham &amp; Co.
   Heavy central-bank dollar selling helped push the dollar sharply
lower last week, along with a report out of Japan pointing to joint
cooperation between Japan and West Germany to hold down the dollar
outside their home markets.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.45 Japanese yen to a closing 145.50 yen. It was
quoted at 144.45 yen in London, and 144.60 yen in New York, down
from 144.70 Friday.
   The British pound rose in London to $1.5485 from $1.5340 late
Friday. Sterling fetched $1.5430 in New York, up from $1.5410.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday,
included: 1.9785 West German marks, down from 1.9810; 1.7090 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7110; 1.19865 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19725;
6.7155 French francs, down from 6.7290; and 1,431.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,441.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday: 1.9735
West German marks, down from 1.9915; 1.7045 Swiss francs, down from
1.7213; 6.6940 French francs, down from 6.7620; 2.2351 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.2385; 1,439.75 Italian lire, down from
1,443.50; and 1.1991 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1973.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $367.10 a troy ounce, up from $365.10 Friday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $366.50 a troy ounce,
up from late Friday's $363.75. In Zurich, gold rose to close at a
bid of $366.25, up from $363.75 late Friday.
   All financial institutions in Hong Kong were closed Monday for
official birthday celebrations of Queen Elizabeth II.
   Silver prices gained ground. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.323 a troy ounce from $5.285 Friday.
Silver rose in London to $5.37 an ounce from Friday's $5.27.
</TEXT>
