<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TrustcorpMerger     06-19 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trustcorp Merger,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trustcorp to Merge with Society Corp. of Cleveland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trustcorp Inc., which has been rocked by bad
loans, has agreed to be bought by Society Corp. of Cleveland in a
stock-swap deal worth about $495 million, company officials
announced Monday.
   The agreement was approved Sunday night by the boards of
directors of both companies, said Robert W. Gillespie, chairman of
Society Corp.
   The deal, which still needs to be approved by Trustcorp
shareholders and the Federal Reserve Board, should be closed by the
end of the year, Gillespie said.
   ``From Society's perspective, it's the first time we've ventured
outside of the borders of Ohio. We think it's a teriffic way for us
to enter into the interstate regional banking activities,''
Gillespie said at a news conference.
   Society said the deal would expand the bank holding company into
two new markets _ Indiana and Michigan.
   Toledo-based Trustcorp, reeling from bad loans on development
projects, said the merger was in the best interest of its
shareholders.
   ``This is not a disaster,'' said Chester Devenow, Trustcorp's
interim president and chief executive officer. ``I am very pleased
with what's happened here. I feel very comfortable that it's in the
best interest of our shareholders and employees, but also for the
city of Toledo. ... We're not giving up ownership of this bank.''
   Under the agreement, holders of Trustcorp common shares will
receive three fourths of a Society common share for each share of
Trustcorp common stock. Society will pay about $30 a share for
nearly 16 million shares of Trustcorp stock.
   The combined operation will have about $16 billion in assets.
   Trustcorp shareholders will hold about 35 percent of Society's
stock after the merger and will be represented on Society's board.
   Trustcorp Bank of Ohio, a Trustcorp Inc. subsidiary, would be
absorbed into the Society system, while Trustcorp Inc. would be
dissolved. Frederick Teal, chairman of Society's bank in Columbus,
Ohio, would become the new chief executive officer of Trustcorp
Bank, Ohio.
   Society hasn't decided on a corporate name for Trustcorp,
Gillespie said.
   ``It's not our intention for Trustcorp to become a branch office
of a Cleveland company. We intend to run Trustcorp of Ohio as a
stand-alone, independent bank,'' he said.
   The decision to sell Trustcorp follows months of speculation that
the holding company would be the target of a takeover because of
financial troubles.
   Trustcorp in the last five months had to write off $76 million
because of the bad loans. The company took $52 million in write-offs
and added $24 million to its loan-loss reserves.
   A write-off is a loan that no longer is expected to be repaid and
written off as a bad debt.
   The losses were blamed on loans on real estate development
projects, particularly in downtown Toledo. Trustcorp had loaned
about $100 million to various downtown Toledo projects during the
last decade.
   Six of Trustcorp's top executives, including George Haigh, former
president, chairman and chief executive officer, resigned or were
fired in the wake of the losses.
   Gillespie said Trustcorp had several non-banking operations that
would enhance Society's business, including an insurance agency, a
travel agency and an investment advisory unit.
   Society said the merger would make it the third-largest bank
holding company in Ohio and the 40th in the nation. Society now
ranks fourth in Ohio and 54th in the nation.
   Trustcorp has assets of $5.9 billion with 170 banking outlets in
Ohio, Indiana, Michgan and Florida.
   Society has nearly $10 billion in assets with more than 200
outlets across Ohio and affiliates based in Cleveland, Canton,
Columbus and Dayton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0284 </DOCNO>
