<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market settled for a mixed showing
Monday in a subdued atmosphere following Friday's ``triple witching
hour.''
   Trading set its slowest pace in more than two months.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 6.49 to 2,479.89,
while some other prominent market indicators eked out small gains.
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advances in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 686 up, 733
down and 542 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 130.72 million
shares, down from 244.51 million Friday and the lightest total since
a 128.54 million-share day on April 17.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 155.13 million shares.
   The market held steady on Friday amid a barrage of activity by
traders completing computer-program strategies involving a group of
expiring stock index options and futures.
   Analysts noted that these quarterly witching hours are often
followed by at least a brief letdown in stock prices and trading
volume.
   In addition, brokers cited lingering uncertainty over the next
likely turn in the Federal Reserve's credit policy. The stream of
economic data that Wall Streeters watch along with the Fed runs dry
for the next couple of days.
   NWA climbed 6{ to 114[ after a delayed opening. An investor group
led by Alfred Checchi of Los Angeles announced an agreement to
acquire NWA for $121 a share, apparently ending a bidding war among
several parties.
   The action in NWA stock helped most other airline issues gain
altitude as well. UAL rose 6{ to 128{ and Delta Air Lines was up 1[
at 68[.
   Time Inc. fell 5| to 156~, while Warner Communications rose ] to
59| as the most active NYSE issue. On Friday Time began a
$70-a-share offer for Warner after Paramount Communications
disrupted plans for a Time-Warner merger with a hostile bid for Time.
   Paramount shares gained 2] to 60{.
   Sea Containers Ltd. jumped 6~ to 72{. The company, which is
fighting a $50-a-share takeover bid by the European concerns Tiphook
and Stena, said it was working on a plan for a buyout or
restructuring.
   Federal National Mortgage, which said the interest-rate spread
that helps determine its profitability continue to improve in May,
rose 4 to 88~.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $1.25 billion, or 0.04
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.20 to 179.79.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose .38 to 368.12, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up .54 at 321.89.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 1.12 to 446.09. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 362.39, up .56.
