<FIRST>u f AM-IntegratedResources     06-19 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Integrated Resources,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Concern To Restructure $955 Million in Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc., a troubled financial
services company, said Monday it plans to replace $955 million in
short-term debt with secured borrowings as part of a major corporate
overhaul.
   Integrated said it was putting up almost all of its $7.8 billion
in assets as collateral and sharply cutting back operations after it
moved last week to default on outstanding bonds and commercial paper
because of a cash shortage.
   ``They needed to establish working capital lines and it looks
like they've proposed a plan to do that,'' said Jan Konstanty,
associate director of Moody's Investors Service, which downgraded
Integrated's credit rating last week.
   Company president Arthur Goldberg said the company's problems do
not affect any of its 35 subsidiaries, which have about 750,000
investor accounts. Among its subsidiaries are Integrated Resources
Life Insurance Co. of Des Moines, Iowa, and Capitol Life Insurance
Co. of Denver.
   After meeting with creditors, the New York-based firm with
subsidiaries nationwide said holders of debt due within 45 days
would receive new, secured obligations payable in 18 months that can
be extended for six months if the company pays more than $200
million before the deadline.
   In addition, the 20-year-old firm that made its fortune in tax
shelters and then expanded into financial services said it would try
to sell some businesses in tax-sheltered annuities _ which had $160
million in sales last year _ direct life insurance and other
segments.
   It also said it plans to reduce operating expenses by $40 million
a year by slashing expenses, overhead and other unspecified budget
items. Integrated spokesman David Caouette declined to say whether
the plan involved layoffs.
   The company, which has $1.1 billion in capital, said in a
statement it would concentrate on its core businesses of money
management and mutual funds, variable insurance products and limited
partnerships.
   ``The steps we are proposing ... will help to provide Integrated
Resources with the financial strength and management focus to
continue its role as a major player in the financial services
industry,'' Goldberg said.
   Integrated said it would submit the proposal, drafted over the
weekend in meetings with its major commercial banks, to short-term
lenders and commercial paper holders.
   The company's stock, which sold for as much as $40 a share in
1986, dropped 37{ cents Monday to $6 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange. Shares have plunged from $15 in the last week.
   Last Wednesday, banks withdrew Integrated's access to short-term
credit markets amid signs of weakening financial conditions at the
firm.
   Integrated said it did not have the money to pay off its debt,
including some $373 million in commercial paper and loan shares due
within 45 days. The debt payments amount to about $8 million a day.
   Integrated also has $491 million in short-term bank credit lines,
mostly payable on demand.
   The debt to be restructured includes outstanding short-term bank
debt, domestic and European commercial paper and notes outstanding
under loan-sale programs, the company said.
   About 50 banks are providing short-term loans to Integrated and
the company said it has about 50 to 75 holders of commercial paper
and notes under loan-sale programs.
   Integrated said it would pledge ``substantially all'' of its
assets and non-operating subsidiaries as collateral. Secured notes
oustanding would be prepaid from some of Integrated's planned asset
sales.
   Goldberg said the company's problems do not affect any of its 35
subsidiaries, which have about 750,000 investor accounts. Among its
subsidiaries are Integrated Resources Life Insurance Co. of Des
Moines, Iowa, and Capitol Life Insurance Co. of Denver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
