<FIRST>r f BC-WPP-Ogilvy     06-19 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WPP-Ogilvy,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>WPP Group Says 95 Percent of Ogilvy Shares Tendered by Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   WPP Group PLC said Monday that more than 95
percent of Ogilvy Group's shares were validly tendered under terms
of its $54-a-share buyout offer and that it intends to move quickly
to complete the largest acquisition ever in the advertising business.
   The deal would make London-based WPP second only to Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi PLC, also based in London, among the world's largest
advertising and marketing services concerns.
   WPP already owns the J. Walter Thompson ad agency, the Hill &amp;
Knowlton public relations firm and about three dozen marketing
services firms.
   The WPP and Ogilvy boards agreed on the buyout last month and
WPP's $54-a-share tender offer expired at 10 a.m. Monday.
   WPP said that its depositary for the offer, Citibank, said that
as of 6 a.m. Monday 13.8 million shares, or 95.2 percent, of
Ogilvy's 14.5 million shares were validly tendered and not withdrawn
as of that point.
   In addition, WPP beneficially owns an additional 585,000 Ogilvy
shares.
   The stock purchase would cost WPP about $783 million. The company
had previously said it valued the deal at $864 million, including
purchases of options, refinancing debt and other expenses.
   In either case, the purchase clearly exceeds the previous largest
in the ad business _ WPP's $566 million takeover of J. Walter
Thompson's parent in 1987.
   WPP said it intends to complete the merger of Ogilvy with one of
its subsidiaries as soon as practicable. In the merger, Ogilvy
shares that have not been tendered will be converted into the right
to receive $54 a share in cash.
</TEXT>
