<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-19 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices finished mostly higher
Monday led by a surge in the July crude oil contract.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of crude oil, finished 91 cents higher at $20.86
cents a barrel. The July contract had traded as low as $19.67 a
barrel, below Friday's $19.95 close.
   Analysts said investors were concerned about the direction of
crude prices before the last day of trading in July crude oil on
Tuesday.
   ``The expiration of the July contract produces some nervousness;
that brings in short-covering,'' said Richard Redoglio, energy
broker with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Crude contracts for delivery after July showed more modest gains.
The August crude oil contract rose 38 cents to $18.96 a barrel and
September gained 18 cents to $17.99.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for July delivery rose
0.86 cent to settle at 59 cents a gallon. Other unleaded gasoline
contracts were mixed.
   Heating oil for delivery in July rose 0.35 cent to 46.06 cents a
gallon on low volume. Contracts for delivery later in the year also
rose.
   An attack on a major Colombian oil pipeline helped boost prices
slightly early in the day, but the effect was short-lived, observers
said.
   ``It had some psychological impact but since it's a sour crude,
it's hard to say how much of an impact it really had,'' said Randall
Rothenberg, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Analysts said that Colombia's state oil company, Ecopetrol, was
informing U.S. customers that deliveries would be disrupted for
several days while damage to the pipeline is repaired.
</TEXT>
