<HEAD>Power Producer Wins Deadline Extension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTROSE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado-Ute Electric Association has won
a three-week extension of a deadline for responding to an
involuntary Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing, a company spokesman said
Monday.
   John McNeill, general counsel for the Montrose-based
Colorado-Ute, said the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Denver extended the
company's June 26 response deadline to July 17.
   Three commercial banks _ Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co., United
Bank of Denver and Norwest Bank Minneapolis _ each owed $10 million
by Colorado-Ute, filed the involuntary petition on June 5.
   The filing did not affect electric service to Colorado-Ute's
14-member rural electric cooperatives, which in turn, supply power
to 49 of the state's 63 counties.
   Colorado-Ute is $1.1 billion in debt and claims $887 million in
assets. It is trying to reach an agreement with its creditors to
avoid Chapter 11 proceedings.
   The U.S. Rural Electrification Administration, the largest
creditor owed more than $410 million, is trying to negotiate a
standstill agreement with Colorado-Ute.
   REA officials said a six-month standstill would be used to sell
all or part of Colorado-Ute, or merge the company with another
generation and transmission concern.
