<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EEC-Stocks     06-19 0119</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-Stocks,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Ministers Adopt Ban On Insider Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   EEC ministers Monday agreed to ban insider
trading on European stock exchanges over the next three years.
   The decision will require some of the 12 countries in the
European Economic Community, including Germany, Italy, Belgium and
Ireland, to tighten their rules regarding trading on insider
information.
   Insider trading is defined by the EEC as the use of privileged
information for personal gain. Privileged information is information
that has not been revealed to the public and could influence the
price of a stock if it were.
   Under the proposal, all EEC countries must enact measures
``sufficiently strong'' to prevent insider trading no later than
June 1, 1992.
</TEXT>
