<FIRST>u f AM-Sematech     06-19 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sematech,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sematech Opens Preliminary Discussions With European Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sematech said Monday it has held preliminary talks
with European manufacturers on cooperation in research on
semiconductor manufacturing technology.
   ``Representatives of European integrated circuit companies
visited Sematech to discuss opportunities for cooperation between
Sematech and JESSI (Joint European Submicron Silicon),'' the U.S.
consortium said Monday in a prepared statement.
   ``It was agreed that any potential cooperation must be based on
reciprocity. It was also agreed that such cooperation is highly
desirable.
   ``A study group was set up to further define the areas where
common activities can substantially help in reaching mutual goals,''
the statement said.
   The meeting at Sematech's Austin headquarters occurred last
Friday and involved representatives of NV Philips, a Dutch company;
Siemens AG, West Germany and SGS-Thomson Microelectronics BV,
according to Sematech spokesman Miller Bonner.
   However Bonner noted that the three, while they account for the
bulk of the European industry, do not represent JESSI, which is
still in the formative stages.
   Bonner said the meeting grew out of contacts with potential JESSI
members who were seeking help in setting up a Sematech-like effort
to battle the Japanese for the $45 billion semiconductor industry.
   Sematech, an acronym for Semiconductor Manufacturing Technology,
was created last year with a goal of U.S. global leadership in the
semiconductor manufacturing technology by 1993.
   Although the Europeans in some ways are competing with the United
States for that leadership, Bonner said Sematech's focus on
manufacturing technology and not on the end-use of computer chips
means cooperation would not be inconsistent with Sematech's goal.
   ``If our goal is to retain world leadership in the semiconductor
manufacturing, clearly we have to take a very broad view of the best
way to accomplish this,'' Bonner said.
   But Bonner disputed a report in this week's issue of Business
Week magazine that the talks would lead to joint membership in both
consortia for the 14 U.S. companies and their European counterparts.
   ``That's a giant leap from what we talked about here on Friday,''
Bonner said. ``We're a long way from talking about joint membership.
There's one thing to discuss standards. It's quite another to talk
about joint membership.''
   Sematech's members include International Business Machines Corp.,
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., NCR Corp., Texas Instruments
Inc., Digital Equipment Inc., Motorola Inc., Hewlett-Packard Co.,
and Intel Corp. The members fund half of Sematech's $200 million
annual budget with the Pentagon contributing the remainder.
</TEXT>
