<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Economy     06-19 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Economy,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Renewal Of Wage-Price Pact Expected To Bolster Mexico In Debt
Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is hoping early renewal of an
inflation-fighting pact will ease anxiety over prolonged foreign
debt negotiations and bolster its position in the talks.
   The latest extension of the pact, announced late Sunday, makes no
major changes in the one that expires July 31.
   Prices will be held at current levels and the one-peso-a-day
devaluation of the country's currency against the U.S. dollar will
be maintained, the pact says. It mentions no new minimum wage
increase.
   An agreement between the government and foreign commercial banks
on their share of the country's $107.4 billion foreign debt had been
expected before the renewal was announced. Analysts say investors
had become nervous over what both might contain, prompting the
government to keep domestic interest rates high to keep capital in
the country.
   ``The renewed pact strengthens Mexico's negotiating position'' on
foreign debt, Salinas said in a televised speech after the signing.
   Negotiations between representatives of the government and the
more than 500 foreign commercial creditor banks are under way in New
York. Private banks hold about 70 percent of the foreign debt.
   Unity among labor, private enterprise, the farm sector and the
government in bringing down inflation through the series of pacts
has won recognition from foreign governments and multilateral
lending agencies, Salinas said, and ``now opens a new space for us
to not accept under pressure just any arrangement, but on the
contrary to reach an adequate agreement.''
   Inflation was running at a record annual rate of 159 percent when
the first pact was signed in December 1987. The rate was 8 percent
for the first five months of this year and 18.5 percent for the 12
months ending in May. Reducing inflation further and gradually
renewing economic growth, stagnant from 1982 to 1988, remain the
pact's priorities, Salinas said.
   The International Monetary Fund and World Bank have granted
Mexico new loans totaling about $5.8 billion.
   Manuel Sanchez, director of the Center for Economic Research and
Analysis, a private think tank, said in an interview that short-term
anxiety will ease if investors see that the government is
negotiating a solid, long-term agreement on the debt. Continuing
structural changes, such as reducing its role in the economy and
holding down its own spending also will boost investor confidence,
he said.
   Salinas, who took office last Dec. 1, wants an agreement that
will cover the rest of his six-year term.
   Government officials have indicated they are holding out for a 55
percent reduction in principal on the loans held by private banks.
The banks are reported to have offered a 22 percent reduction on at
least part of the debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
