<FIRST>u f AM-SteelTalks     06-19 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Talks,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Members Reject National Steel Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Steelworkers members rejected a 50-month
contract offer from National Steel Corp. that was patterned after an
agreement ratified at Bethlehem Steel Corp., union officials said
Monday.
   Union negotiator Buddy Davis said the nearly 7,000 members at
National's plants in Ecorse, Mich., Portage Ind., and Granite City,
Ill., apparently believed they could get better terms from the
nation's sixth-largest steelmaker.
   ``One of the problems with these early negotiations is that
people get to thinking, `Well, we don't have anything to lose so
let's send them back to get us some more.' Well, there isn't any
more. At least that's what I've been telling them,'' Davis said.
   Before the ballot had been finished at a Pittsburgh hotel, Davis
said, ``If it goes down, I'd say they're in trouble.''
   The vote was 3,239 to 2,054 to reject the restoration of previous
concessions and raise wages by $1.50 an hour over the life of the
contract. Like three other major producers, National faced a July 31
contract expiration.
   ``If the union members at our divisions voted against the
agreement because they believe National can afford to give more,
they're wrong,'' said Dick Coffee, chief negotiator for
Pittsburgh-based National.
   National is already one of the less profitable producers among
the major companies.
   The two sides opened negotiations early, and presumably will
return to bargaining after a cooling off period.
   Second-ranked Bethlehem won ratification of terms similar to
National's offer.
   Meanwhile, the union continues negotiations with Inland Steel
Industries Inc., although the Chicago company has been taking a
tough line, and union officials have been telling workers that
strike preparations have begun.
   Inland claims it is offering terms at least as good as
Bethlehem's. The union claims its workers deserve better from a
financially healthy company.
   The two sides bargained over the weekend and through the night
until 5 a.m. Monday in Chicago. The negotiators then recessed to
rest.
   Talks with Armco Inc. were scheduled to resume Tuesday but have
been postponed until after July 4 because of a shortage of hotel
rooms in Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
