<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Wendy'sSuit     06-19 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wendy's Suit,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wendy's Sues Over Franchise Breach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wendy's International Inc., the world's
third-largest hamburger restaurant chain, is suing the parent
company of Carl's Jr. restaurants and a Wendy's franchisee for $119
million over Carl's Jr.'s purchase of 10 Wendy's outlets in Arizona.
   The suit, filed Monday in U.S. District Court in Tucson, alleges
that Carl Karcher Enterprises breached ``contractual terms that are
the cornerstone of any franchise system'' when it bought the
Wendy's-franchised restaurants.
   The Dublin, Ohio-based plaintiff seeks $79 million in
compensatory, consequential and punitive damages and attorney's fees
from Carl Karcher Enterprises and $40 million from Ronald Brown, who
owns Wendy's of Tucson Inc.
   Brown sold individual Wendy's stores in Prescott and Flagstaff,
and eight in Tucson, to Carl Karcher Enterprises.
   The complaint claims that the purchase has deprived Wendy's of
current and future income from the 10 stores, pirated prime
locations and destroyed Wendy's market presence.
   The suit alleges that Wendy's had notified both Karcher
Enterprises and Brown that it would not consent to sale.
   Brown was out of town and could not be reached for comment, an
employee said.
   Carl's Jr. attorney Richard Ceilio said in a statement read over
the telephone from Anaheim, Calif., that he had not seen the
complaint but that based on Wendy's announcement his company
believed the suit was totally without merit.
   Carl's Jr. has 498 restaurants nationwide, while Wendy's operates
or franchises nearly 3,800 restaurants in the United States and
overseas.
</TEXT>
