<FIRST>u f AM-UAWConvention 1stLd-Writethru f0288 06-19 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0288,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Convention Gets Down to Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Gephardt comments; Picks up
3rd graf pvs, `The convention's ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected House Majority Leader
Richard Gephardt on Monday ticked off a campaign-style list of
things wrong with the United States and asked the United Auto
Workers union to help him set things straight.
   Gephardt, making his first major speech since taking the House
Democratic leadership position two weeks ago, told delegates to a
UAW convention that the Bush administration has ``made some good
sounds on trade.''
   ``It remains to be seen if they are tough,'' he added. ``If not,
we're going to have the Gephardt amendment or something like it.''
   The congressman from Missouri based a large part of his
unsuccessful presidential campaign last year on trade issues. The
legislation he proposed in Congress would have forced the president
to take action against countries that traded unfairly with the
United States.
   ``You cannot compete against unfair competition,'' he said to
applause from a crowd of about 2,000 UAW members.
   In an address sounding much like a political stump speech,
Gephardt criticized the Bush administration, saying the nation
needed a comprehensive energy policy and to divert spending from
military hardware to education and the fight against drugs.
   ``This is our time ... to make America great and good and strong
again,'' he said.
   Earlier Monday, a UAW dissident movement was dealt its second
blow in two days when convention delegates rejected efforts which
would have required direct election of national union officers.
   The ``one-man, one-vote'' issue came up in 30 resolutions
submitted to the convention. They were lumped together and turned
down in a show-of-hands vote.
   The convention's constitution committee recommended rejection of
the move to referendum voting for national officers.
   ``A referendum is only the outer shell of democracy,'' Jim McNeil
of Local 600 in Dearborn, Mich., said in reading the committee's
report.
   ``The convention system delivers the substance,'' he said.
   The UAW membership elects its officers through delegates to the
convention every three years. This year's elections are scheduled
for Wednesday, and President Owen Bieber is facing no oppositon.
   The New Directions dissident movement, led by Jerry Tucker of St.
Louis, has complained among other things that the union has lost its
democratic roots.
   Dan Mallett, a delegate from Local 31 in Fairfax, Kan., said a
referendum method would make the union's leadership more accountable
to the membership.
   ``They pay their union dues, they deserve the right to vote,'' he
said.
   But his arguments and those of others failed to persuade enough
delegates to pass the resolution.
   It was the second defeat for Tucker and his forces in as many
days. On Sunday, the convention's opening day, New Directions
backers lost a battle over seating some delegations. At that time,
Tucker said there would be other challenges from his camp during the
week-long convention.
   Before the debate on the referendum issue, former Rep. Barbara
Jordan of Texas praised the union and its leadership. Her remarks
were framed in references to recent events in China in which a
pro-democracy student demonstration was put down forcefully.
   ``You in the United Auto Workers have a responsibility to explain
democracy of the rest of the world,'' she said, ``because you are a
microcosm of democracy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
