<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AmericanAirlines-Computers     06-19 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-American Airlines-Computers,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Announces Contract For 50,000 Computer Terminals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines Inc. announced Monday it had
chosen three vendors _ AT&amp;T, IBM and Tandy Corp. _ to supply as many
as 50,000 workstation computers for its reservation and travel agent
systems.
   The models are based on the Intel 386 microprocessor chip and
will be installed over the next two years.
   Terms of the contract were not disclosed.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. said its portion of the
contract was the largest-ever it has received for workstations. The
company declined to give the value of its contract or the number of
units.
   The workstations will be installed in American Airlines domestic
reservations centers and in travel agencies that use the American's
SABRE Travel Information Network, American said.
   The SABRE system allows travel agents to book airline, hotel, car
and other travel-related reservations from workstations located in
their offices.
   American said it anticipates purchasing more than 50,000
workstations based on Intel's 386 microprocessor. The new chip
permits faster processing and greater memory capacity than the model
286 chip now in use.
   The workstations, which will be installed over the next two
years, will be interchangeable, the airline said.
   AT&amp;T's workstations are expected to be used primarily by SABRE
customers. Those from International Business Machines Corp. are
planned for use in American domestic reservations offices and for
SABRE customers, and Tandy's workstations are geared for domestic
airport terminals and certain maintenance locations.
   Allocation wasn't announced, but American said any one vendor's
share would be at least 10 percent.
</TEXT>
