<FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest 5thLd-Writethru f0321 06-19 0900</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest, 5th Ld-Writethru, f0321,0927</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Announces Merger Agreement With Checchi Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `Checchi, 40 ...,' to CORRECT his age to 41.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MP2, NY34</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' parent, NWA Inc., accepted
a $4 billion buyout offer Monday from a group led by Los Angeles
investor Alfred Checchi, capping a weeks-long bidding war and taking
further steps to keep other bidders from returning.
   The Checchi group, which agreed to pay $121 a share for the
parent of the nation's fourth-largest airline, said it planned to
retain current management and believed it could win needed federal
approval of the sale.
   NWA announced that if its deal fell through with the Checchi
group _ which included KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and the Australian
conglomerate Elders IXL _ it would undertake a recapitalization that
would pay NWA shareholders a special $70 a share cash dividend.
   Analysts said such a recapitalization _ which would load NWA up
with new debt and possibly place a big stock holding into friendly
hands _ would make the company much less attractive to hostile
suitors.
   NWA stock soared $6.50 a share to $114.12{ on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   The Checchi group, Wings Holdings Inc., beat at least three other
bidders: rival airline Pan Am Corp.; the International Association
of Machinists, which represents about 20,000 of Northwest's 37,000
workers; and oil billionaire Marvin Davis, who sparked the bidding
with a $90 a share offer on March 28.
   Davis, who owns 2.9 percent of NWA's common shares, said in a
statement that he supports the proposed transaction, but will
reserve final judgement until he meets with his advisers.
   ``While disappointed by the outcome, I am pleased that the NWA
special committee has elected to sell the company as we urged all
along,'' Davis said.
   Pan Am issued a statement saying it was disappointed its bid was
not chosen, but that it wanted its offer to be considered if the
Checchi bid fell through _ and before NWA undertook its
recapitalization plan.
   The Machinists' union did not return repeated phone calls seeking
comment.
   Checchi, 41, a former Marriott Corp. treasurer, said he signed an
agreement with the NWA board about 1 a.m. Monday in a New York City
law office.
   Northwest said the Checchi bid was the highest offer it received,
had the fewest contingencies and was the most likely to close.
   Checchi said none of his associates would join Northwest's
management team and he expected NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier to
keep running the company.
   ``I talked to Steve last night and we mutually congratulated each
other,'' Checchi said Monday. ``I certainly hope he plans on
staying. I have no reason to believe he is not.''
   Checchi's proposal includes $700 million equity and $3.35 billion
to be borrowed from a syndicate of banks led by Bankers Trust Co.
Checchi's equity partners include KLM, Bankers Trust; Richard C.
Blum and Associates, a San Francisco merchant banking and investment
firm; and Elders Finance Group, a subsidiary of Elders IXL.
   With about 30.5 million common shares outstanding, the tender
offer would cost about $3.7 billion, but Checchi's group already
owns 4.9 percent of NWA stock. The buyers also are contributing
equity that boosts the total package to over $4 billion.
   The buyout was conditioned on a majority of NWA's shares being
purchased and the deal being completed by Sept. 18.
   Checchi said he was not concerned about meeting financial fitness
requirements of the U.S. Transportation Department, which must
approve the acquisition.
   The Justice Department is not likely to review the deal because
it does not involve a merger of two airlines, a department spokesman
said.
   Federal regulations prohibit foreign carriers such as KLM from
owning more than 25 percent of a U.S. carrier.
   However, KLM and Northwest could share gates and coordinate
schedules for connecting flights, said Barbara Beyer of Avmark Inc.,
an aviation consulting firm in Arlington, Va. Such an arrangement
would not require any merger of employees or corporate staff, she
said.
   Checchi said his plan calls for ``substantial growth'' at
Northwest, including the purchase of 138 new planes already on order
or option by NWA.
   William Genoese, president of the airline division of the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, said he would meet with
Checchi's group later this week.
   ``They want the company to grow,'' said Genoese, whose union
represents about 7,000 flight attendants and clerks at Northwest.
``I'm for anyone that comes in that will make things grow and
improve labor relations.''
   NWA said its recapitalization plan would pay shareholders $70
cash per share, which would cost about $2.1 billion. The plan might
be financed partly with an equity contribution from a third party,
NWA said, which would determine how much the company would have to
borrow to pay for the recapitalization.
   Kurt Rivard, an analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. of Minneapolis,
said new debt the recapitalization would load on NWA could
discourage a hostile bidder from trying to circumvent the Checchi
deal.
   Monday's decision capped a bidding war opened March 28 by Davis,
who offered $2.7 billion, or $90 a share.
   The board rejected Davis' bid and his subsequent tender offer for
the same amount. It then opened a two-phase bidding process that
attracted other suitors such as Pan Am.
   However, NWA's board rejected the first round of bids as
inadequate and invited suitors to try again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
